<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Rejected by Elian Kin  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX VEIGA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno took an
extraordinary step to resolve the Elian Gonzalez case Wednesday but
failed to persuade his relatives to end the wrenching 4{-month
custody struggle.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Reno for 2{ hours, the boy's great-uncle
Lazaro Gonzalez was defiant and said they won't turn over the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The moment has come for the final decision and I want you all
to know and for the whole world to see that they are preparing to
storm a family home,'' Gonzalez said. ''Our position is that we
will not turn the child over. We will not turn the child over at
Opa-locka or any 'locka.'''
</P>
<P>
   Opa-locka was a reference to the government's suggestion that
Elian be handed over at the airport in the city outside Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Reno met with Lazaro Gonzalez, the boy's cousin Marisleysis and
other relatives at the Miami Beach home of Sister Jeanne
O'Laughlin, the nun who was host of a January meeting between Elian
and his grandmothers from Cuba. Elian attended the meeting, moving
from lap to lap at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Diaz, an attorney for the family, said Reno and
Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris Meissner
heard ample evidence during the meeting that Elian does not want to
go back to Cuba but refused to take that into account.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Meissner called a midnight news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''She wants to do anything possible to resolve this,'' Justice
Department spokesman Myron Marlin said before the meeting. ''She
realizes it's a tall order but believes she may be the one who can
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said that in the meeting, no deadline was issued and
no letter was delivered detailing handover plans. However, she said
there was talk of a meeting Thursday in Washington involving the
Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was very respectful and they were very honest,''
O'Laughlin said. ''The pain of this family and their understanding
of the pain of Juan Miguel was very evident. They have expressed
over and over again their ... desire to be a loving family, whole
again.''
</P>
<P>
   One option Reno had planned to propose was for Elian and some of
his Miami relatives to come back to Washington, perhaps even on her
plane, to arrange a meeting with the boy's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, and the eventual transfer of custody, according to a
government official, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Elian left the meeting only when the subject matter with Reno
was too sensitive. ''He was precious with her,'' O'Laughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his relatives had left their politically charged
Little Havana neighborhood for O'Laughlin's gated home earlier in
the day. She said Elian would stay there Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
