<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 56 Die As Philippine Boat Capsizes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- An overloaded wooden Philippine
ferry boat headed for Malaysia capsized, killing at least 56
people, officials said Thursday. More than 100 others were missing
and feared dead.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen people had been rescued as of Thursday morning, said
Abdusakur Tan, governor of southern Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers were crowded on one side of the boat Arlahada,
causing it to tip and then capsize shortly after leaving Jolo, the
provincial capital, on Wednesday night, Tan said.
</P>
<P>
   The boat was only authorized to carry cargo, not passengers,
said Coast guard district commander Capt. Heliberto Pascual. It had
only nine crew members and 11 cargo agents on board when it
departed Jolo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ship then picked up scores of passengers at sea from small
boats, he said. They apparently boarded from the same side, causing
the ship to tilt.
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers were trapped inside the ship's cabin after it
capsized, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are still searching for the more than 100 passengers who
are still missing,'' Tan said. ''We don't know if they are alive or
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 fishermen in the area were helping in the search.
There were no immediate reports of whether foreigners were on
board.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry was headed for the Philippine province of Tawi-Tawi
and then for Saba in Malaysia, he said. Jolo is at the southern tip
of the Philippines and is close to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Ferries are the main form of transportation among the
Philippines' more than 7,000 islands, but overcrowding and
accidents are common. In the world's worst peacetime shipping
disaster, the Dona Paz ferry collided with a tanker on Dec. 20,
1987, killing 4,341.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
