<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increase in payments for doctors seeing Medicaid patients favored  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State legislators negotiating the new
2000-01 state budget have reached an agreement to give physicians a
financial incentive to see Medicaid-covered patients.
</P>
<P>
   The current $7-per-visit fee paid to primary care providers
would go up to $30 a visit under a recommendation made Wednesday by
a legislative conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative conference committees are working to conclude
outstanding issues in the budget for the state fiscal year which
began April 1. Legislative leaders say they hope to have their
chambers adopt a new $78 billion spending plan by next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state Medical Society and other medical groups have long
complained that their members have lost all incentive to see
Medicaid patients because of low reimbursement rates by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being welcome in private doctors' office, many
Medicaid patients have been forced to seek treatment at hospital
emergency rooms or clinics. The health committee chairmen in the
Senate and Assembly, Sen. Kemp Hannon and Assemblyman Richard
Gottfried respectively, said it can cost $100 or more per Medicaid
patient visit to a clinic or emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing reimbursement rates for physicians will not cost the
state any more money because there will be corresponding savings
through fewer Medicaid recipients seeking care at more expensive
medical facilities, Hannon and Gottfried said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators said they have also agreed to a $2 million
allocation to increase the reimbursement rates for health
specialists treating Medicaid recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders said
they will spend $250 million on new clean-fuel buses and
retrofitting existing diesel buses servicing the New York City
area.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Fuel Bus program would provide for the purchase of 550
new clean-fuel buses for use by the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority and require all existing diesel buses be converted to
conform with ''clean'' technology.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is part of a revised MTA Capital Plan agreed to
by Pataki, state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno and state
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver.
</P>
<P>
   ''This historic plan will ensure that the MTA has the cleanest
bus fleet, not only in the nation, but in the world,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 550 clean-fuel buses that will be purchased, 300 will be
fueled by compressed natural gas (CNG) and 250 will run on
hybrid-electric power. MTA currently owns 350 CNG-fueled and 140
hybrid-electric buses.
</P>
<P>
   Older diesel buses will be retrofitted to include continuously
regenerative traps -- a device that captures and burns pollutants
before emission -- and to use ultra-low sulfur fuel. The plan calls
for the entire MTA bus fleet to be retrofitted within three years.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA currently has 4,300 buses in service.
</P>
<P>
   MTA also promised to phase out its two-stroke diesel buses,
which have higher emissions, by December 31, 2003. It also agreed
to work with the state Department of Environmental Conservation to
develop new emissions performance standards for MTA buses.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other budget matters under discussion Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   --Hannon and Gottfried said they were close to an agreement to
extend the Medicaid managed care program, set to expire in June, to
the end of 2003. Changes will be made to increase participation and
quality of care, the lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   --Whether to include $7.9 million in the budget for AIDS-related
spending through the state's AIDS Institute.
</P>
<P>
   --The governor's proposal to spend $75 million on a new secure
juvenile detention facility to replace the Harlem Valley Secure
Center. A proposal from Pataki calls for a new facility for violent
youths to be built near the Greenhaven state prison about 50 miles
north of New York City. The conference committee discussing social
services issues said it could not agree on Pataki's proposal, with
senators in favor and Assembly members opposed.
</P>
<P>
   --Whether to include $15 million in the 2000-01 budget to support
construction of a new 22,000-seat stadium in Rochester for the
Rhinos professional soccer team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
