<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget likely to include increase in crime victims' funding  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The yet-to-be-finalized state budget could
cost convicted criminals $2.9 million in fees that would go toward
helping their victims recover, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be raised by increasing the two fees offenders
in New York are mandated to pay upon their convictions, said Joseph
Conway, a spokesman for the state's Budget Division.
</P>
<P>
   The state's main assessments on convictions, currently $25 to
$150 depending on the severity of the crime, would rise to between
$30 and $200 and the state's Crime Victims' Assistance Fee would
rise from $5 to $10.
</P>
<P>
   The fees -- charged on both misdemeanors, such as loitering and
littering; and felonies, such as assault and murder -- currently
raise about $12 million annually for the Crime Victims Board,
Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the past, many people who have been assaulted had to deal
with this on their own,'' said Joe Maltese, a spokesman for Sen.
Dale Volker, an Erie County Republican. ''Money must be invested to
help these individuals move on with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Volker and Assemblyman Joseph Lentol are co-chairs of a
bipartisan state Legislature conference committee discussing the
public safety portion of the 2000-01 state budget. That committee
approved the fee increases Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the increases were proposed initially by Gov. George
Pataki, acceptance by the committee virtually assures the higher
fees will be in the budget eventually approved by state
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 programs received a total of $21 million in funds
from the Crime Victims Board and the federal government last year
to support services like counseling and helping victims get
restitution.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is roughly triple the funding the 33-year-old board
dispensed five years ago, according to Caroline Quartararo, a
spokeswoman for the state Division of Criminal Justice Services.
</P>
<P>
   ''More and more victims are becoming aware that this service
exists,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lentol, a Democrat from Brooklyn, said he would like to see
some of the revenues used to help support a proposal to increase
pay for the lawyers assigned by courts to represent indigent
defendants in New York courts. Currently ranging between $25 and
$40 an hour, chief state Judge Judith Kaye has proposed increasing
the fee scheduled to between $60 and $75 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Distributing some of the new money to support the ''assigned
counsels'' would ''help prevent a collapse of the justice system,
where people aren't getting adequate counsel,'' Lentol said.
</P>
<P>
   Lentol said he agrees more money needs to be allocated to the
victims' compensation board.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just hope that with the increase we find we have more money
than we need and can start to do both,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki affirmed Tuesday that the money would go to crime
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are trying to make a deal on a state budget worth
about $78 billion for the fiscal year that began April 1. Their
leaders want to have the spending plan adopted by the start of
Passover, on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The increased fees would take effect with the acceptance of a
finalized budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 0018 </TRAILER>
