<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani's Yankee decision adds to questions about his campaign  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's decision to scrap
Senate campaign visits to Rochester and Buffalo in favor of
attending the New York Yankees home opener has raised new questions
about whether he has the drive needed to beat Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big question remains how psychically committed he is to
the race,'' New York Post columnist John Podhoretz, a Giuliani
admirer, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Passionate supporters of his are getting nervous,'' Podhoretz
said.
</P>
<P>
   GOP strategist and television commentator Jay Severin said the
mayor's decision is particularly surprising in light of polls
showing Clinton running strongly against Giuliani in traditionally
more conservative upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   The region is a key battleground and represents about 45 percent
of voting in statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to me the mayor would spend his time better north of
Yankee Stadium,'' Severin said. ''Any day the mayor does not run
like he's behind is a wasted day.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did her best to remind upstate voters about Giuliani's
decision. While she had originally planned to campaign Wednesday
only in Buffalo, a Rochester area stop was laid on at the last
minute. It was her fourth day upstate in the past six.
</P>
<P>
   Until last month, Giuliani had been leading the first lady in
statewide polls. The advantage vanished in the wake of the fatal
shooting of Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed black man, by New York
City police. Instead of condolences to the family, Giuliani made
public Dorismond's prior criminal record, including the dead man's
sealed juvenile record.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times/CBS News poll out earlier this month had
Clinton leading Giuliani, 49 percent to 41 percent, and running
even with him in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   There was slightly better polling news for Giuliani on
Wednesday. Zogby International's latest survey had the race
statistically even with Giuliani at 45 percent and Clinton at 44
percent with the mayor leading upstate, 55 percent to 34 percent. A
Zogby poll conducted in late March had the first lady at 45 percent
and the mayor at 42 percent, also a statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby's latest telephone poll of 705 likely voters was conducted
April 5-7 and has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about the Giuliani campaign have been bubbling for
months. Upstate party leaders have openly complained they are not
seeing him enough.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week to the Giuliani campaign, Rockland County
GOP Chairman Vincent Reda said he and others ''feel we are victims
of unrequited passion ... If our attentions are unwanted, please
simply advise us to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island has warned party leaders
they are in danger of ''blowing'' the Senate race if they stick
with Giuliani. The congressman has offered himself as an
alternative candidate, if party leaders want him.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani began the Senate race with some inherent problems. In
1994, he angered many die-hard Republicans by crossing party lines
to endorse incumbent Democrat Mario Cuomo in the governor's race
won by George Pataki. Also, there is a traditional bias against New
York City among upstate voters, generally the core region for
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there has been speculation throughout that Giuliani
really doesn't want to be a senator and would prefer to be
governor, U.S. attorney general or, most likely, stay on as mayor.
Term limits are forcing him out of that job at the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the mayor announced he would attend the Yankees game
rather than campaign upstate, Podhoretz was in the Post with a
column Tuesday saying ''there is one activity about which he has
shown, and continues to show, a certain ambivalence: His candidacy
for Senate. He's not campaigning very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth, I think, is that Giuliani loves his current job so
much he hasn't reconciled himself to the fact that he will soon be
asking the people of the state of New York to elevate him out of
it,'' Podhoretz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum said such criticism
is overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ''By every objective criteria, this campaign is functioning very
well,'' he said, noting the mayor leads in fund raising ($19
million to $12 million), is running about even in the polls and has
a good statewide organization.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing the mayor will step up his campaign activity as the
election draws nearer, Teitelbaum echoed a familiar Giuliani
refrain -- the mayor has a full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all due respect, Mrs. Clinton doesn't have a job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Podhoretz said he has heard the arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes strategies are reflective of what people want, not
what's best for them,'' the columnist said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm looking at his behavior and I'm listening to the music ...
He gets a real charge from being mayor and he knows that ends when
he goes into the Senate,'' Podhoretz added.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Marc Humbert has been covering New York politics for The
Associated Press for more than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 0018 </TRAILER>
