<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton adds last-minute stop to upstate campaign swing  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHILI, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton made an extra stop
during a campaign trip upstate -- at a diner near where Rudolph
Giuliani was to have appeared before scrapping the trip to watch
the Yankees play ball.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was doing her best to highlight her rival's
absence Wednesday, Giuliani the Senate candidate was taking a back
seat to Giuliani the fan at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a human being. I love baseball. I love the Yankees,'' said
the mayor, outfitted in a Yankees jacket and cap. ''Opening day is
something of real great significance to me.''
</P>
<P>
   A city emergency would have taken priority, he said, ''but if
we're just talking about raising money, you can raise money
anytime. The Yankees don't open every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had been scheduled to meet with women voters in
Rochester and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has spent much of the past week crisscrossing upstate,
where 45 percent of potential Senate votes lie. She used
Wednesday's stops at an elementary school, senior center and diner
to talk up her plans for the federal budget deficit, Medicare and
health care.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Clinton said she would fight for a voluntary
prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients, a $3,000 tax
credit for people providing long-term care for relatives, and to
re-import American-made drugs from Canada, where they sell more
cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   The latter, she said, would eliminate the need for senior
citizens and others to cross the border to buy affordable medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Like her husband, Clinton favors using the federal budget
surplus to keep safety-net programs like Medicare and Social
Security in the black for another generation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began the day reading to students at the Frederick Law
Olmsted School in Buffalo, where she advocated federal funding for
100,000 teachers.
</P>
<P>
   After a stop at the Town of Amherst Senior Center she dropped by
a restaurant in Chili, a Rochester suburb, and chatted with diners
while sipping an iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   A brouhaha in February over her failure to leave a tip at a
restaurant in Albion, 30 miles west of Rochester, must have been on
her mind: After ordering two tuna sandwiches to go, Mrs. Clinton
gave waitress Karen Ciriello a $20 gratuity.
</P>
<P>
   Until last month, Giuliani has been leading the first lady in
statewide polls but he lost ground in the wake of the fatal
shooting of an unarmed black man by New York City police.
</P>
<P>
   A Zogby International poll released Wednesday had the race
statistically even with Giuliani at 45 percent and Clinton at 44
percent, with the mayor leading upstate, 55 percent to 34 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
