<HEADLINE> 28 Electrocuted in Eastern India  </HEADLINE>
By NEELESH MISRA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- An 11,000-volt electric cable snapped
and fell on a crowd of singing and dancing Hindu devotees,
electrocuting 28 people Thursday during a midnight chariot
procession, police said.
</P>
<P>
   At least eight others were injured, and four had serious burns.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 people were marching through Daltongunj city
behind a large colorful chariot with a glittering statue of Lord
Rama, one of the most revered Hindu gods whose birthday is
celebrated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One devotee had a thick bamboo flag staff carrying a saffron
Hindu flag that snapped the high tension wire at the town's main
square, police official Sardev Rai said by phone. The thick wire
fell on the crowd, causing a stampede.
</P>
<P>
   ''The chariot started burning, and people were running all
over,'' Rai said, citing witnesses. ''There were bodies on the
road, and people were shouting and crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of grieving relatives rushed to the scene and the
bodies of most of the dead had been handed over to their families,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Daltongunj, 500 miles southeast of the capital of New Delhi, is
located in the eastern state of Bihar, India's poorest and most
lawless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
