<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Target Predatory Lending  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic lawmakers are pushing a measure
aimed at curbing a growing practice by some mortgage and
home-equity loan companies of seeking low-income borrowers and
charging them what are considered unfairly high fees and interest.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration expressed support Wednesday for the
proposal aimed at so-called predatory lending, but Republicans so
far have not signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers called the bill ''an
important step ... to combat abusive lending practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development, meanwhile,
released a study showing that minority and low-income home buyers
increasingly have become dependent on lenders that make
higher-interest loans to people with damaged credit histories.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are concerned that a growing number of these families may
be exposed to unregulated predatory practices that financially
burden them with high interest rates (and) excessive fees,'' HUD
Secretary Andrew Cuomo said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The moves came three weeks after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan criticized predatory lending, saying in a speech that it
can hurt poorer neighborhoods by forcing homeowners into
unaffordable mortgage payments, loss of their equity and even
foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, consumer finance companies have taken advantage
of people with low incomes or inferior credit histories, many of
them minorities or elderly, who cannot get conventional loans and
are desperate to become homeowners or raise cash by borrowing
against their homes. Government regulators and consumer groups say
that aggressive sales tactics and excessively high interest rates
are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John LaFalce of New York, the House Banking Committee's
senior Democrat, cited the case of Florence McKnight, an
84-year-old widow from Rochester, N.Y., who was persuaded by
salesmen to buy more than $20,000 in new windows. Under the loan,
she would have to pay more than $72,000 over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The financing deal, secured by a mortgage on her $50,000 home,
was signed at the hospital where she was medicated and recovering
from a stroke and breast cancer. Her home is in foreclosure,
LaFalce said at a news conference on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to curb predatory lending has been proposed in
California, Illinois, Maryland, Minnesota, Missouri and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The practice ''has reached near-epidemic proportions in recent
years, robbing millions of American households of the equity in
their homes and undermining the economic vitality of our
neighborhoods,'' LaFalce said.
</P>
<P>
   LaFalce and Sen. Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, senior Democrat on
the Senate Banking Committee, are the chief sponsors of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by representatives of consumer groups, the
American Association of Retired Persons and the Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would extend consumer protections under current
law to cover more high-cost mortgage refinancings, home equity
loans and home repair loans. Under current law, such high-cost
loans are not prohibited but lenders are subject to special
restrictions and disclosure requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The law now defines high-cost loans as those with interest rates
that are 10 or more percentage points above the yield on Treasury
securities with the same term. High fees are defined as those
exceeding 8 percent of the loan amount.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation would lower those ''triggers'' to 6 or
more percentage points and 5 percent of the loan, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would:
</P>
<P>
   --Prohibit up-front collection and financing of any credit
insurance or similar product on high-cost loans.
</P>
<P>
   --Limit prepayment penalties to 3 percent of the loan amount.
</P>
<P>
   --Prohibit lenders from demanding payment in full of the loan
balance under ''call'' provisions of mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   --Require companies making high-cost loans to determine that the
borrower is able to repay the loan based on federal criteria.
</P>
<P>
   --Require lenders to warn consumers in writing about the higher
risks of such loans and the need for credit counseling, and to
provide a list of local certified credit counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Banking industry officials maintain that finance companies
provide a valuable service to consumers whose low incomes and poor
credit records prevent them from qualifying for normal loans. They
say new regulations could dry up credit in many of the areas that
need it.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: HUD's new study on predatory lending:
http://www.hud.gov/news.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0030 </TRAILER>
