<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Interest Rate Hike Imminent  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Even as the European Central Bank
reported of marked improvement in the continent's economy, revised
economic forecasts for higher inflation put new pressure on the
bank to raise interest rates and slow the snowballing economy.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB, which began managing monetary policy in the 11
countries using Europe's common currency, the euro, in January
1999, gave a positive overview of the bank's first year in the
report released Wednesday. It said the members have successfully
stuck with guidelines for reducing national deficits and
introducing market-oriented reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ECB president Wim Duisenberg even praised the performance of the
euro. Despite losing roughly 17 percent of its worth against the
dollar since being launched at $1.16 on Jan. 1, 1999, the euro has
recently stabilized in a range of 95 cents to 97 cents.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news and economists largely expect the bank's
17-member governing board to keep rates steady at Thursday's
regular meeting -- especially after just boosting it a quarter-point
to 3.5 percent a month ago. But they say another rate hike is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The distance from the last step is still too short, but the
ECB still has the intention to raise rates. That is clear. Perhaps
later this month or in early May,'' said Petra Koehler, an
economist with Dresdner Bank in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   At the central bank's last meeting March 30, Duisenberg warned
the board was prepared to step in and raise rates if inflation in
the region creeps closer to the 2 percent ceiling set under ECB
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows were raised Tuesday when the European Union Commission
-- the EU's regulatory body -- upped its 2000 inflation forecast for
the euro countries to 1.8 percent, from an earlier prediction of
1.5 percent in November. The ECB keeps its own economic forecasts
private and closely watches those made by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were tempered, however, by several factors helping
keep prices level.
</P>
<P>
   High oil prices, which fan inflation, are already falling after
last month's agreement by leading the world's oil producers to
raise output. And the foundering euro, which makes imports more
expensive, has bounced back and stabilized against the dollar after
hitting a low of 93.90 cents in late February.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate labor contracts signed recently in Germany have also
mitigated fears that runaway wages in Europe's biggest economy
would spill over into other areas of the economy and push up
consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
   Still, economists say another hike will be needed soon to check
Europe's brisk economic recovery. The European Commission on
Tuesday boosted its forecast for the region's economic growth to
3.4 percent, up from its prediction of 2.9 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
   An overheating economy can spur inflation, and raising interest
rates tends to cool things off by making it more expensive to
borrow money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0035 </TRAILER>
