<HEADLINE> Kansas Player Receives Probation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Dion Rayford, the former Kansas football
player accused of damaging the drive-through window at a Taco Bell,
pleaded guilty Wednesday to criminal property damage.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 260-pound defensive end was sentenced to one year
of probation. Douglas County District Judge Paula Martin also
ordered Rayford to pay court costs and restitution for damage to
the drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the guilty plea, prosecutors dropped charges of
disorderly conduct and having an open container of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant employees said Rayford tried to crawl through the
window Nov. 17 because he thought servers failed to include a
chalupa in his takeout order.
</P>
<P>
   The widely publicized incident resulted in Rayford's suspension
for the final game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Rayford, 25, Los Gatos, Calif., transferred to Kansas before the
1998 season from West Valley Junior College in Saratoga, Calif. He
started 10 of 11 games in 1998 and all but the season finale
against Iowa State last season.
</P>
<P>
   Rayford led the team in tackles for losses, nine for 66 yards,
and was second in quarterback sacks with four.
</P>
</TEXT>
