<HEADLINE> Advanced Micro Devices Soars  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL LIEDTKE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Just when investors feared the personal
computer market had weakened, Advanced Micro Devices provided
evidence that the industry may still have plenty of bounce left in
its step.
</P>
<P>
   AMD, the No. 2 chipmaker after Intel, blew past forecasts with a
$189 million profit for the quarter ended April 2. The quarter --
the best in AMD's history -- may help calm the market jitters about
PC demand, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's possible that this could help turn the tale of the
(ticker) tape,'' said Daniel Myers, who follows chip makers for
Robertson Stephens in San Francisco. His comments came as the
tech-laden Nasdaq composite index suffered its biggest one-day
point decline. Wednesday's selloff was triggered by a Goldman
Sach's analyst's decision to cut his revenue estimate for
Microsoft's fiscal third quarter, citing slumping personal computer
sales.
</P>
<P>
   AMD said a 73 percent jump in revenues helped produce a
first-quarter profit of $189 million, or $1.15 per share, nearly
double what most industry analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   And in a conference call following the report, AMD officials
predicted even stronger results for the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The encouraging news seemed to contradict the market-rattling
comments issued earlier in the day by a top analyst who said
Microsoft's sales are being hurt by weaker demand for personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-laden Nasdaq market, already plagued by worries
about corporate profits, plunged 7 percent on Wednesday amid news
that Rick Sherlund at Goldman Sachs had lowered his revenue
estimates for the software maker.
</P>
<P>
   But after the close of regular stock trading, AMD reported that
it sold 1.2 million of its speedy Athlon microprocessors in the
quarter, a 50 percent increase from last year, as the company
grabbed a larger share of the market for PCs costing less than
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the PC market is strong and it's getting stronger,''
CEO Jerry Sanders told analysts during the conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Joseph, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in San
Francisco, said Sanders' comments should carry great weight with
investors after AMD's impressive first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   AMD's results for the first three months of 2000 compared with a
loss of $128 million, or 88 cents per share, in first quarter of
1999. The jump in Athlon sales accounted for the bulk of a record
revenue tally of $1.09 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The once-struggling company's improving fortunes have been
fueled by rising demand for lower-priced PCs, which have emerged as
the fastest growing part of the computer market as households buy
their first and second machines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0039 </TRAILER>
