<DOCNO> APW20000413.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United, Pilots Seek Mediation  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines and its pilots union are taking
their negotiations to federal mediation, officials for both sides
said after a key deadline passed without agreement on a new
contract.
</P>
<P>
   United passengers are not affected by the impasse. The pilots,
who are part-owners of the world's largest airline, said Wednesday
there are no plans for a strike or other work action.
</P>
<P>
   The motivation to settle the long-stalled talks comes from the
expiration of United's 1994 employee stock-option plan at midnight
Tuesday night. While the contract remains in effect until a new one
is signed, pilots' compensation was automatically rolled back to
the level of six years ago -- raising pilots' pay by 6.7 percent but
no longer providing any stock.
</P>
<P>
   United's pilots, machinists and many of its white-collar
employees own a combined 55 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Dubinsky, head of the Air Line Pilots Association, and
United chairman James Goodwin plan to fly to Washington on Friday
to submit the standoff to the National Mediation Board, the pilots
and the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   United, based in Elk Grove, Ill., has acknowledged it needs to
raise pilots' salaries substantially to keep pace with other
airlines. The negotiations will determine if the stock ownership
plan is renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Herb Hunter, spokesman for the United Airlines unit of the
ALPA, said the fact Dubinsky and Goodwin are flying together to
Washington is a positive sign, although it doesn't necessarily mean
a settlement is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tone of the negotiations has changed in the past few days,
but the substance really hasn't,'' he said, adding ''We're miles
behind all of our competition.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Aviation Information Resources, a United junior
captain with 10 years' experience earns $10,677 a month, while he
or she would make $12,715 a month at Delta Air Lines, for example.
</P>
<P>
   United spokesman Joe Hopkins said mediation is ''just part of
the process.'' He declined to comment on the status of contract
talks but emphasized that there will be no disruption in service
for United passengers.
</P>
<P>
   United also faces the expiration of a contract with its
machinists July 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
