<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, April 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reno Rejected by Elian's Family
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno ordered Elian
Gonzalez's Miami relatives to bring the boy to a Miami-area airport Thursday
afternoon after she failed to persuade them to end the wrenching 4{-month
custody struggle. Reno took the extraordinary step of coming to Miami to meet
for 2{ hours with the six-year-old boy's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, who later
defiantly said he would not relinquish custody of the boy. ''We will not turn
this child over, not in Opa-locka, not in any 'locka,''' he said, referring to
the government's demand that Elian be brought to the airport in Opa-locka,
outside Miami. ''They will have to take this child from me by force.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. Moves To Remove Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- South Carolina state senators on Wednesday endorsed a
bill to remove the Confederate flag from atop the Statehouse dome. Opponents say
the banner is racist but supporters insist it's a symbol of Southern heritage.
The bill would remove the banner from the dome and place a similar battle flag
behind an existing monument honoring Confederate soldiers on Statehouse grounds.
The flag would fly on the north side of the Statehouse from a pole no taller
than 20 feet. That element was added to satisfy black lawmakers and other flag
opponents who did not want the flag in a prominent position to passers-by.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury Rejects Sheppard Son's Claim
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- A jury on Wednesday unanimously rejected the claim of Dr.
Sam Sheppard's son that his father was wrongfully imprisoned for his mother's
1954 slaying, ending another chapter in the sensational case that inspired ''The
Fugitive'' television series. The eight-member jury in Cuyahoga County Common
Pleas Court did not find Dr. Sheppard guilty of murder -- that wasn't the
question before it. Rather, the decision means the couple's son, Sam Reese
Sheppard, failed to meet the burden of proof in his wrongful imprisonment civil
lawsuit against the state of Ohio. To win, Sheppard needed to convince jurors
the majority of evidence showed his father, who died in 1970, was innocent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ferry Sinks, Killing Up to 56
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- An overloaded wooden ferry boat capsized,
killing at least 56 people, officials said Thursday. More than 100 others were
missing and feared dead. Abdu Sakur, the governor of southern Sulu province,
said the ferry Arlahada capsized shortly after leaving the capital of the
province, Jolo, Wednesday night. The ferry was headed for the Philippine
province of Tawi Tawi and then to Saba in Malaysia, he said. Nineteen people
were rescued, he said. There were no immediate reports of whether foreigners
were on board.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senegalese Dancers AWOL in U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Seventeen members of a Senegalese dance troupe walked
off the stage and disappeared in the San Francisco Bay area, forcing organizers
to cancel the remainder of their U.S. tour. By Wednesday, none had filed for
political asylum from Senegal -- which ended 40 years of socialist rule this
month. They were in this country under temporary work permits that allowed them
only to work as dancers for their company.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Unilever Devouring Ben &AMP; Jerry's
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- Ben &AMP; Jerry's, the counterculture-capitalist ice
cream maker, is selling out to the corporate suits. Unilever, the multinational
conglomerate that makes such products as Wisk detergent, Q-tips and Popsicles,
is paying $326 million for the company started by two ex-hippies in an old gas
station in 1978. The Ben &AMP; Jerry's deal announced Wednesday was an outcome
neither Ben Cohen nor Jerry Greenfield favored. But the two founders were under
pressure from shareholders to sell to Unilever, which offered $43.60 per share,
or nearly 25 percent over Ben Jerry's closing price Tuesday of $34.93}.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Drop
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks dropped sharply Thursday morning as steep declines
on Wall Street dragged down Japanese blue chips and high-technology issues. The
Nikkei Stock Average shed 377.01 points, to 20,456.20 at the end of the morning
session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Outscore Raptors 77-73
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jalen Rose scored 24 points and Austin Croshere had 15
and led a fourth-quarter comeback as the Indiana Pacers beat the Raptors 77-73
Wednesday night, preventing Toronto from clinching the franchise's first playoff
berth. The victory, combined with Miami's loss to Detroit, gave the Pacers a
two-game advantage over the Heat in their battle for home-court advantage
throughout the Eastern Conference playoffs. Indiana plays at Miami on Friday.
Vince Carter had 28 points for Toronto, which led 67-61 with 7:21 to play. Tracy
McGrady had 19 for the Raptors, who will clinch a spot in the playoffs with one
victory or one Milwaukee or Orlando loss.
</P>
