<HEADLINE> Fox Closes Book on TV Marriage  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Fox had concluded that there was little it could
have done to prevent the public relations fiasco that followed
''Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Burned by the revelation that wealthy groom Rick Rockwell had a
restraining order issued against him in 1991 by a former fiancee,
the TV network hired a law firm to probe whether it could have done
anything more to check into his background.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm found that the show's producer, Next Entertainment,
hired a private investigator and search firm to check Rockwell's
record before the show aired, Fox spokesman Jeff DeRome said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal Fair Credit Reporting Act prohibited the
disclosure of embarrassing events that had occurred more than seven
years earlier, except for criminal convictions, DeRome said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the law, producers and Fox depended on Rockwell to
let them know if there was anything in his background they should
know -- and the restraining order didn't come up, he said. Rockwell
has said he considered the event ''ancient history'' and ''somewhat
of a nonevent when it occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   No one at Fox will lose their jobs or be punished for their role
in setting up the special, DeRome said.
</P>
<P>
   The February wedding drew tremendous ratings, but launched an
immediate debate on the propriety of a TV network brokering a
marriage between two strangers. Rockwell and his bride, Darva
Conger, quickly ended the marriage and Fox has vowed never to do
anything like it again.
</P>
<P>
   ''Case closed,'' DeRome said. ''It is clear to us now how it
happened and why it happened. I guess everyone involved has learned
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading into a ratings ''sweeps'' month in May, Fox has clearly
toned down. It has scheduled specials on ghosts, UFOs, the
paranormal and funny game show outtakes. As promised, Fox has
steered clear of police chases and marauding animals.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is also planning a live special where an ancient Egyptian
tomb is opened. For that, it hired one of the most noncontroversial
hosts it could find: genial former ''20/20'' anchor Hugh Downs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
