<HEADLINE> Baltic Leaders Discuss Russia  </HEADLINE>
By JAN M. OLSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOLDING, Denmark (AP) -- Ministers from the Baltic Sea region
stressed cooperation with the largest member, Russia, as they
tiptoed around the sensitive issues of Chechnya and EU expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia is a very complementary and important partner to the
Baltic Sea region and to Europe,'' Danish Prime Minister Poul Nyrup
Rasmussen said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But widespread international condemnation of Russia's offensive
in the breakaway republic of Chechnya was also echoed at the summit
in Kolding, 145 miles west of Denmark's capital, Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   One of the conditions of normalization between Europe and Russia
''should be that the Chechnya question is solved in an acceptable
manner,'' Nyrup Rasmussen said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day conference, which ends today, was aimed at
strengthening regional cooperation among the Council of the Baltic
Sea States by bringing together ministers from the 11 member
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers, including German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and
other leaders, planned to tackle issues ranging from the
environment and crime to attempts by Poland, Lithuania, Latvia and
Estonia to join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union, the four EU
candidates, which all border Russia, have made joining the
15-member bloc a top foreign policy priority in the hopes of
tapping into lucrative markets and enhance national security.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has voiced opposition to the EU's eastward expansion but
says it would like more regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Latvia's ambassador to Denmark, Aivars Baumanis, said their
participation in the Baltic conference was a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are able to cooperate in this regional structure, it
shows that we can cooperate in the large structure of the EU,''
Baumanis said.
</P>
<P>
   Poland has said the EU enlargement process was moving too slowly
because of the large number of candidate countries. Nyrup
Rasmussen, whose country was playing host to the summit, promised
the complaint would be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Romano Prodi, president of the European Union's executive
Commission, reassured them that expansion was a priority but said
it would take time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want the enlargement as soon as possible,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
