<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Neill Autopsy Results Published  </HEADLINE>
By JANET McCONNAUGHEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great dramatist Eugene O'Neill was as brilliant as ever
during the last decade of his life, but he couldn't write: Brain
cells controlling voluntary movement had withered away.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill had feared it was Parkinson's disease, but it was
instead a rare and little-understood brain illness. In today's New
England Journal of Medicine, scientists offer a detailed cellular
look at the damage and diagrams showing just where the brain
decayed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is by far a more detailed account than has been published
before,'' said Murray Biggs, a professor of English and theater
studies at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Price, chief of neurology at Harvard-affiliated McLean
Hospital in Belmont, Mass., wrote the article with Dr. E.P.
Richardson Jr., who supervised O'Neill's autopsy in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright suffered from ''a very rare degenerative disease
of the cerebellum. Which luckily was not passed on. No other
O'Neill family member has this disease,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is called idiopathic cerebellar-cortical atrophy,
which means only a wasting of the brain of unknown cause.
</P>
<P>
   The true nature of O'Neill's disorder was first described by
Arthur and Barbara Gelb in their 1962 biography of the playwright.
</P>
<P>
   Gelb said he and his wife, who are revising and expanding the
biography from one volume to three, were given a copy of the
15-page autopsy report in 1960 by O'Neill's widow, Carlotta
O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were the only ones she gave that to. She handed it to me
personally,'' Gelb said. ''She said, 'I want you to have this for
your book, because you can't understand the tragedy of this man
unless you have the autopsy report.'''
</P>
<P>
   The report is also part of a 185-box O'Neill collection at Yale,
but was among papers kept private for 25 years at Mrs. O'Neill's
request. There have been no restrictions on their use since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Those papers are a big reason the Gelbs are rewriting their
biography. The first new volume is due out next month.
</P>
<P>
   Another biography, ''Eugene O'Neill: Beyond Mourning and
Tragedy,'' was published in November and also describes the
neurological disorder in some detail.
</P>
<P>
   Author Stephen Black of Simon Fraser University said he used the
typewritten autopsy report, interviews with medical experts and a
letter in which Mrs. O'Neill's psychiatrist explained the autopsy
report to her.
</P>
<P>
   Price said medical tradition requires doctors to keep an autopsy
report confidential unless the family agrees to publication, which
he got through actress Geraldine Chaplin, O'Neill's granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   That also meant he could use slides of O'Neill's brain tissue,
which are still at Massachusetts General Hospital, and reports of
neurological examinations during the last years of O'Neill's life.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's doctors had told him he had Parkinson's disease, but
that diagnosis was refuted by the autopsy report.
</P>
<P>
   Price said he does not know what caused the disease. ''It was
apparently a random and very tragic mutation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the great advances in medicine since 1953, there
probably still would be no cure.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill ultimately died of pneumonia, probably brought on by
breathing in bits of food that he was unable to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could have prolonged his life. With good antibiotics and
pulmonary care, we probably could have been able to treat his
pneumonia,'' Price said. ''He might have had a little better
quality of life, a little more quantity, but ultimately he would
have died from it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   McLean Hospital: http://www.mclean.harvard.edu
</P>
<P>
   Beinecke Library at Yale:
http://www.library.yale.edu/beinecke/brblhome.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
