<HEADLINE> Dodgers 3, Giants 2, Suspended, 5{  </HEADLINE>
By DENNIS GEORGATOS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The swirling winds may have been left
behind at Candlestick Park, but there's no stopping the rain.
</P>
<P>
   The first night game at Pacific Bell Park was interrupted by a
downpour Wednesday night, and it was suspended in the sixth inning
with the Los Angeles Dodgers leading the San Francisco Giants 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The teams will complete the game from the point it was stopped
on Thursday at 5:05 p.m. PDT. The Dodgers and Giants are scheduled
to play Thursday night at 7:35 p.m., or 30 minutes following the
completion of the suspended game.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre's sacrifice fly in the top of the sixth put the
Dodgers ahead 3-2. The Giants were coming to bat in the bottom half
when it began to rain heavily, sending the sellout crowd
scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   Play was halted and a tarp was rolled out to cover the infield,
heralding the first weather delay at Pac Bell Park a day after its
grand opening Tuesday when the Dodgers beat the Giants 6-5. It was
suspended after a delay of one hour, 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had the bases loaded with none out in the second
after Shawn Green led off with a single and Eric Karros and Todd
Hundley walked, but Beltre hit into a double play, scoring one run.
Kevin Elster, greeted with boos in his first at bat after Tuesday's
three-homer effort, struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles went ahead 2-0 on Green's third inning sacrifice fly
before San Francisco evened the score, getting a home run from Rich
Aurilia leading off the third and scoring without benefit of a hit
in the fourth when Bill Mueller came around from second on first
baseman Karros' fielding error.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown was placed on the 15-day
disabled list with a broken right pinkie finger and left-hander
Carlos Perez was recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque to fill his
roster spot. Perez is scheduled to start Thursday night's series
finale against the Giants in Pac Bell Park. ... Gary Sheffield
singled in the third inning to extend his hitting streak to eight
games. He also had a hit in each of the last six games of the 1999
season. ... Giants first baseman J.T. Snow was recognized for his
defensive excellence before the game, when he was presented with a
fifth straight Rawlings Gold Glove award. ... Left-hander Shawn
Estes, who began the season on the disabled list because of a sore
pitching shoulder, had a rehabilitation start for the Giants' Class
A affiliate in San Jose. He pitched seven innings against
Bakersfield on Wednesday night, allowing two hits and no runs while
striking out 11. The Giants could activate him later this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
