<HEADLINE> Senate passes treasurer reform bill  </HEADLINE>
By STRAT DOUTHAT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Faced with a veto threat from Gov. John
G. Rowland, the state Senate today unanimously approved an amended
reform measure designed to create more oversight of the tarnished
state treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, passed in the early hours of the morning, was changed
to give the state Ethics Commission a voice in determining who can
collect finder's fees for dealing with the treasurer and brokering
investments of state pension funds. It now goes back to the House,
which last week passed a controversial version opponents said was
so flawed it would not correct the problems that led to indictment
of former Treasurer Paul Silvester on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   The governor had said he would veto the bill if it were not
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   The amended version contains provisions to create the position
of investment specialist in the treasurer's office and strengthen
oversight safeguards by the Investment Advisory Council.
</P>
<P>
   The bill outlaws the payment of finder's fees to anybody except
qualified financial counselors so designated by the treasurer in
consultation with ethics officials. It provides penalties for
anybody who violates the finder's fee provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill addresses our concerns,'' said Alan Plofsky,
executive director of the state Ethics Commission. He had attacked
the House version, which would have permitted ''investment
professions'' to do business with the treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Plofsky said the earlier bill was virtually worthless because
anybody could call himself an ''investment professional.'' The
amended bill is a great improvement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Denise Nappier said she strongly supports the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I encourage the governor to sign the bill,'' she said. ''It
puts the force of law behind administrative action I've already
taken, and strengthens oversight of the office.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, among other things, replaces the deputy treasurer with
a chief investment officer and prohibits the state treasurer, any
candidate for state treasurer or any member of the Investment
Advisory Council, from seeking campaign contributions from persons
connected to an investment company.
</P>
<P>
   The reform measure stems from last year's scandal surrounding
Silvester, a Rowland appointee who pleaded guilty in September to
charges of racketeering and money laundering related to
fund-raising in his failed 1998 campaign. He admitted accepting
kickbacks in the form of campaign donations from companies with
which he invested state pension money, and raising money for the
campaigns of others including the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who has denied any knowledge of the fund-raising
illegalities, appointed Silvester after the former treasurer
resigned to go to work for an investment company that had done
business with the state.
</P>
<P>
   The reform bill requires the treasurer to wait at least one year
from the date a contract is negotiated before going to work for the
company, if the contract amounts to at least $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also restricts the governor's power to appoint someone
to fill a vacancy in the Treasurer's Office when the General
Assembly is not in session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 0145 </TRAILER>
