<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prescient Canadian General Retires  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- There were the nightmares and flashbacks, visions
of mutilated, decaying corpses brought on by a smell or glance or
just the dark of night. More than once, Lt. Gen. Romeo Dallaire
contemplated suicide.
</P>
<P>
   For the commander of the U.N. Rwanda mission that became one of
the world body's biggest failures, the post-traumatic stress
syndrome he has suffered for more than two years finally became too
much.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Dallaire announced he was taking early retirement
next week, more than a year before he reaches the mandatory
retirement age of 55 for senior officers.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with Canadian media, the trim 53-year-old man said
psychological wounds from viewing the slaughter of 500,000 Rwandans
without being able to stop it forced him to give up a 35-year
military career.
</P>
<P>
   Now he hopes to conclude therapy and then teach, lecture and
write about his experiences. That includes telling his side of the
Rwanda story, something he has been unable to do because of
military restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I need to get that out,'' he said. ''Simply as part, I think,
of reasonable therapy. I think a lot of that will be useful to
people who command in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallaire went to Rwanda in 1993 as head of the more than
2,000-member peacekeeping force comprising some Canadian and
Belgian troops, along with African soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to figure out the dynamics of a country
known for cycles of ethnic slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, 1994, he cabled his New York superiors a warning
that Hutu extremists were preparing plans to slaughter minority
Tutsis. According to an independent report on the U.N. role in
Rwanda, Dallaire's cable was never shown to the Security Council
and failed to receive the necessary attention.
</P>
<P>
   His request for more troops to try to stop the extremists from
arming their supporters were denied. When the plane carrying
Rwanda's Hutu president was shot down April 6, 1994, the planned
attacks on Tutsis and moderate Hutus began and Dallaire lacked the
manpower, firepower and mandate to try to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. on Wednesday of hearing
friends scream for help as he spoke to them by telephone. The
nightmares and flashbacks continue, he said, though he is working
in therapy on what triggers them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a certain smell or something that catches his
eye, he said. Asked if he ever contemplated suicide, he said yes,
''a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Long after the genocide, the Belgian Senate accused him of
negligence in the death of 10 Belgian soldiers under his command
who were massacred on April 7 after he assigned them to guard the
Rwandan prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Dallaire said the true blame lay with some of the powerful
countries in the United Nations that were unwilling to face the
political price of losing troops to try to stop the Rwandan
carnage. He refused to name countries.
</P>
<P>
   Dallaire has been on medical leave since 1998. He had been
serving as an associate defense minister in charge of military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   He has championed the cause of soldiers suffering psychological
effects from service abroad. He said Wednesday that soldiers
exposed to combat must be watched for years after they come home
because reactions can be delayed or repressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my case, I finally broke four years after the event,'' he
said. ''I couldn't take it any more.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what he thinks of himself, others consider him a
Canadian hero.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Art Eggleton said Dallaire left an indelible
''mark of dedication and duty to this country and the Canadian
Forces.'' He added: ''Rwanda has left a mark on him and on his
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0150 </TRAILER>
