<DOCNO> APW20000413.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expectation Shadows Gen. Powell  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Even while 20,000 feet in the air, Colin
Powell has his heels dug in deep on the questions he's been asked
about a million times.
</P>
<P>
   No, he's still not looking for any elected office.
</P>
<P>
   No, even if George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, got down on his hands and knees, he wouldn't
sign on as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   And no, he's not campaigning for a Cabinet post in a Bush
administration, although he would listen if such a job was offered.
</P>
<P>
   The former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff put it this way
Wednesday: ''I'm not looking for a job. I'm very happy with the
work I'm doing. But when a president or a president-elect asks you
about it, you have to think about it. And I have never excluded
going back into government.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Powell says, he is fulfilled leading the charge for
the nation's youth while heading up America's Promise: The Alliance
for Youth. It is an organization that for nearly three years has
been encouraging volunteerism and mentoring.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been in the vineyards planting the vines and we now see
them bearing fruit,'' Powell said in an interview with The
Associated Press en route to a North Carolina event for America's
Promise.
</P>
<P>
   The plum of this trip was getting the signature of North
Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt on an agreement that commits Hunt's support
to America's Promise's goals.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, signed during a rally at a Greensboro
shopping mall, Hunt issued an executive order giving state
employees paid time off to mentor children.
</P>
<P>
   For Powell, the goal is to get more than money from
corporations. The former Army general wants their souls.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's easy to write an oversized check and say, 'We've done our
part.' But we go to the company's chairman and president to get
them to invest in their own futures. It's more than volunteering.
What they do is in their self-interest,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   America's Promise is centered on five guiding principles --
pairing children with caring adults, providing safe haven for kids,
giving children proper nutrition, teaching marketable skills and
providing community service.
</P>
<P>
   At a roundtable of community and corporate leaders, Powell
drinks in the message from representatives from companies like
First Union Bank, the Pepsi Bottling Co. and General Electric -- a
pledge to give employees paid leave to volunteer time at local
schools and community facilities.
</P>
<P>
   At the mall, Powell tells a cheering crowd, ''The children of
today have enemies in their lives - drugs, crime, violence and
dispair. We have to step forward and be mentors.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many times Powell expresses his passion for
helping children or his aversion to the prospect of nonstop
political fund-raising and the other confines of seeking elected
office, the general knows another question about his nonexistent
political ambitions is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ten years ago, I was a lieutenant general who was dragged into
the White House. Before I knew what happened, I was chairman'' of
the Joint Chiefs, Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you turned back the clock 12 years and gave me back the
anonymity I had, it wouldn't bother me in the least. At least I
could go to garage sales again.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said that while he has no interest in either the
presidency or vice presidency, he believes American voters could
look beyond its racially divided past and unite behind a black
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the country is ready,'' he said. ''When I considered
running (for president) in 1995, I had to talk to America and I
concluded the country had changed to a point where it would be
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he added, ''the country has matured.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Is there anybody else the party would rather see there than
Colin Powell?'' gushed Mary Matalin, conservative television
commentator. ''The party would love him to grab the vice
presidential slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Matalin agreed with Powell that Americans wouldn't have a
problem for a presidential ticket that included a black man.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see any risk for the party. Ask people what they want
in leaders today as a backlash to what's been happening and they
say leadership, character, patriotism -- everything Colin Powell
embodies. It's not a color thing that would decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, a Democrat, concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a military man who has commanded troops, he now is
mobilizing people nationwide to give back to their communities. He
stands for all the right things,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the adulation from both sides of the political
spectrum, Powell said his mind is made up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no interest in being vice president. I'm not being coy
or cute. ... I admire people who seek political office but you need
to have a certain type of passion for that.
</P>
<P>
   ''If any president or elected official asks you to serve, you've
got to listen to that request. I'm not ruling anything like that
out but I'm not ruling it in either.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Paul Shepard covers minority affairs for The
Associated Press in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   America's Promise site: http://www.americaspromise.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
