<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> America's museums promise to step up search for Holocaust art  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It was a fine 16th century painting of the
Virgin Mary and Jesus that graced a wall in the Vienna home of
Philipp von Gomperz before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Nazis marched in and seized the work. A photograph of
it was taken for Adolph Hitler's review.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a half century later, ''Madonna and Child in a
Landscape'' by Lucas Cranach appeared on the Internet, as part of
the collection of the North Carolina Museum of Art. And on Feb. 3,
2000, after negotiations, the work was relinquished to two sisters
who are the sole heirs of the Gomperz family.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Wheeler, director of the North Carolina museum, was one
of four heads of major U.S. museums who testified Wednesday before
the Presidential Advisory Commission on Holocaust Assets. The
commission acts as a national body examining what stolen war-era
assets exist in the United States and oversees the research to
identify them.
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying at the hearing of the commission's Committee on
Art and Cultural Property were directors Philippe de Montebello of
New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art, Glenn Lowry of the Museum of
Modern Art in Manhattan and Malcolm Rogers of the Boston Museum of
Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The four museums own many of the 20,000 European artworks in
America, some of which ''might be possibly suspect,'' said Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   The directors pledged to the commission to step up their efforts
to solve an artistic Holocaust mystery: finding any Nazi-looted art
that might now be owned by American museums.
</P>
<P>
   ''The burden of research is absolutely enormous. But this is a
national priority,'' said Rogers,
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, his Boston museum posted seven European
paintings on its Web site, asking the public for help in tracing
their history.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a flashpoint when works of art become visible,'' said
MOMA's Lowry. ''And we intend to continue drilling away.''
</P>
<P>
   Montebello's Metropolitan Museum is now researching almost 400
of its pieces to make sure they are not on the Nazi-plundered trail
that stretches back a half century to art that once adorned pre-war
European homes.
</P>
<P>
   However, because there are often gaps in a piece's history,
Montebello added, ''there is a great deal of serendipity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowry said he hoped the research would be done with the direct
help of claimants, rather than through lawsuits. In September, a
U.S. magistrate barred the return to Austria of an Egon Schiele
painting on loan to MOMA that may have been stolen by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, several works in U.S. museums have been proven
to belong to Holocaust heirs, though Lowry said he did not believe
the number of looted works in American collections was ''vast.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Deputy Secretary of the Treasury Stuart Eizenstat, a
commission member, said that in addition to art held by U.S.
museums, any research should take into account works owned or sold
by private dealers and auction houses. Christie's and Sotheby's
both have participated in identifying Nazi-linked art.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman William Singer presided over the hearing held
Wednesday at the headquarters of the New York Bar Association in
midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the presidential commission's role is to oversee
research on assets and organize a central database of artworks,
rather than to seek restitution.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the committee also focused on lesser-known art,
books and religious items that comprise Jewish cultural property
stolen during the wartime era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 0154 </TRAILER>
