<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Trust in Government Higher  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ask people how they feel about ''the federal
government'' and they're likely to give a cool response, but ask
how they feel about a specific agency and they probably will offer
a more favorable view.
</P>
<P>
   What people think of specific agencies also depends on who you
ask. Some who benefit from the agency's work may say government
workers are doing a great job, while others may see the agency's
duties in a less favorable light.
</P>
<P>
   An example is the Internal Revenue Service. While six of 10
professional tax preparers view the agency in a positive light,
taxpayers and business tax officers had generally negative views of
the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way a lot of smiling, courteous IRS employees are
going to make tax collection popular,'' said Paul Light, an expert
on government reform and director of governmental studies at the
Brookings Institution. ''But there's actually good news in this
poll about the IRS. People think highly of the employees. They
think they're professional. They just don't happen to like the
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Most agencies are viewed differently by different sets of their
customers, according to the poll by the Pew Research Center for the
People &AMP; the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Four of five environmental advocates have a favorable view of
the Environmental Protection Agency, and two-thirds of the public
felt that way, but only half of the business regulatory officers
polled felt positively about the agency.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Social Security Administration, three-fourths of
recipients of benefits had a positive view of the agency compared
with just over half of the payroll taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Depending on your relationship with the agency, it can make a
difference in how you evaluate it,'' said Mary McIntosh, a
Princeton Survey Research Associates analyst who directed the
study. ''Favorable feelings about an agency vary according to how
much people support or oppose the mission of that agency. It really
does depend on who you ask.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh said the tendency is to assume that the generally
unfavorable feelings people have about government as a whole spill
over to individual agencies, but the poll indicates otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration was seen favorably by more than
four of five medical professionals, business regulatory officials,
advocates and the chronically ill.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration was viewed positively by
four of five frequent fliers and two-thirds of pilots, but only six
of 10 air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   A separate Pew poll taken in February showed that four of 10
people said they trusted the federal government just about always
or most of the time, compared with only about one-fourth of the
public who felt that way in November 1998, at the height of the
Monica Lewinsky scandal and impeachment drama.
</P>
<P>
   ''A person's overall trust in government is usually related to
how the economy is doing, how they feel about Bill Clinton, how
they feel about campaign corruption,'' Light said. ''They generally
are much more trusting of their mailman, more favorable toward the
person who answers the phone at Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Majorities of every group polled said employees of the five
agencies were courteous.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters surveyed 3,147 people between mid-January and
mid-March with error margins ranging from plus or minus 4
percentage points for the 641 individual taxpayers to larger error
margins for smaller samples, such as those who receive Social
Security benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0155 </TRAILER>
