<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serial Killing Jolts Pakistan  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY GANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- Clutching his splintered cricket bat,
9-year-old Zishan Khan stared fearfully at the simple wooden door
that opened to a house of horrors, where 100 children were lured to
their deaths with promises of food and a warm bed.
</P>
<P>
   While the neighborhood slept, Javed Iqbal led homeless children
by the hand to the dank, three-room cement home -- where he sexually
abused them, strangled them and dissolved their bodies in a vat of
acid.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down at his dirt-caked plastic sandals, Zishan tapped
the cracked cement laneway with his cricket bat. ''I never knew,''
he whispered. ''I didn't know what was going on inside there.''
</P>
<P>
   The revelation of Iqbal's horrific crimes, committed with two
teen-age accomplices, jolted human rights groups in Pakistan to the
plight of street children, estimated to number in the millions.
</P>
<P>
   It ''brought home with a bang how limited society's safeguards
for the children were and with what gruesome consequences,'' the
Human Rights Commission of Pakistan wrote in its annual report.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapping and rape of children is one of the most common
crimes in Pakistan, involving an average of one young girl a day,
the commission reported.
</P>
<P>
   The details of Iqbal's killing spree first emerged in a letter
he wrote to the police late last year. That led authorities to his
house, where they found the remains of two bodies in a vat of acid,
a pile of children's clothes and the photographs of 100 children --
the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Iqbal turned himself in. He was tried, convicted
and sentenced to die as his victims had -- strangled, his body cut
into 100 pieces and dissolved in acid.
</P>
<P>
   Area resident Abdul Jabbar said Iqbal did not target
neighborhood children who lived at home with their parents -- he
sought out the street children.
</P>
<P>
   Children like 9-year-old Adil Riaz.
</P>
<P>
   Adil, who has never gone to school, has been working in a
mechanic's shop for two years now. His mother is a widow who needs
the 50 cents a day he makes working 10 hours to help feed his five
brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he said, he sleeps on the street outside the shop,
not far from Iqbal's house. He smiled shyly when asked if he is
afraid at night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mostly I'm just tired. Every day I'm just tired,'' he said,
rubbing his oil-blackened hands. His tiny fingernails are jagged
and filled with built-up grease.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is what drives many of the children from their homes.
And with no family nearby or homeless shelters available, they
become easy targets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because they are so poor, families, particularly those with
many children, have been unable to keep track of every child and
some need their children to support them,'' said Afrasiab Khattak,
chairman of the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets, gangs thrive on them.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are certain mafias who take the children on the street
and exploit them,'' Khattak said. ''They are the mafias who run
begging rings, child prostitution rings.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sheikhupura, in Punjab province, a gang that kidnapped young
children would break their legs or arms and let the bones reset
crooked, then send them into the streets to beg.
</P>
<P>
   Another gang was traced to Multan, also in Punjab province, the
human rights report said. That group kidnapped boys between 10 and
14 years old, castrated them and then sold them to the circus and
for stage shows.
</P>
<P>
   Khattak said the heart of the problem is mixed-up priorities
that allocate nearly 70 percent of Pakistan's annual $14 billion
budget on defense and debt servicing and barely 4 percent on social
services.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the problem is an ill-equipped and inept police force
that rarely investigated reports of missing children.
</P>
<P>
   Iqbal's neighbor, Jabbar, said that before Iqbal wrote his
letter he went to the police station to report his crimes, but was
sent away. It took two weeks before police investigated Iqbal's
house after receiving information about the crimes committed there,
Jabbar said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police never took it seriously,'' he said. ''Police
thought it was a joke and that he was a mental patient. He told the
police 'I have killed these children,' and the police said, 'come
back in the morning.'''
</P>
<P>
   In late December, after the extent of Iqbal's crimes was known,
the Punjab police chief distributed a memo to officers throughout
the province saying ''reports of missing children should not now be
taken lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The government should open a center for children on the street
and find their parents,'' Jabbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Khattak said in some cities the social services department has
begun trying to document the street children, rather than simply
ignore them. The Human Rights Commission of Pakistan has begun a
survey to determine how many street children there are, the
problems they face and what they need.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the children in the neighborhood are still
having nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Zishan, who lives in the same alleyway as Iqbal, now refuses to
walk to school alone.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the dark, I worry about bad spirits from there,'' he said.
''I am afraid they will come and eat me.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.hrcp.cjb.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
