<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Holds Midnight Rendezvous  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore didn't arrive here
until after midnight, but that wasn't going to stop him from
keeping an appointment with a local teacher who was serving as host
for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, on his third all-day trip to a school in two weeks, has
made a point of sleeping over the night before at the home of a
teacher from the chosen school. This time, it was Laurel Warfield's
turn to play host.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very excited,'' she said. ''We've been really
anticipating this big day -- or evening, or whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, precisely, six or so hours when most people are sleeping
and with Gore due to depart for Marie Davis Middle School at about
6:45 a.m., it wasn't clear how much conversation there would be.
</P>
<P>
   Warfield knew she wasn't getting prime time with Gore. When told
that his late-night visit was already running an hour late, she
said, ''Oh my lord.''
</P>
<P>
   But Warfield and her family were waiting up, checking out the
local TV crews and swarming Secret Service agents as she prepared
to tuck the vice president into her son's corner room.
</P>
<P>
   ''Normally I would be tired but I'm not tonight,'' she said. ''I
figure I can be tired and worry about it another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Warfield is a 6th grade language arts teacher at the middle
school, a magnet program that offers advanced courses with a
special focus on foreign languages and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Warfield and Gore were both awake enough to talk about
education, she hoped to chat about the importance of getting
everyone involved in schools -- not just teachers, but parents and
students, too.
</P>
<P>
   Warfield suspects she was chosen because of her students' high
test scores, but she's also the sort of voter Gore will need in
November. Generally a Republican, she crossed over to vote for
democratic Gov. James Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't decided who to vote for in the presidential contest.
''I'm still waiting on some of the issues,'' she said Wednesday
night as she was still waiting for the vice president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
