<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Election Head for Runoff  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori will have to wait
for a runoff election for another chance to beat his upstart rival,
Alejandro Toledo, after falling short of a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, Toledo says the playing field will be different
as they seek a clean campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the second round, we demand substantially different
conditions to compete,'' Toledo said Wednesday night after final
results were released. ''The international community is watching.
The nation is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, 61, made no immediate public statement. He has kept a
low profile since Sunday's vote -- the culmination of an election
campaign so riddled with accusations of government abuses and
irregularities that the international community all but insisted on
a second round.
</P>
<P>
   ''The accumulation of fraud allegations from Sunday are so
numerous that the president's image is irreparably damaged,'' said
political scientist Julio Carrion. ''I seriously doubt that
Fujimori, if he is declared president, will still be president at
year's end.''
</P>
<P>
   A runoff election will be scheduled for late May or early June.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Toledo's followers who for hours had waited for the
deciding result in downtown Lima broke into wild cheers when they
heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   For three days Toledo's supporters had demonstrated by the tens
of thousands in Peru's main cities. The former World Bank official
had warned that the mostly peaceful marches and rallies could turn
violent if Fujimori claimed an unprecedented third five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people went to the streets and shook up Fujimori's
government,'' said Teresa Casallo, a 45-year-old primary school
teacher. ''This time it will be difficult to pull off a fraud
because if it happens, the people will take to the streets again.''
</P>
<P>
   After tallying 97.68 percent of the ballots, Fujimori had 49.84
percent compared to 40.31 percent for his challenger. Various other
candidates split the rest. Election officials said the remaining
ballots could not change the tally enough to give Fujimori a win.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, exit polls and unofficial tallies by independent
monitors had indicated Fujimori would not reach the 50 percent plus
one vote needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   But after an unexplained 12-hour delay, the first official
returns showed Fujimori on track to claim a first-round victory,
prompting suspicions of fraud. Then on Tuesday, officials said
Fujimori had 49.96 percent of the vote with 90.8 percent of the
ballots counted.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deciding results were released Wednesday, U.S. State
Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the United States would
have ''serious, serious questions'' if there was not a second
round.
</P>
<P>
   European governments intensified the heat on Fujimori as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have a lot of confidence in the voting process
either,'' British Ambassador Roger Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   As election officials announced the deciding results, Francisco
Tudela, Fujimori's vice presidential candidate and a former foreign
minister, complained bitterly about U.S. interference in the
election.
</P>
<P>
   He said he rejected in the ''most energetic terms the fact that
a foreign government would emit a judgment value about elections in
another country before the official count is in.''
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, opposition candidates accused Fujimori's
military intelligence service of using rock-throwing thugs to
disrupt political rallies, sponsoring lurid tabloid newspaper
attacks and blocking access to largely state-controlled television
and radio.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to Sunday's vote, Toledo, 54, was the
target of a smear campaign that accused him of everything from
shunning an illegitimate daughter to being an architect of a
financial pyramid scheme that impoverished thousands of Peruvians
in the early 1990s. He has denied the charges.	   Analysts expected more of the
same in the runoff campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're probably going to see personal attacks directed at
Toledo and his family all over again. We're probably going to see
government funds used heavily to favor the president,'' said
political analyst Fernando Rospigliosi. ''That's the image that is
going to stay with Fujimori.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0239 </TRAILER>
