<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Julie Krone Eases Into Retirement  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD ROSENBLATT, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Julie Krone is feeling more comfortable about
life now that it's been nearly a year since she retired as
thoroughbred racing's top female jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I'm less apt to leap off curbs when I'm rollerblading and
I will actually leave my home on time so I don't have to drive
fast,'' said Krone, whose stellar 19-year career was plagued by
injuries. ''I'm a little more balanced and basic. My friends would
say I'm more grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   At 36, Krone has packed up her tack and moved to Los Angeles,
where she works for TV Game Network's racing show and also has a
budding career doing voiceovers for Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having a squeaky voice is paying off,'' said Krone, whose
high-pitched voice kept her from ever getting lost in a crowd even
though she stands 4-foot-10{ and weighs 98 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Krone feels so good these days she says she'd love to get back
on a thoroughbred again.
</P>
<P>
   ''But only in the morning,'' she said. ''I'd like to gallop 'em
because that's what I miss the most. But I will never race ride
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone, who won most of her 3,545 races at East Coast tracks, was
back in New York on Wednesday to participate in a roundtable
discussion, sponsored by Pfizer Inc., on post-traumatic stress
disorder (PTSD), which she suffered from in her final years as a
jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Post-traumatic stress disorder affects as many as 13 million
Americans, or 10 percent of the general population, according to
Dr. Jonathan Davidson, a professor of psychiatry at Duke who also
was part of the round table. PTSD affects twice as many women as
men and can be triggered by trauma such as violent crime, war,
death of a loved one, or, as in Krone's case, horrific injury.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after she became the first female rider to win a
Triple Crown race by capturing the 1993 Belmont Stakes aboard
Colonial Affair, Krone was seriously injured in a terrifying spill
at Saratoga. She shattered her right ankle, bruised her heart and
punctured an elbow. The ankle injury required two steel plates and
14 screws to repair.
</P>
<P>
   Although Krone said she did not experience mental stress after
that injury, it was a spill just 13 days after returning to racing
that unleashed a torrent of debilitating symptoms. The fall came on
Jan. 13, 1995, at Gulfstream, when Krone broke both hands when
thrown from her mount at the top of the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was lying there on the ground, I knew my life was going
to change,'' Krone said. ''And as I was getting ready to come back
I had trepidation. I had nightmares about falling. I used to get
lost on streets I'd been driving on for years. I wondered, 'What is
wrong with me?' My daily plan was how to kill myself that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys have to be fearless in order to compete, and can never
back down from any challenge. It's the way the business works. As
Krone says, you always have to be ready to ''give up body parts for
a winner.'' But for her, the fearlessness was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ''My subconscious ability to communicate with horses was
diminished,'' said Krone. ''It was like someone going through the
motions of being a jockey.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when she looked for help, finally realizing her so-called
shield of invincibility, which seems to be built into most athletes
these days, was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Krone went to a psychiatrist, Dr. Tom Qualtere, in Saratoga
Springs. He diagnosed her with post-traumatic stress disorder, and
by late 1997 she began taking Zoloft, an anti-depressant approved
by the U.S. Federal Drug Administration for treatment of PTSD.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Krone refused to take any medication, but a seven-day
suspension from riding gave her a window of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was thinking about all the people who bet on me when I was
suffering from PTSD, and I'd be riding in the back thinking,
'Please don't let me die,''' Krone said. ''When I started taking
Zoloft things got better. All the things I lost came back and I got
to be myself again.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a turning point in my career and life.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone, who was nominated earlier this year for Thoroughbred
Racing's Hall of Fame, continued to ride and finished as the
winningest female jockey and with $81 million in purses earned --
16th on racing's career list.
</P>
<P>
   Krone is feeling a lot better about herself, and would like
nothing more than to stick around to watch Saturday's Wood
Memorial, featuring Kentucky Derby favorite Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw him in California,'' Krone said. ''I like him a lot.
Plus, I have him in my fantasy stable for the Derby.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0243 </TRAILER>
