<HEADLINE> Michigan Gymnast Has Routine Down  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Sarah Cain of Michigan offers a textbook
example of how to hit the routine nearly every time -- whether she's
on the vault, the floor exercise or in the interview room.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines have a strong chance of winning the NCAA women's
gymnastics title because Cain's 9.927 vault average leads the
nation. She's the highest-rated all-around athlete with a 39.387
average.
</P>
<P>
   Cain also ranks third in the floor and fourth on the bars,
demonstrating her ability to perform well anywhere. Yet mention her
individual prospects, and Cain showed she can say the right things,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just looking to go out Thursday and Friday and hit my
routines,'' she said. ''I'm not here to win the all-around. It's a
team focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Team semifinals are today, and the top three schools from two
pairings advance to Friday's team finals. Today's events also
involve the all-around meet, and UCLA coach Valorie Kondos said
Cain is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's very good, very clean and absolutely lovely to watch,''
Kondos said. ''You're not going to get any deductions out of her
form. It's only going to come from a wobble or a fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are expected to duel Michigan for the team
championship. But if either falters, there are plenty of
traditional powers ready to emerge from the 12-team field.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama has the No. 1 ranking, stemming from a national-best
score (197.3) at regionals. There's two-time defending champ
Georgia, 10-time titlist Utah and BYU, Nebraska, Oregon State, Iowa
State, Penn State, LSU and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is apparent UCLA is the most talented team,'' Alabama coach
Sarah Patterson said. ''I also know we've won three national
championships when we didn't have the most talented team. You can't
miss on an event and still win.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA set school records this season on bars, floor exercise and
vault, but fell three times on the beam at the regional meet two
weeks ago. Kondos made a point of discussing those mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told the team we could pretend it doesn't exist or we could
throw it out there and talk about it,'' she said. ''I said, 'You
can perform like you practice or you can think about it too much
and get anxious.'''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's talented team includes Heidi Moneymaker, who twice hit
10s on the vault this season, and Mohini Bhardwaj, ranked No. 2
nationally behind Cain in the all-around and the nation's top
performer on the bars.
</P>
<P>
   ''UCLA was outstanding this year,'' Utah coach Greg Marsden
said. ''It's their meet to win or lose. If they don't fall, they're
going to be very competitive, very hard to beat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
