<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USOC Boss: Slash 'Low Value' Sports  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE WILSTEIN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- No gold, silver or bronze means no green in the
bottom-line world of new U.S. Olympic Committee boss Norm Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Blake plans to push through a radical and long overdue change
this weekend that would slash the budgets of some 20 sports while
enriching traditional medal-winning powerhouses like swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Other big winners in Blake's plan are expected to be gymnastics,
figure skating, ice hockey, track and field, and boxing. The losers
would be sports like team handball, biathlon, field hockey,
weightlifting and table tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel we are accountable to making America proud, and that
comes down to the medal count,'' Blake said before presenting his
plan to the 19-member USOC executive committee on Friday. ''So we
are consciously allocating resources to that end, which means we
are taking from some to give more to others.''
</P>
<P>
   By eliminating or sharply cutting what Blake called, in the
business jargon he frequently employs, ''low value-added
programs,'' the USOC hopes to speed up the development of athletes,
improve coaching, and boost the overall haul of medals.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 45 national governing bodies of the sports the USOC
funds, including 39 Olympic NGB's, about half are going to feel
cuts, Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've employed sort of a portfolio management discipline where
we've attempted to evaluate the medal potential that each sport has
and then to critically assess the capability of that sport to
achieve the winning of those medals,'' Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC, which budgeted $160 million for grants to the NGB's
from 1997 through 2000, should not waste money on sports with a
small following in the United States and little hope of medals,
Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are certain sports that are not indigenous to the United
States, so the available feedstock of potential athletes is
limited, the amount of support available in the U.S. from a
fundraising standpoint is limited, and we are therefore
disadvantaged,'' he said. ''We have to very seriously look at what
level of support we give those particular sports.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are sports that, for all practical purposes, are not
really a concern to the American public, and the level of athletic
involvement at the grassroots level is relatively nominal. Do we
want to throw money at a sport that, frankly, would not have the
means to ever medal or to make America proud? And how much money is
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his plan would most punish the weakest sports and
essentially give up on them, Blake replied:
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel an obligation as part of the Sports Act that we need
to have a basic readiness to serve or a minimal capacity to
represent even a minor sport,'' he said. ''We feel an obligation to
make sure that that sport remains viable at some minimal level.
Very frankly, minimal level means to support a nominal amount of
overhead costs, and enough of an organization to advocate the
interests of that sport. Not much more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Each NGB will be evaluated on its own merits, he said, and some
will suffer deeper cuts than others during the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Blake knows he will hear a lot of howling from the sports that
will lose out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are we trying to make everybody happy and make sure everybody
has enough money, and field less than our best team at the games?
Because it has to come from somewhere. We're dealing with finite
resources,'' he said. ''There has to be some give-up. But the
give-up doesn't necessarily mean you close down some sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake, a 58-year-old former hotel and insurance executive with a
history of resurrecting struggling companies, became chief
executive officer and secretary general of the USOC in February
with a mandate to revitalize it. He described the new approach to
funding the national governing bodies of sports as similar to a
franchise relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC will negotiate agreements with the NGB's and provide
such things as coaching support, marketing programs, operational
assistance and bookkeeping.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the NGB will be accountable for running an efficient
operation, maintaining quality staff and training facilities,
fundraising for the sport, and making sure money gets to the
athletes and the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Each NGB also will be obligated to work with a new national
governing body, which would represent the interests of all disabled
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the past when the NGB's pretty much ran their own
show, Blake said, ''there will be strings attached'' to every
dollar the USOC gives to a sport.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to be convinced that it is a wise investment on behalf
of our sponsors and the public at large, that we are spending money
wisely to better serve the interests of our athletes and to enhance
their overall competitive performance,'' Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the USOC also will be acting like a venture
capitalist firm with the various sports, giving them seed money for
development if Blake thinks it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not always going to bat 1.000, but I'm willing to make
that investment,'' Blake said. ''But there has to be a partner
that's willing to change and look at things differently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0243 </TRAILER>
