<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dysfunctional Flyers Face Sabres  </HEADLINE>
By KEN BERGER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- John Vanbiesbrouck pondered a question about
how strange things have been for the Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did you ever see the movie 'Young Frankenstein?'''
Vanbiesbrouck asked, before comparing his chaotic team to a
character in that wacky flick.
</P>
<P>
   ''Abby Normal,'' Vanbiesbrouck said. ''That's who we are, Abby
Normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, it doesn't seem like a strange thing to hear in
this locker room. In this locker room, you never know what will
happen next.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers, who begin their first-round playoff series against
the Buffalo Sabres tonight, might as well have been taping episodes
of an afternoon talk show in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here they are, hockey's First Family of Dysfunction, sitting
nicely with the top seed in the Eastern Conference, getting ready
for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs. Remember those?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's playoff time,'' new captain Eric Desjardins said. ''Any
questions about the playoffs or Buffalo?''
</P>
<P>
   No, thanks. Not even the most important games of the year could
match the twists and turns of South Philly's longest running drama.
</P>
<P>
   This is a rematch of a 1998 series won by Buffalo in five games,
and Desjardins says the Flyers are still stewing over that loss.
It's hard to imagine how they have time to concentrate on such
things.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Sabres have problems of their own. Doug Gilmour, their
star forward, has lost 10 pounds with a stomach virus and said
Wednesday he's not sure if he'll be ready for Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a weird virus, something I've never been through in my
life,'' Gilmour said.
</P>
<P>
   But a tummy ache? There's no way that can match the Flyers'
litany of distractions, ego trips, illnesses and infighting.
</P>
<P>
   Where to begin?
</P>
<P>
   -- The Flyers are without captain -- er, former captain -- Eric
Lindros, who is not close to coming back from his fourth concussion
in two years. Even if the Flyers get past Buffalo and Lindros is
back some time in the second round, his tenure with the team he was
expected to lead to a Stanley Cup appears over.
</P>
<P>
   -- Coach Roger Neilson heroically returned from cancer treatments
ahead of schedule, but showed up at practice Tuesday to find out he
couldn't have his job back. Interim coach Craig Ramsay will run the
team for the Buffalo series.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lindros lost his captaincy to Desjardins after accusing the
club's medical staff of failing to diagnose his concussion, which
he believes occurred after a hit from Hal Gill on March 4 at
Boston. General manager Bob Clarke returned the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want the controversy,'' Clarke said Tuesday. ''We
didn't start it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one teammate, Jody Hull, urged Lindros to apologize.
Others took a pass when given a chance to defend their former
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros rejoined the team Tuesday and stood by his comments
without apologizing. More important, Lindros still is experiencing
post-concussion headaches five weeks after the injury. He cannot
return to the ice until they go away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe, without Eric Lindros, the other players can prove
that they can play even without him,'' goalie Dominik Hasek said.
</P>
<P>
   But have all the distractions made the Flyers vulnerable?
</P>
<P>
   ''They say there's turmoil coming out of Philly,'' Sabres coach
Lindy Ruff said. ''It doesn't look to me like it's affected their
hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Flyers finished the season 16-8-1 under Ramsay and
passed the slumping New Jersey Devils for the top playoff seed.
Somehow, the Flyers have managed to concentrate on playing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think people really understand who we are as a team
and what this organization is all about,'' said Ramsay, an
assistant and interim coach of the Sabres from 1984-87. ''These
guys have a wonderful ability to block it out and realize they have
a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres also have some business at hand. They're still mad
about last year's loss to Dallas in the Stanley Cup Finals on Brett
Hull's disputed goal with his foot in the crease. With Hasek
regaining his dominating form after missing 40 games with a groin
injury, the Sabres are a dangerous eighth seed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't really care,'' Hasek said. ''This is the playoffs.
You have to win four games. It doesn't matter if you finish seventh
or eighth or first. All we have to think about is the Philadelphia
Flyers and to beat them four times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
