<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres' Gilmour Feeling Better  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- No one had to remind Doug Gilmour of how
pale and weary he looked.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Sabres veteran, whose status remains in question for
tonight's playoff opener at Philadelphia because of a stomach
virus, was well aware of his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been better looking corpses, I tell you,'' said
Gilmour, who has lost 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   He skated briefly during the team's practice Wednesday, the
first time he has been on the ice since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Skating, however, is a lot different than playing and Gilmour
said his decision to play in Game 1 against the Flyers will depend
upon how he feels leading up to the opening faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to go out for a light skate today to see how my
body and my head felt,'' said Gilmour, clutching two large bottles
of nutrient drinks. ''I feel a lot better than what I did feel
like. Obviously, it's going to take some time. The next 24 hours is
very big to us.''
</P>
<P>
   His doctors have told him the virus has passed although some of
the infection lingers in his stomach. At its worst, Gilmour said
his stomach was so swollen that he had difficulty bending over.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour, who recorded 17 points in 11 games since he was
acquired by Buffalo in a deal with Chicago, has missed the Sabres'
last two games.
</P>
<P>
   After being fed fluids intravenously for four days, Gilmour said
he's managed to eat full meals -- toast and pasta -- the last two
days.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a weird virus, something I've never been through in my
life before,'' he said. ''I'd try to eat and as soon as I ate, I'd
throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour stressed his decision to play will be based on whether
he can go a full game, and not be limited to spot action.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to be responsible. You don't want to be a fault on
the ice where you're going to cause your team any kind of harm,''
he said. ''If I feel like I'm going to play, I'm going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabres coach Lindy Ruff referred to Gilmour's skate as a hopeful
sign. But he's not inserting Gilmour's name in the lineup just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really going to depend on how he feels,'' Ruff said. ''If
we feel we can get something out of him, and he feels like he's got
enough energy in a limited role, that's a possibility, yes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
