<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors say Cuban boy will benefit from family's love  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The psychological impact of going from the
relative deprivation of life in Cuba to Toys R Us and back again is
impossible to predict, but perhaps minimal in an otherwise normal
six-year-old like Elian Gonzalez, say two doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing is the love of his family. These
things are a distraction,'' Dr. Lourdes Rigual-Lynch, a Montefiore
Medical Center psychologist and pediatrics professor at Albert
Einstein College of Medicine, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think that he will know this story, but it will not be an
essential part of his being,'' added Dr. Paulina F. Kernberg, a
professor of psychiatry at Cornell University Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   The two New York experts and Dr. Jerry Wiener, professor
emeritus of psychiatry and pediatrics at George Washington
University, were hand-picked by Attorney General Janet Reno to
offer guidance on how to end the four-month crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Rigual-Lynch and Kernberg met with Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, in Washington and joined Wiener in a Miami meeting with
Lazaro Gonzalez, the father's uncle, who has had custody of Elian
since he was rescued from an inner tube in the Florida Straits last
November.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives and many others in the Cuban exile community
contend that Elian would have a better life in the United States
than under President Fidel Castro's rigid communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   All three doctors supported the Clinton administration's view,
that Elian should go home to Cuba with his father.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint interview, Rigual-Lynch and Kernberg said they found
Elian to have two ''loving families'' -- his father and stepmother
in Havana, and the extended family of paternal uncles and cousins
in the United States, and predicted that he would remain close to
both even after returning to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Rigual-Lynch and Kernberg agreed that Elian should be able to
adjust amid familiar surroundings and people in Cuba, without
pining away for his more comfortable life in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is really impressive to us, and what we did not expect to
find, was such a commitment and fondness and longing of this father
for his son,'' said Kernberg.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a father and a family that deeply cares for Elian,''
added Rigual-Lynch. ''This gives us a sense of confidence that if
he has to go back with the father, he will be able to work on
everything that has happened, and he will have a good atmosphere
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''By returning to a more settled life in Cuba he will be able to
grieve for his mother. So far there have been too many
distractions,'' Kernberg said.
</P>
<P>
   However, both doctors had kind words for the Miami relatives,
especially Lazaro Gonzalez's 21-year-old daughter Marisleysis, who
was thrust into the role of surrogate mother to the boy cousin she
had never met, and has been hospitalized for stress. ''She has been
put in the limelight and trying to do her best, but I think too
much was expected of her,'' Kernberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is understandable that he (Elian) has attached himself to
her, because she has nurtured him'' said Rigual-Lynch. ''It has
been a difficult time and I think that is something he will
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   They agreed that Elian is old enough that he would remember his
mother's death at sea, his rescue by fishermen, and even some of
the subsequent turmoil over his fate, as militant anti-Castro
members of Miami's Cuban community campaigned to prevent the U.S.
government from sending him back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said some of Elian's expatriate relatives had made
return visits to Cuba since leaving there in 1983, and it was his
great-uncle Manolo who taught Elian a prayer that he used to
sustain himself while drifting at sea.
</P>
<P>
   In a Washington interview, Wiener said Elian's Miami relatives
may believe their actions are in the boy's best interests, even
though that judgment is ''now being dominated by ideological and
political issues.''
</P>
<P>
   While relying on Chilean-born Kernberg's Spanish in the
interview with Lazaro Gonzalez, Wiener said he judged the uncle, by
his ''non-verbal'' responses, to be ''somewhat angry and
volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro, he said, was adamant that the two families could not
meet except on his terms, did not seem to understand that Elian's
return to Cuba was all but assured, and raised questions about his
nephew's fitness as a father, despite there being ''nothing that
seemed to substantiate that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was ''foolishness'' to suggest, as some have,
that Elian could be ''irreparably harmed by a family that raised
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
