<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 03:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs Federal Spending  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House lawmakers sought to fix one of the most
costly -- and emotional -- issues schools face with a $2 billion a
year guarantee to help disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   Since special education laws enacted 35 years ago, schools
nationwide have complained the federal government requires them to
educate children with disabilities without sending enough money to
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The House Education and Workforce Committee voted on a plan
Wednesday to boost the federal share of the $60 billion spent
annually on special education from 12.6 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congress made a promise to children and families with special
education needs,'' said Rep. Bill Goodling, R- Pa., committee
chairman. ''If we had kept our promise, school districts would have
the funds necessary to build new schools, hire new teachers, reduce
class size and buy new computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling said the 1975 Individual With Disabilities Act called
for a 40 percent contribution as part of its requirement that
schools educate disabled youngsters. Often, such children -- whose
disabilities range from the physical to specific problems on
learning -- were sent to institutions or remained at homes, where
they didn't get quality instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 6 million children receive special education instruction
and services.
</P>
<P>
   Schools have felt burdened by the mission. Last year, the
Supreme Court ruled that a Cedar Rapids, Iowa, school district
would have to pay the $30,000 bill for the nursing care of
paralyzed high school student on a ventilator. The National School
Boards Association estimates that 17,000 children nationwide have
such high-cost needs.
</P>
<P>
   The House panel's act, agreed to by all members by a voice vote,
may be largely symbolic. Last week, Senate lawmakers haggling over
the budget rejected a similar plan -- some feared locking the
federal government into spending that could take away flexibility
from the overall budget to pay for tax cuts. There are no immediate
plans to offer another special education spending proposal, Senate
aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But over four years, the Republican-led Congress has increased
what it spends on special education, said Joseph Karpinski,
spokesman for Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., chairman of the Senate
Health Education Labor and Pensions Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is broad support,'' he said. ''When educators come to
Washington, this is one of major issues they talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The House panel today continues its work on a slate of school
safety programs included in federal spending on elementary and
secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats say President Clinton will reject this latest
round of education lawmaking because it dilutes his priorities such
as after-school centers. Under this bill, schools could take money
marked for such programs and shift it to the school-safety programs
they prefer. For example, class-size reduction grants could be used
for character education instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 0345 </TRAILER>
