<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 03:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One dead following store shooting with cop  </HEADLINE>
By MELANIE CARROLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An off-duty police officer working security in a
Brooklyn clothing store fatally shot a teen-ager and wounded
another person after a confrontation, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at 5:48 p.m. Wednesday at the Jimmy Jazz
clothing store at Hanover Place and Fulton Street. The store's
alarm sounded when the two suspects entered the store, causing the
officer to respond, thinking it may have been a possible
shoplifting incident, said Assistant Chief Joseph Esposito, a
police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Nimrod Ollivierre, 29, confronted the suspects,
words were exchanged, and a fight ensued. At least one of the
suspects produced a weapon and gunfire was exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Ollivierre apparently shot one suspect in the chest, police
said. The suspect -- identified as Malcolm Burno, 17, of Brooklyn --
was pronounced dead at Brooklyn Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The other suspect, Claude Muller, 28, of Brooklyn, was shot in
the leg and fled in a dark-colored car, apparently after picking up
the dead suspect's gun. He was later apprehended at Bellevue
Hospital, where he had checked himself in, Esposito said.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen or more shots were fired, but it was not known how many
were fired by Ollivierre or who had fired first, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A store employee, standing in back of the store, was shot in the
leg and taken to St. Vincent's Hospital in Manhattan, where he was
in stable condition. It was not immediately clear who shot him.
</P>
<P>
   Ollivierre, who was given permission from department officials
to work at the store, sustained several facial injuries, Esposito
said. Ollivierre is assigned to the 71st Precinct in Flatbush,
Brooklyn. He has a clean record and had not been involved in any
previous shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The officer and both suspects in Wednesday's shooting are black.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking police source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said police were investigating whether the suspects were
part of a gang that sets off alarms upon entering stores. The scam
works like this, the source said: when the alarm goes off, store
employees see that the suspects have no merchandise. After
shoplifting, the suspects leave the store, setting off the alarm
again, but the store employees, believing the alarm is sounding
erroneously, allow the suspects to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a man opened fire outside the Jimmy Jazz store,
wounding eight people.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's incident was the latest shooting involving a police
officer. The shootings have sparked a public outcry in the city and
led to intense scrutiny of police practices. The U.S. Civil Rights
Commission is considering whether to recommend an independent
federal monitor to oversee the NYPD.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, four white undercover officers shot unarmed West
African immigrant Amadou Diallo on his Bronx doorstep, prompting a
month of daily protests outside police headquarters in which more
than 1,200 people were arrested, including elected officials and
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   The acquittal of those officers in February by an Albany jury
angered many who said it sent the wrong message to police. Shortly
after that verdict, another unarmed black man, Patrick Dorismond,
was fatally shot in a botched drug sting in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Many criticized Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's statements in the wake
of the Dorismond shooting. He did not express sympathy to
Dorismond's family and he and Police Commissioner Howard Safir
released the dead man's criminal record -- including a sealed
juvenile record -- as they defended the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Those actions appeared to have an impact on Giuliani's public
support, giving his U.S. Senate opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, a
boost in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Anger bubbled over into violence between civilians and officers
outside Dorismond's funeral.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 0349 </TRAILER>
