<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Hopkins Becomes U.S. Citizen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Academy Award-winning actor Anthony Hopkins has
shed his British passport and become a U.S. citizen, the Evening
Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins, 62, renounced his British citizenship during a small,
private ceremony Wednesday in Los Angeles, with director Steven
Spielberg among the show-business friends serving as his witnesses,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard said he arrived at Los Angeles' Federal Building
with his mother and his girlfriend, Francine Kay, for the
after-hours ceremony before Judge Margaret Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins, who won the best actor Oscar for ''Silence of the
Lambs,'' was knighted by Queen Elizabeth II in 1993, giving him the
right to use ''Sir'' before his name.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard said that he was required during the citizenship
ceremony to recite the words: ''I further renounce the title of
nobility to which I have heretofore belonged.''
</P>
<P>
   British Consulate officials in Los Angeles said Hopkins could
continue to use his title in Britain and would still be recognized
as a British national, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   His spokeswoman, Catherine Olim, had no comment on the
knighthood, but said Anthony is happy about the citizenship. ''I
know he has been here a long time and it seems like the right thing
to do,'' Olim said.
</P>
<P>
   As with any other candidate, Hopkins had to undergo an FBI
background check, interview with immigration officials and pass a
test on his knowledge of the United States, the Standard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
