<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Considers Rules To Help Deaf  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four years ago, as his neighbors in
Greenville, N.C., took shelter from the howling winds of Hurricane
Fran, Kevin Earp slept quietly in his bed.
</P>
<P>
   He had no idea he was in danger. He's deaf, and the local
television stations didn't provide closed captioning for the
weather broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever an anchor would come on during the programs, he would
be talking, yet there would be no captions,'' Earp later wrote to
the Federal Communications Commission. ''I did not really know due
to not being able to comprehend what the TV station meteorologists
were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   He survived, but Earp's town was part of the region later
declared a federal disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the FCC acted to ensure that hearing-disabled people such
as Earp have access to emergency information.
</P>
<P>
   The commission unanimously approved a rule requiring
broadcasters to deliver information to people with disabilities
that threaten life, health, safety and property. That can be
accomplished through real-time closed captioning, open captioning,
scrolling words or some other means.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will save lives. It's as simple as that,'' FCC Commissioner
William Kennard said in an interview Wednesday. ''We have many,
many stories of people who, for lack of this information, have
nearly lost there lives. Imagine if there's a flood, a fire, or an
earthquake, and everyone else is evacuating and you have no idea.
This is really a matter of life and death for millions of
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   FCC staff members said they were unaware of any deaths because
of a lack of closed captioning, although they didn't rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   Some broadcasters argued against live-captioning mandates,
saying some stations might shy away from comprehensive disaster
coverage if they were required to provide closed captioning for
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Although broadcasters will be allowed to deliver the information
in a variety of ways besides closed captioning, the FCC is expected
to require them to provide critical information like evacuation
routes and the location of shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule is expected to become effective in about 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Closed captioning is a form of technology like subtitles that
allows people who are deaf or hard of hearing to watch television.
But unlike subtitles, closed captioning is hidden as encoded data
transmitted in the television signal and provides information about
sound effects and background noise. A person who wants to see
closed captions must have a decoder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the commission ordered TV broadcasters to provide the
service on 100 percent of new programs by the year 2006, with a few
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the commission has instituted an incremental
transition period. Under the rules, 1,800 hours of new programming
must be closed captioned on each channel this year, 3,600 hours in
the year 2002, and 54,000 hours in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Also under the rules, 75 percent of the old programs -- those in
existence before 1998 -- must be closed captioned by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   FCC's closed captioning rules:
http://www.fcc.gov/dtf/caption.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
