<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Set To OK $1.8T Budget  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans accused Democrats today of
reverting to ''tax and spend'' ways as the GOP began pushing a
final $1.83 trillion budget through Congress calling for tax cuts,
debt reduction and extra money for defense, education and medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're trying to move us backwards,'' Rep. Mark Green,
R-Wis., said as the House moved toward a vote on the package. He
said that while Democrats prefer a ''tax and spend and spend and
tax'' philosophy, the GOP plan ''recognizes we have a
once-in-a-generation opportunity to make progress to secure
America's future, and that's what this reform budget does.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the GOP package plans excessive tax cuts that
would be paid for with harmful cuts in unspecified domestic
programs. They said that since Congress would never accept such
reductions, the budget ensures an end-of-year fiscal confrontation
with President Clinton like last year's.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're right on track,'' said Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash.
''We're going to do it all over again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The House planned to vote on the election-year measure today,
and Senate passage was expected tonight or Friday morning. That
would let the two houses complete the budget by the usually ignored
April 15 deadline for the second consecutive year, underlining the
drive by GOP leaders for Congress to adjourn early this fall for
the political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton does not have to sign the budget, which sets spending
and tax targets for fiscal 2001. But none of the subsequent 13
annual spending bills for next year, which actually provide the
money, or any tax bills will become law without his signature. It
is these measures that will become political battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan calls for at least $150 billion in tax cuts through
fiscal 2005, and up to an estimated $215 billion, depending on how
much economic growth occurs over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants $99 billion in tax cuts over the period, plus $96
billion in higher taxes on tobacco and some corporate transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, the GOP would set aside the entire Social Security
surplus -- about $1 trillion over the next five years -- to reduce
the publicly held debt. If achieved, many economists say that would
put downward pressure on interest rates and spur the economy. The
$5.7 trillion national debt includes $3.6 trillion owed to the
public and $2.1 trillion to federal trust funds, such as Social
Security's.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget also sets aside up to $40 billion over
five years for creation of prescription drug benefits for Medicare
recipients or other changes in the program. It does not, however,
require action on such a program.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said
Republicans were working on legislation that would establish new
private insurance coverage for prescriptions, with federal
subsidies for lower-income seniors and those with unusually high
prescription drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP budget calls for $311 billion for defense, or about $5
billion more than Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
   And it sets about $289 billion for many domestic programs,
roughly $30 billion less than the president proposed. That includes
proposed increases for schools, veterans and research -- which will
have to await the coming spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the budget covers interest payments on the federal
debt and automatically paid benefits like Social Security, Medicare
and Medicaid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
