<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly proposes bill to toughen punishment for sex offenders  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Sex offenders using the Internet to solicit
minors will face harsher punishment under legislation introduced by
the state Assembly to restructure the state's sex-crime statutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Predators lurk around every turn in the cyberworld, and I
think this is a very important piece of legislation,'' Assemblyman
Joseph Lentol, D-Brooklyn, chairman of the Assembly's codes
committee, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sexual Assault Reform Act would add five years to the
maximum sentence of a defendant who engaged in sex with a child
after contacting the victim through the Internet. Since 1996, the
state has had a law on the books making it a crime to use the
Internet to cruise for minors with the purpose of having sex with
them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to registering their names and addresses with law
enforcement agencies under ''Megan's Law,'' convicted sex offenders
would also have to provide any computer name or identifying
information to authorities, the Assembly proposal stated.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would require Internet service providers to give
information to all subscribers concerning availability of filters
to block access to sexual material.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said the proposed legislation
''brings us to the 21st century in terms of incorporating the
Internet and other communication technology into crimes resulting
from enticing minors for sexual activities using the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led Senate has passed Gov. George Pataki's
version of the Sexual Assault Reform Act for the past five years,
but the bill had always died in the Democratic-led Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Similarities -- such as creating a new class of offenses to
specifically punish ''date rape'' cases and boosting age limits for
statutory crimes -- exist between the two versions, but Silver said
the Assembly's bill is ''more comprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno today praised the Assembly's
move and said both sides would now work together to resolve their
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very, very interested in passing that bill,'' Bruno
said. ''I believe that we'll have to go into conference committees
and see if we can't pass it into law this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions of the Assembly's bill include:
</P>
<P>
   --Making the penalty for engaging in sex with a victim
incapacitated by drugs a Class B felony, punishable by up to 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   --Making possession of a ''date rape'' drug called ''rohypnol'' a
Class C felony punishable by up to 15 years in prison. The Assembly
bill also makes another drug, GHB, a controlled substance.
</P>
<P>
   --Authorizing hospitals performing medical examinations on sexual
assault victims to receive compensation directly from the Crime
Victims Board rather than requiring the victims to cover the
expenses and then seek reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   --Requiring designated health care facilities to institute sexual
assault examiner programs.
</P>
<P>
   --Authorizing permanent funding of rape crisis centers. Such
programs are currently funded on a year-to-year basis through the
state Health Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 1125 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 107.96; Nasdaq Up 26.90  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in another volatile session on
Wall Street today. Technology investors remained cautious after
Tuesday's steep selloff, and the Dow Jones industrials slipped due
to weakness in financial shares.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading, the Nasdaq composite index was up 26.90 at
3,796.53. The index initially lost more than 50 points, then
coasted as much as 92 points higher before slipping back.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 107.96 at 11,017.17.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 6.40 at 1,460.77.
</P>
<P>
   In a nervous market, even some good news on technology
companies' earnings failed to enliven the sector. Advanced Micro
Devices, a leading computer chip maker, said late Wednesday it
earned $1.15 a share in the first quarter, nearly twice analysts'
forecasts of 58 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro got a powerful lift, rising 6~ to 74~. The
broader semiconductor sector was higher, with LSI Logic up 2 7/16
to 63 7/16 and Texas Instruments up 5 13/16 at 144 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   But the broader technology group was mixed. Cisco Systems fell 1
7/16 to 63 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are reeling from a long, steep slide in the Nasdaq
composite, which last year posted the sharpest annual gains of any
stock market index in history. The Nasdaq has fallen 26 percent
from its peak on March 10, tumbling well into what some Wall Street
professionals consider a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop is a
growing sense that investors pushed technology stocks too far last
year, awarding many young, unproven companies valuations they did
not yet deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kerschner, chief investment strategist at PaineWebber,
said many technology stocks could see their share prices slashed by
another third before their prices are in line with their earnings
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sharp correction in the 'new new industrials' has not
fully erased their excesses,'' Kerschner said. Large-capitalization
technology stocks that have only recently gone public are most
vulnerable, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks kept the Dow lower. J.P. Morgan, which rose
Wednesday after reporting strong profit growth, fell 5 to 131 11/16
today. American Express fell 4[ to 146].
</P>
<P>
   Bank and brokerage stocks were weighed down by the latest
government report on inflation. The Labor Department's Producer
Price Index showed that wholesale prices shot up 1 percent in
March, led by the biggest jump in energy costs in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The advance was a worse showing on inflation than the 0.5
percent rise many analysts were expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 340.11 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.63 to 492.81.
</P>
<P>
   ------
