<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate to pass 'fire safe' cigarette legislation  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The leader of the state Senate announced
today that his chamber will adopt legislation approved this week by
the state Assembly that would make New York the first state to
require tobacco companies to make self-extinguishing cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel that now is the time to do it. New York can provide
leadership for the federal government,'' Senate Republican Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno said at a late-morning news conference at the
state Capitol. The legislation is to be acted on early next week by
the Republican-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The ''fire safe'' cigarette legislation was passed by the
Democratic-led state Assembly the past three years and again on
Monday, but had always failed to gain enough support in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Frank Padavan, who sponsored the Senate bill,
said with 15 Republican co-sponsors and the support of the
Democratic minority, ''there's no doubt that it will pass the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   After the bill is passed in the Senate, it would still need the
approval of Gov. George Pataki if it is to become law.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokeswoman Suzanne Morris said, ''We'll definitely take
a look'' at the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said he has spoken with Pataki and said, ''The governor
said he recognized the merits ... and he'll take a look at it when
he gets it.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of so-called ''fire safe'' cigarettes say the long,
continuous burn of most American cigarettes too often leads to
deadly fires when smokers fall asleep with them in their hands,
leave them unattended or fail to snuff them out.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters and anti-smoking groups praised the Assembly for
passing the Cigarette Fire Safety Act on Monday and today applauded
the Senate's plan to follow suit, saying the move could greatly
reduce the number of fires caused by burning cigarettes left
unattended.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know hundreds of lives of New York City residents and New
York state residents will be saved with passage of this
legislation,'' said Capt. Peter Gorman, president of the Uniformed
Fire Officers Association of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also calls for the industry to meet other
performance standards set by the state Office of Fire Prevention
and Control to limit the risk that cigarettes would ignite
household furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cigarette industry has treated this issue much like the
smoking issue,'' said state Democratic Assemblyman Alexander
Grannis, the bill's Assembly sponsor. ''They've known the problem
for a long time ... They can make a safer product and refused to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes were the leading cause of fatal fires in New York in
1997, the latest year figures were available from the state Office
of Fire Prevention and Control.
</P>
<P>
   If signed into law, the measure would go into effect April 1 the
following year. Cigarette companies would be required to stop
making non-self-extinguishing cigarettes one year after the measure
goes into force.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Philip Morris said the tobacco giant already is
working on ''cigarettes that are less likely to cause fire when
handled carelessly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to find a way to make cigarettes that are less
likely to ignite certain fabrics but also appealing for smokers,''
Brendan McCormick said. ''We think this is an issue that's best
dealt with at a federal level.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there is no such thing as ''fire safe'' cigarettes,
preferring instead to classify cigarettes according to their
''reduced ignition propensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Smith, a spokesman for Louisville-based Brown and
Williamson, agreed that self-extinguishing cigarettes don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   If such cigarettes appeared on the market, they wouldn't sell
because ''they'll go out while smoking, they won't burn.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the characteristics smokers demand,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York state government: http://www.state.ny.us/
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris: http://www.philipmorris.com
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson: http://www.brownandwilliamson.com
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco Products Liability Project: http://www.tobacco.neu.edu
</P>
