<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religion News in Brief  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- After posting its first membership loss
since 1926, the Southern Baptist Convention has reported an
increase of 122,400 for 1999. The new membership figure --
15,851,756 -- remains a bit below the 1997 total.
</P>
<P>
   The convention is America's largest Protestant body and a
bellwether for conservative Protestant trends.
</P>
<P>
   The denomination said the 419,342 baptisms for 1999 exceeded
1998 and 1997 totals. Sunday School enrollment was down 482 for the
year, to 8,147,457. Total giving rose 5.4 percent, to $7.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The denomination faces continued tension from those dissatisfied
with its rightward direction. This week the 800-member First
Baptist Church of Athens, Ga., part of the denomination since its
1845 founding, voted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The church said it believes in the personal autonomy of members,
while the national denomination ''appeared to favor increased
pastoral authority.'' It maintains membership in the Cooperative
Baptist Fellowship, a group of 1,800 moderate congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.sbc.net.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Lutheran leaders act on Episcopal pact, homosexual issues
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Leaders of the 5.2 million-member Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America have decided to press ahead on a unity
pact with the Episcopal Church, despite some opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Church Council, which sets policy between sessions of the
Lutherans' national assembly, also asked the denominational staff
to consider whether exceptions should be allowed to a 1990 ban on
clergy same-sex behavior and report back in November. The issue
arose when the St. Paul, Minn., region requested a waiver for a
lesbian clergy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The council rejected a separate proposal for a study on whether
to ordain gay and lesbian clergy who are not committed to celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   Though the latter study -- under consideration since the idea was
proposed last year to the assembly -- was scuttled, the council
called for ''deliberate, and prayerful conversations'' through 2003
on the inclusion of gays and lesbian in church life.
</P>
<P>
   On Episcopal Church relations, the council directed that a
comprehensive unity pact approved by last year's assembly go into
effect next Jan. 1 if the Episcopal Church gives its assent at a
July convention. Lutheran opponents of the pact had asked for
delay.
</P>
<P>
   The council also stated that regional units are not free to
accept or reject parts of the Episcopal pact, as opponents had
requested. There could be further discussions about bypassing rules
on clergy ordination ''in unusual circumstances and with
appropriate consultation,'' the council said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, who say the pact violates Lutheran tradition by
following the Episcopal concept of bishops, met March 26-29 to
organize the WordAlone Network.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Evangelical Lutheran Church in America:
www.elca.org. WordAlone Network: www.wordalone.org.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Study proposes changing religious oath for future British monarchs
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A forthcoming report commissioned by the British
government will propose that future monarchs no longer be required
to swear allegiance to the Protestant faith, the Daily Telegraph
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The government confirmed that it had authorized a study by Derby
University professors concerning official treatment of British
religions, but said no recommendations had yet been given to Home
Secretary Jack Straw.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the reigning monarch is head of the Church of
England and Catholics are not allowed to succeed to the throne or
to marry a monarch.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said the report would also put on the national
agenda the elimination of the Church of England as the official
state religion, a status it has held since King Henry VIII broke
with Roman Catholicism in the 16th century.
</P>
<P>
   The academic report was quoted as saying the primacy of the
established church represents a ''historically rooted religious
disadvantage'' to other faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Oklahoma legislator defends amendment on God
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The state lawmaker who wrote an amendment
requiring public school science texts to acknowledge God said that
if a majority of voters in his district didn't agree, ''it would
boggle my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Jim Reese, a Republican and a Methodist, filed
the amendment that would require all books adopted by the state
textbook committee to include ''acknowledgment that human life was
created by one God of the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese said he believes the amendment would aid family welfare
and send a message to textbook publishers. He favors equal
treatment for evolution and the concept that humanity was created
suddenly by God instead of evolving from more primitive life forms.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want publishers to know that the public is not happy with
their textbooks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Attorney General Drew Edmondson has said the textbook
committee did not have the authority last year to require the
publishers to put a disclaimer in science textbooks referring to
evolution as a controversial and unproven theory.
</P>
<P>
   Reese's amendment will probably be sent to a conference
committee with the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Second student sues school that banned Wicca symbol
</P>
<P>
   ELWOOD, Ind. (AP) -- The Indiana Civil Liberties Union said a
second student has joined a lawsuit against Elwood High School over
its ban on wearing pentagrams, a symbol of the Wiccan religion.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Shauntee Chaffin is enrolled in the same ''cadet
teaching'' program as the original plaintiff, Brandi Lehman, 17,
who sued the schools in March for not allowing her to wear a
pentagram necklace.
</P>
<P>
   School officials ordered Lehman to remove the necklace when she
participates in a student teaching program at an elementary school.
An interim agreement allows Lehman to wear the jewelry to school,
but not while student-teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Chaffin, who also practices Wicca and wears a similar necklace,
contacted the civil liberties union for help after being subpoenaed
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Lehman, Brandi's father, said she had received
expressions of support since the suit became known. ''Many teachers
and coaches have told her they support her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wicca or Neo-Paganism is a modern variant of nature worship that
reached public notice with Gerald Gardner's ''Witchcraft Today''
(1954).
</P>
<P>
