   ------
Ignoring bishop's order, nun speaks in Nebraska
</P>
<P>
   CAMP KITAKI, Neb. (AP) -- Despite being forbidden by the local
bishop to speak in his diocese, Sister Jeannine Gramick told a
group of Nebraska Catholics they should have the right to weigh
deeply held personal convictions against the church's official
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one has the right to intrude on your conscience,'' Gramick
told 60 people at a meeting of Call to Action Nebraska, which seeks
church reforms. ''No one has a right to invade that sacred space
between you and God.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Vatican banned Gramick from ministering to gays
and lesbians because of her liberal views.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Fabian Bruskewitz of the Lincoln diocese wrote Gramick
saying he had Vatican authority to forbid her to speak. But canon
lawyers advised Gramick the bishop could not prevent her speech as
long as she did not violate the ban on homosexual ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Bruskewitz drew national attention in 1996 when he said
Catholics in the diocese who did not quit Call to Action and 11
other groups would be excommunicated. The excommunication directive
is still in force.
</P>
<P>
   ------
New Jersey Jewish leaders concerned about Christian missionaries
</P>
<P>
   ABERDEEN, N.J. (AP) -- Reform Rabbi Laurence Malinger has met
with congregants to warn them that missionaries known as Jewish
Christians, Hebrew Christians or Jews for Jesus are gaining more
converts from Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only New Jersey Jewish leader concerned about the
evangelical groups' activity. At the Marlboro Jewish Center, Rabbi
George Schlesinger has invited speakers and scheduled discussion
sessions at the Conservative synagogue's school. Educating members
has become a priority, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Goldstein, director of the New Jersey region of the
American Jewish Congress, said those most vulnerable to conversion
are Jews who do not attend synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   There were an estimated 10,000 Jewish Christians in 1978
compared with 350,000 today, mainly in the United States, according
to Mark Powers of Jews for Judaism, an advocacy group that counters
the missionaries. He said Jewish Christians have 400 U.S.
congregations and 100 in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League provides a more conservative estimate
of 100,000 U.S. converts.
</P>
<P>
   ''In just about every Jewish community, this is a problem,''
Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   Malinger told his congregation, ''I'm not talking about Roman
Catholics, Episcopalians, Methodists, or mainline Christianity. I'm
not talking about 90 percent of the general Christian population.
I'm talking about fundamental Christians who use Jews as a primary
target.''
</P>
