<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 76.86; Nasdaq Up 72.98  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology investors, chastened after three days
of steep losses, went cautiously back into the stock market today,
but blue chips fell after a spike in wholesale inflation raised new
fears about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading, the Nasdaq composite index was up 72.98 at
3,842.61. The index again fluctuated, having slipped more than 50
points at the start of trading before moving higher. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 76.86 at 11,048.27.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were improving after early declines.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 2.97 at 1,470.14.
</P>
<P>
   Some good news on technology companies' earnings helped lend
support to the shaky sector. Advanced Micro Devices, a leading
computer chip maker, said late Wednesday it earned $1.15 a share in
the first quarter, nearly twice analysts' forecasts of 58 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro got a powerful lift, rising 7 1/16 to 75 1/16.
The broader semiconductor sector was higher, with LSI Logic up 2
7/16 to 63 7/16 and Texas Instruments up 6 1/16 at 145 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   But the broader technology group was mixed. Cisco Systems fell 1
7/16 to 63 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are reeling from a long, steep slide in the Nasdaq
composite, which last year posted the sharpest annual gains of any
stock market index in history. The Nasdaq has fallen more than 25
percent from its peak of 5,048.62 on March 10, tumbling well into
what some Wall Street professionals consider a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop is a
growing sense that investors pushed technology stocks too far last
year, awarding many young, unproven companies valuations they did
not yet deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kerschner, chief investment strategist at PaineWebber,
said many technology stocks could see their share prices slashed by
another third before they are in line with their earnings
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sharp correction in the 'new new industrials' has not
fully erased their excesses,'' Kerschner said. Large-capitalization
technology stocks that have only recently gone public are most
vulnerable, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks kept the Dow lower. J.P. Morgan, which rose
Wednesday after reporting strong profit growth, fell 3 11/16 to 133
today. American Express fell 4 15/16 to 145 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and brokerage stocks were weighed down by the latest
government report on inflation. The Labor Department's Producer
Price Index showed that wholesale prices shot up 1 percent in
March, led by the biggest jump in energy costs in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The advance was a worse showing on inflation than the 0.5
percent rise many analysts were expecting.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony today before the Senate Banking Committee, Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan dismissed charges that the Fed has
tried to drive the stock market lower by boosting interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have denied and I continue to deny that our job is to
jawbone the stock market; it is not,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 482.47 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.25 to 495.69.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
