<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BBC Assembles New Copperfield Crew  </HEADLINE>
By MARCUS ELIASON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''No cameo parts in Dickens, they're all gems,''
the actor Laurence Olivier once wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier knew what he was talking about. The great man himself
played a small role as Creakle, the headmaster, in the 1970 film of
''David Copperfield.'' W.C. Fields had already played Micawber in
the 1935 Hollywood version.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as if to bear out Olivier's observation, the BBC has
assembled the cream of British theater in an array of cameos --
sorry, gems -- for yet another delightful ''David Copperfield,''
airing on PBS in two parts Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   There's Oscar-winner Maggie Smith as David's redoubtable aunt,
Betsey Trottwood; and Ian McKellen (''Gods and Monsters'') as
Creakle, all spindly, wheezing malevolence; and Micawber in the
rotund shape of Bob Hoskins, who these days turns up everywhere
from Showtime (as Manuel Noriega) to TNT as (Sancho Panza) to
moviehouses (as a serial killer in ''Felicia's Journey'').
</P>
<P>
   And then there's a whole army of talent recognizable to the
''Masterpiece Theater'' crowd: Nicholas Lyndhurst, transformed from
his usual chirpy-Cockney persona into the oily schemer Uriah Heep;
Trevor Eve (''Heat of the Sun'') as David's tyrannical stepfather,
Mr. Murdstone; Zoe Wanamaker, a breathtaking ''Electra'' on
Broadway last year, as Murdstone's viperish sister.
</P>
<P>
   This is the BBC's fifth ''David Copperfield'' for television,
and give or take a few plot alterations, it covers all the
traditional terrain in lavish period costume and location shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The story: David (played as a youth by the angelic but never
cloying Daniel Radcliffe) is raised in rural bliss by his sickly
widowed mother (Emilia Fox) and the faithful family maid, Clara
Peggotty (Pauline Quirke). But the idyll ends suddenly when
Murdstone marries David's mother, fires Peggotty and ships David
off first to the sadistic Creakle's school, then to a nightmare job
in a shoe polish factory.
</P>
<P>
   David runs away to his Aunt Betsey, who takes him in. A new life
begins for the hapless boy. Grown up (and stalwartly portrayed in
part two by Ciaran McMenamin), he becomes a reporter, falls in
love, marries the wrong girl, inadvertently brings tragedy upon the
Peggotty family in a memorable disaster at sea, foils Heep's
dastardly scheme to bankrupt his friend Agnes' father, realizes
that Agnes is his true love, marries her and lives happily ever
after. Phew!
</P>
<P>
   From its beguilingly artless opening (''Chapter 1: I am born'')
to the heaving pathos of its final sentence (''O Agnes, O my
soul...'') ''David Copperfield'' is widely regarded as the most
autobiographical of Dickens' 14 novels. Dickens himself hinted as
much, and called it his ''favorite child.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Dickens-lover has a favorite child, be it ''Bleak House,''
''The Pickwick Papers,'' ''Oliver Twist'' or ''Nicholas Nickleby.''
But ''David Copperfield'' contains many of Dickens' most memorable
lines and characters, and the new production faithfully preserves
them:
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Aunt Betsey to her enchantingly loopy cousin, Mr.
Dick, when a ragged, starving David turns up on her doorstep:
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Dick, ... what shall I do with this child?''
</P>
<P>
   Pause.
</P>
<P>
   ''Have him measured for a suit of clothes directly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Dick..., give me your hand, for your common sense is
invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the ever-impecunious Mr. Micawber's financial advice to
David: ''Annual income twenty pounds, annual expenditure nineteen
and six -- result, happiness. Annual income twenty pounds, annual
expenditure twenty pounds ought and six -- result, misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Barkis the cart driver delivering his famously terse proposal
of marriage to Clara Peggotty: ''Barkis is willin'.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard, in the TV-jaded consumer culture of today, to
imagine the impact the written or recited word had on Victorian
audiences. At cliffhanger junctures of Dickens' serializations,
crowds would gather in American harbors to await the ships bringing
the latest chapters. In Britain and America his public readings
made audiences weep with sorrow or laughter. Ralph Waldo Emerson
heard a reading in Boston and laughed so hard he felt he would
''crumble to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   When the author died in 1870, aged 58, the historian Thomas
Carlyle eulogized him as ''The good, the gentle, high-gifted,
ever-friendly, noble Dickens -- every inch of him an Honest Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Today Dickens' popularity in English culture is second only to
Shakespeare's. The names Heep, Micawber, Gradgrind, Pecksniff and
Fagin have become part of the language. And an author dead for 130
years continues to enrich us with gems.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   on the Net: http://www.fidnet.com/(tilde)dap1955/dickens
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   CYNICAL BILL: Bill Maher returns to HBO for a stand-up comedy
special, the network has announced. To be televised live June 10
from the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts in San Francisco, ''Bill
Maher: Be More Cynical'' will mark the third hour-long HBO special
by the star of ABC's late-night ''Politically Incorrect.'' Topics
are expected to include the male-centered viewpoint of rap music,
the hypocrisy of senators suing tobacco companies, and the
Clintons' marriage bed.
</P>
</TEXT>
