<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb's profit jumps 59 percent to $23.9 million  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Robust sales of eye-surgery products and
disposable contact lenses drove Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc.'s profit up 59
percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding a $15.2 million gain from a patent dispute with rival
Alcon Laboratories, the world's biggest eye-care company said
Thursday its earnings from continuing operations were $23.9
million, or 42 cents a share, up from $15 million, or 26 cents a
share, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The results edged Wall Street analysts' expectations of 41 cents
a share, according to First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 4 percent to $406.9 million from $389.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   When the litigation gain and $7.4 million from discontinued
operations are included, Bausch &AMP; Lomb posted a net profit of $39.1
million, or 68 cents a share, up from $22.4 million, or 39 cents a
share, in the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Double-digit growth of SofLens66 and PureVision extended-wear
contact lenses helped boost lens sales by 8 percent in the quarter,
but that was offset by a 6-percent drop in sales of lens-care and
vision-accessories products.
</P>
<P>
   Propelled by double-digit growth in sales of refractive surgery
products, its surgical segment revenues jumped 14 percent over last
year. Pharmaceutical sales rose 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb is in the midst of a hostile effort to take
control of Wesley Jessen VisionCare Inc., which controls about
two-thirds of the highly profitable cosmetic color-lens market. On
April 3, it launched a tender offer for all outstanding shares of
the Des Plaines-based company.
</P>
<P>
   If it takes control of Wesley Jessen, Bausch &AMP; Lomb will have
combined contact-lens revenues approaching $800 million. That would
put it within distance of market leader Johnson &AMP; Johnson, which
had about $900 million in contact-lens revenues in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb has been refocusing in recent years on eye care --
contact lenses, ophthalmic drugs, and eye surgery instruments -- by
selling its animal-research and hearing-aid businesses and a
sunglasses division that included the famed Ray-Ban brand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
