<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed marginally higher Thursday,
dragged down by a faltering technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares had dropped sharply at the start of trading,
as the U.S.-based Nasdaq Stock Market struggled to recover from its
plunge the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   Shares rallied a bit, however, as the Nasdaq recouped in early
U.S. trading.
</P>
<P>
   British Telecommunications gained 44 pence, or 4.0 percent, to
1,133 pence, after the company announced long-awaited restructuring
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone Airtouch continued to gain after the European Union
Commission gave conditional approval Wednesday for the company's
takeover of Germany's Mannesmann. Vodafone shares ended up 11
pence, or 3.5 percent, at 323.5 pence, with 330 million shares
traded, or over one-fifth of total FTSE 100 volume.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index closed up 2.1 points at
5,181.3.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell
0.12 points to 384.84, while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index rose 10.5
points to 4,951.4 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, ended down 0.04 points
at 430.79.
</P>
<P>
   In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100 Share Index rose 6.2
points, or 0.1 percent, to 6,357.0.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the CAC 40 closed up 25.64 points or 0.4 percent at
6,264.34 points.
</P>
<P>
   French food group Danone was the CAC's main gainer, with a rise
of 9.3 euros, or 3.8 percent, to 254.8 euros on the news it is in
talks with Japan's Yakult Honsha about an alliance and a number of
positive reports from brokerage houses.
</P>
<P>
   In Milan, the blue-chip MIB30 index gained 0.2 percent, or 110
points, to close at 45,534, while the overall Mibtel index rose 0.2
percent, or 55 points, to 30,894.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index rose 5.99 points to end at 7,449.06.
</P>
</TEXT>
