<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs $1.83 Trillion Budget  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a swipe at President Clinton and his
Democratic allies, Republicans pushed through the House today a
final $1.83 trillion budget for next year that calls for tax cuts,
debt reduction and extra money for defense, education and medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the measure on a near party-line 220-208 vote,
setting up likely final approval by the Senate later in the day.
Clinton does not have to sign the plan, which sets spending and tax
targets for fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the subsequent 13 annual spending bills which
actually provide the money, or any tax bill, will become law
without the president's signature. With Republicans planning deeper
tax cuts and less spending than Democrats prefer, the election-year
battle lines were already clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who would like to spend more are not keeping their eye
on the target: balancing the budget, paying down debt, protecting
Social Security,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The House Budget Committee chairman, Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio,
the budget's chief author, said Clinton considers the plan's tax
cuts too big because he ''thinks we should take our paychecks and
send it all to the government.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said the GOP plan contained skewed priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a speech to the American Society of Newspaper
Editors, said the Republican budget was ''loaded with exploding tax
breaks and untenable cuts in critical investments.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''We cannot afford to veer from the proven path onto a
trail of unmet obligations, unrealistic cuts and unnecessary
giveaways. We can't squander the moment by squandering the
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the House floor, Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, said,
''Any way you want to cut it, the center piece of this budget is a
massive tax cut at the expense of debt reduction, Social Security,
agriculture and defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate approval would let Congress complete the budget by the
usually ignored April 15 deadline for the second consecutive year,
underlining the drive by GOP leaders to let lawmakers go home early
this fall for the political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan calls for at least $150 billion in tax cuts through
fiscal 2005, and up to an estimated $215 billion, depending on how
much economic growth occurs over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants $99 billion in tax cuts over the period, plus $96
billion in higher taxes on tobacco and some corporate transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, the GOP would set aside the entire Social Security
surplus -- about $1 trillion over the next five years -- to reduce
the publicly held debt. If achieved, many economists say that would
put downward pressure on interest rates and spur the economy. The
$5.7 trillion national debt includes $3.6 trillion owed to the
public and $2.1 trillion to federal trust funds, such as Social
Security's.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget also sets aside up to $40 billion over
five years for creation of prescription drug benefits for Medicare
recipients or other changes in the program. It does not, however,
require action on such a program.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Hastert said Republicans were working on
legislation that would establish new private insurance coverage for
prescriptions, with federal subsidies for lower-income seniors and
those with unusually high prescription drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP budget calls for $311 billion for defense, or about $5
billion more than Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
   And it sets about $289 billion for many domestic programs,
roughly $30 billion less than the president proposed. That includes
proposed increases for schools, veterans and research -- which will
have to await the coming spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the budget covers interest payments on the federal
debt and automatically paid benefits like Social Security, Medicare
and Medicaid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1327 </TRAILER>
