<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Threats Hit Army Depot  </HEADLINE>
By AMALIE YOUNG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERMISTON, Ore. (AP) -- Bomb threats have stopped construction
nine times in the past six weeks at an Army depot where workers are
building an incinerator to destroy millions of pounds of deadly
chemical weapons stored at the base.
</P>
<P>
   No bombs have been found. The FBI and Army authorities have
declined to comment on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers at the Umatilla Chemical Depot said they are mostly
unfazed, worrying less about a leak of nerve agents than about the
loss of pay.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure that there are some that are scared. And if they
found that guy, he'd be lucky to get off that site,'' electrician
Joe Vandecar said. ''But as far as feeling threatened, no, no, not
a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Feb. 28, nine threats have been called in or been
broadcast over two-way radios used at the site. Each time,
construction has been halted, with workers briefly evacuated to a
safe area or sent home for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to take them all seriously,'' said Lt. Col. Thomas
Woloszyn, who oversees operations at the depot.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1,000 or so electricians, carpenters and other hourly
workers, the time has meant money -- 40 hours' worth.
</P>
<P>
   The depot, near the Columbia River that forms the
Oregon-Washington state line, holds about 220,000 munitions and
containers filled with 7.4 million pounds of deadly nerve and
mustard gas agents -- about 12 percent of the nation's stockpile of
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The incinerator is about two-thirds complete and is scheduled to
be finished next year. Woloszyn said it is not clear if the threats
have pushed back the completion date.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon Demilitarization Co., which is supervising
construction, an electrical subcontractor and two union groups are
offering a $30,000 reward for information about the threats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
