<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reading Methods Fighting Criticized  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The best way to teach children how to read is
not to fight over the best way to do it, a national panel of
reading teachers, parents and college instructors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's report sought to quell the dispute over two basic
reading methods -- phonics or whole language. It endorsed neither as
the only way. Instead, it said beginning-reading instruction should
take the best from both: Children should start learning to sound
out letters and words, but also build their vocabularies early.
</P>
<P>
   In whole language, students learn the meaning of words through
the context in which they are used. Phonics teaches students how to
read through sound and letter drills. Reading advocates and
lawmakers Thursday praised the report for helping teachers wade
through a morass of reading research and theories.
</P>
<P>
   ''Teachers have been barraged with conflicting information,''
said Rep. Anne Northup, R-Ky., who wrote the 1997 law establishing
the 14-member panel. ''A six year old is only six once. If we don't
reach these youngsters now, we can't come back 15 years and make it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley said the report's findings
provide ''further evidence that the reading wars are over.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been fueled by dismal test scores showing that
two-thirds of U.S. fourth graders can't read at the level expected.
Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., said he would seek federal funds to
help children who still can't read after third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Many teachers support whole language because they say it
emphasizes creative writing and immerses children in literature.
Critics say students are not provided the tools to understand what
they read. These building blocks are provided by phonics, they
maintain.
</P>
<P>
   But the dispute is sure to continue on the political front.
Normally debated only in school board elections, the dispute over
how children should be taught to read is now being discussed on the
presidential campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush, in campaign ads
against Vice President Al Gore, cites the use of phonics as a major
educational accomplishment. And in Indiana, Republican
gubernatorial candidate John Price has promised to require all
schools in the state to use phonics when teaching reading to young
children.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen states specifically tell their schools to teach
phonics or other methods such as whole language, said Richard M.
Long, of the International Reading Association. But half of the
state constitutions prevent state lawmakers from getting that
involved in how local schools teach children, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reading advocates will help by posting the information on web
sites and hosting public forums, said Andrew Hartman, director of
the National Institute for Literacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Expecting people to read big, thick reports is unrealistic,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Reading Panel: http://www.nationalreadingpanel.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
