<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Passes Cockfighting Bill  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House subcommittee Thursday unanimously
passed legislation to ban the shipment of birds for cockfighting
across state lines, bringing supporters one step closer to closing
a loophole in federal law.
</P>
<P>
	   ''The public's behind this,'' said Rep. Collin Peterson, the
pro-hunting Minnesota Democrat who sponsored the bill.
</P>
<P>
	   The legislation would prevent birds from the 47 states where
cockfighting is illegal from being shipped to the states where it
is still legal -- New Mexico, Oklahoma and Louisiana. Peterson said
that state law enforcement officials have complained that the
loophole makes it difficult to enforce their own states'
cockfighting bans.
</P>
<P>
	   With little discussion, the House Agriculture Committee's
livestock and horticulture subcommittee approved the bill, paving
the way for a vote by the full committee. The Senate Agriculture
Committee has already approved similar legislation sponsored by
Congress' only veterinarian, Wayne Allard, R-Colo.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents had tried to block the vote, acknowledging that it was
difficult for members to oppose the bill. Cockfighting matches
blade-wearing birds in what is often a death match, and spectators
often bet on which bird will win.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Behind the scenes there are people that have concerns about
this bill,'' Peterson said. ''But as you can see here today, nobody
wants to go on record against it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Former Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, who has been hired to lobby
against the bill by the cockfighting industry, said he would now
focus on the full committee.
</P>
<P>
	   ''What we have to do is make members realize that they are
falling into the trap of elitists in Washington knowing what's best
for people around the country,'' said Symms, adding that the
legislation would put ''honest game breeders'' out of business.
</P>
<P>
	   ''If that bill becomes law, then the forces behind the bill
would start in on circuses, rodeos, and dog races, which are also
sporting events which use animals for the entertainment of the
public.''
</P>
<P>
	   He called the bill ''a test of states rights.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Peterson, the subcommittee's top Democrat, said he had a
quick answer to members who had lobbied him not to bring the bill
up for a vote: ''If you want to have cockfighting, if you want to
have your people in this business, then go to your state
legislature and change the law.''
</P>
<P>
	   Peterson, the co-chairman of the Congressional Sportsmen's
Caucus, was asked by the Humane Society of the United States to
sponsor the bill to counter arguments that the legislation was part
of an aggressive animal rights campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Cockfighting information: http://www.paulniteowl.com/birds/
</P>
<P>
   Humane Society: http://www.hsus.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
