<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Meets Gay Republicans  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Emerging from a meeting with gay
Republicans, George W. Bush today declared he was ''a better
person'' for hearing their stories although he said they still
disagree on such subjects as gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Former presidential contender Gary Bauer, however, warned that
Bush was risking losing conservative support to third-party
candidate Pat Buchanan. He said one idea broached at the meeting --
having a gay speaker at this summer's Republican National
Convention -- would go over ''like a lead balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be bizarre to pick somebody to speak at the
convention based on their sexual preference, because once you go
down that road, why don't you pick a transvestite?'' Bauer told The
Associated Press in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   After his meeting, Bush declared: ''I welcome gay Americans into
my campaign.'' While reaffirming that he opposes gay marriage, a
position important to his conservative Republican base, Bush
preferred to focus on the simple fact that he had met with the
gays.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important for the next president to listen to people's
real-life stories,'' Bush told reporters at a news conference at
his Texas headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are people from our neighborhoods, people with whom all
of us went to school,'' Bush said. ''I appreciate them sharing
their stories with me. I'm mindful that we're all God's children.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the primaries, the Texas governor has been trying to
moderate his political image after his appeals to religious
conservatives helped him win in South Carolina in February.
</P>
<P>
   But that shift to the center is raising a new concern: that Bush
might alienate those same conservatives with any concession to
homosexuals, who tend to support Democrats. Exit polling in the
1998 congressional elections found that voters who said they were
gay identified themselves as Democrats much more often than as
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group that met with Bush today said they were
pleased by their hour-long session.
</P>
<P>
   ''The goal was not to change his mind. It was to start a
conversation,'' said Steve Gunderson, a gay former Republican
congressman from Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   David Catania, a Republican city councilman from Washington,
said, ''We went in with the hope and expectation that we would
raise his consciousness on certain issues. We think we've done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush ''was very interested in the idea'' of having a gay speaker
at the Republican National Convention, Catania said. The discussion
centered on the possibility that Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., might be
that speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference Bush also:
</P>
<P>
   -- Confirmed reports that he planned to meet with his former
chief rival, Arizona Sen. John McCain, on May 9 in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   -- Criticized the Clinton administration for its handling of the
Elian Gonzalez case. He said the administration had succumbed to
publicity and pressure from Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   -- Responded to criticism from his Democratic rival, Vice
President Al Gore, that Bush's health record in Texas and his
recently announced health care plan amount to ''political
malpractice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ''This is a good plan and yet rather debating merits,
the way this man wants to run his campaign is to say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the meeting with the gay Republicans, social
conservatives had said they would reserve judgment, partly because
Bush's campaign had assured them he would stay true to his core
conservative beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Others expressed some concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the meeting that's the problem, it's what he says
when he gets there,'' said Janet Parshall, a spokeswoman for the
Family Research Council in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabin Republicans, an organization for gays, has
pressured the presumed Republican presidential nominee to take a
stand on such issues as gay marriage. Bush has shunned the group
and was criticized for it during the presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Before today's meeting, some of those who planned to attend said
it was a good first step.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to be talking about who we are and what it's like
to be gay and get a greater understanding of who we are and the
issues that we face,'' said Carl Schmid of the Human Rights
Campaign, a gay political organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Huch, a gay activist from northern Virginia, said, ''If we
come out of that meeting at a minimum and have Bush say, 'This is a
good conversation ... I expect to learn more,' considering where
this party has been in the past on gay and lesbian issues, I think
that is a tremendous step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was arranged by Charles Francis, a gay public
relations executive in Washington whose brother, James Francis Jr.,
is a Bush fund-raiser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1502 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
