<DOCNO> APW20000413.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Thursday, April 13, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   BP Amoco, Arco Merger Approved
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission today approved BP
Amoco's $27.6 billion purchase of Atlantic Richfield Co., after the
company agreed to sell large oil holdings in Alaska. The merger
will create one of the world's largest oil companies. The approval
requires BP Amoco to sell all of Atlantic Richfield's oil holdings
in Alaska within 30 days to resolve anticompetitive problems. The
FTC had opposed the merger because of concern that the combination,
without such a divestitures, would be able to dominate the West
Coast oil market. BP Amoco already tentatively has agreed to sell
Arco's holdings to Philips Petroleum Co.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Up 37.26; Dow Down 105.48
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology investors, chastened after three days
of steep losses, went cautiously back into the stock market today,
but blue chips fell after a spike in wholesale prices raised new
fears about the economy. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Nasdaq
composite index was up 37.26 at 3,806.89. The index again
fluctuated, having slipped more than 50 points at the start of
trading before moving higher. The Dow Jones industrial average was
down 105.48 at 11,019.65.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EDT:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The biggest rise in energy costs in nearly 10
years led wholesale prices up 1.0 percent in March, the government
reported today. The advance in the Labor Department's Producer
Price Index was a worse showing on inflation than the 0.5 percent
rise many analysts were expecting. The jolt came from a 5.8 percent
gain in energy prices, the sharpest rise since a 7.5 percent
increase posted in October 1990. But outside the volatile energy
and food categories, the ''core'' rate of inflation at the
wholesale level rose a tiny 0.1 percent. Meanwhile, the Commerce
Department reported that retail sales in March were up 0.4 percent,
compared to a 1.1 percent rise in February.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Stands by Rate Hikes
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
today that the market's wild swings in recent days ''are reflecting
the basic underlying forces'' of sharply different rates of return
on high-technology stocks compared with more traditional ones. ''I
think what's happening is that the markets are groping for the
correct balance underlying the system,'' Greenspan told the Senate
Banking Committee. In response to a question, the central bank
chief denied that the dramatic losses in the technology-heavy
Nasdaq index in recent days were caused by the Fed's policy of
raising interest rates. ''I have denied and I continue to deny
''that our job is to jawbone the stock market; it is not,''
Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   IMF Official Defends Globalization
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- International Monetary Fund and Clinton
administration officials today defended their efforts to promote
freer trade and greater integration of the global economy. They
said such steps offered the best hope of lifting hundreds of
millions of people out of abject poverty. Globalization -- the bane
of thousands of demonstrators in the nation's capital this week who
contend that global capitalism has failed to help the poor -- has
gotten a bad rap, said acting IMF Managing Director Stanley
Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   First Union Reports 13 Percent Drop
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE (AP) -- First Union said today that profits slumped 13
percent in the first quarter as fee income declined and costs rose
at the nation's sixth-largest bank. Operating profits, which
exclude merger-related costs, totaled $838 million, or 85 cents a
share, meeting Wall Street's lowered expectations. That compares
with operating earnings of $965 million, or $1 a share, for the
first quarter last year. Including charges for First Union's
acquisition of CoreStates Financial two years ago, net income
totaled $840 million, or 85 cents a share, compared with $706
million, or 73 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   GM Earns $1.78B in First Quarter
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. earned $1.78 billion in the
first quarter, down 2 percent from a year ago. The results still
beat Wall Street expectations. The world's largest automaker said
today it earned $2.80 a share, in the January-March period compared
to $1.82 billion, or $2.68 a share last year. Earnings per share
increased because fewer shares of GM are on the market now than a
year ago. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial
expected earnings of $2.66 a share in the latest quarter. Revenues
totaled $46.9 billion, a 10 percent increase over $42.4 billion in
the same quarter in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   World Online Chairwoman Resigns
</P>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- World Online chairwoman Nina Brink
resigned today shortly after a shareholders group announced a
lawsuit over the Internet service provider's disappointing initial
public offering. A company statement said Brink took the decision
''in the interests of the company.'' Investors had called on Brink
to resign after World Online's share price fizzled following the
March 17 initial public offering and the chief's admission she
divested most of her equity in December. World Online shares jumped
2.7 percent to finish the day at 18.85 euros ($18.10) after the
resignation was announced about 15 minutes before the close of
trading. The price was still less than half the offering price of
43 euros ($41.30).
</P>
<P>
   European Bank Hints at Rate Hike
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The European Central Bank kept key
interest rates steady today but dropped several warnings about
Europe's fragile economic recovery and hinted a rate hike is around
the corner. ECB President Wim Duisenberg said ongoing labor
negotiations throughout the 11 countries using Europe's common
currency, the euro, could spur inflation if unions push through
excessive wage increases. He said inflation could also snowball if
the euro doesn't gain value against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Higher
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed marginally higher today,
dragged down by a faltering technology sector. Shares rallied a
bit, however, as the Nasdaq in New York recouped in early U.S.
trading. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies
fell 0.12 points to 384.84 and the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index ended
down 0.04 points at 430.79. In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100
Share Index rose 6.2 points, or 0.1 percent, to 6,357.0. In Paris,
the CAC 40 closed up 25.64 points or 0.4 percent at 6,264.34
points. In Milan, the blue-chip MIB30 index gained 0.2 percent, or
110 points, to close at 45,534, while the overall Mibtel index rose
0.2 percent, or 55 points, to 30,894.
</P>
<P>
   Three-Way Aluminum Co. Deal Nixed
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France's Pechiney SA , Canada's Alcan Aluminium
Ltd. and Switzerland's Alusuisse Lonza Group AG are abandoning
their three-way, $17 billion plans to create one of the largest
aluminum companies in the world. Alcan and Algroup will still
pursue their two-way, $4 billion combination, approved by European
regulators last month, the companies said in a statement today. The
three-way merger fizzled after Pechiney and Alcan could not agree
on which assets to sell to satisfy European antitrust regulators,
Pechiney spokesman Jean-Claude Nicholas said. Last month Pechiney
and Alcan were forced to withdraw their application to the European
Commission when it was clear the three-way linkup request would be
rejected.
</P>
