<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 169.39; Nasdaq Down 11.07  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A fragile advance by technology stocks
evaporated today, as weakness in the blue-chip Dow industrials
spread to the broader market. Stocks came under pressure after a
spike in wholesale inflation raised new fears about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was down 11.07 at 3,758.56. The index had
risen as much as 145 points earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 169.39 at 10,955.74.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 11.95 at 1,455.22.
</P>
<P>
   Some good news on technology companies' earnings helped lend
support to the shaky sector. Advanced Micro Devices, a leading
computer chip maker, said late Wednesday it earned $1.15 a share in
the first quarter, nearly twice analysts' forecasts of 58 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro stock got a powerful lift today, rising 5} to
73}. The broader semiconductor sector was higher, with LSI Logic up
1 to 62 and Texas Instruments up 4~ to 144.
</P>
<P>
   But there were still signs of discomfort in the broader
technology group. Some of the Nasdaq's most volatile stocks turned
sharply lower, proving that the nervousness that has dominated
trading this week still hangs over Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Juniper Networks fell 11 1/16 to 193 1/16, while Rambus lost 13
13/16 to 200. Just Wednesday, Rambus reported a quarterly loss of
$6.98 per share, citing acquisition costs and one-time expenses.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparently too steep for many investors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any bottom-fishing that occurs will be among stable companies
that make money,'' said Michael Strauss, managing director of
Commonfund Asset Management. ''The heyday for stocks that have a
good story but no earnings is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors are skittish after a long, steep slide in the Nasdaq
composite, which last year posted the sharpest annual gains of any
stock market index in history. The Nasdaq has fallen more than 23
percent from its peak of 5,048.62 on March 10, tumbling well into
what some Wall Street professionals consider a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop is a
growing sense that investors pushed technology stocks too far last
year, awarding many young, unproven companies valuations they did
not yet deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kerschner, chief investment strategist at PaineWebber,
said many technology stocks could see their share prices slashed by
another third before they are in line with their earnings
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sharp correction in the 'new new industrials' has not
fully erased their excesses,'' Kerschner said. Large-capitalization
technology stocks that have only recently gone public are most
vulnerable, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks kept the Dow lower. J.P. Morgan, which rose
Wednesday after reporting strong profit growth, fell 5\ to 131 7/16
today. American Express fell 3 13/16 to 146 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and brokerage stocks were weighed down by the latest
government report on inflation. The Labor Department's Producer
Price Index showed that wholesale prices shot up 1 percent in
March, led by the biggest jump in energy costs in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The advance was a worse showing on inflation than the 0.5
percent rise many analysts were expecting.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony today before the Senate Banking Committee, Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan dismissed charges that the Fed has
tried to drive the stock market lower by boosting interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have denied and I continue to deny that our job is to
jawbone the stock market; it is not,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 826.45 million
shares, behind Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.03 to 492.41.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
