<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Requires Closed Captioning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Broadcasters and cable operators must transmit
emergency information to people with hearing disabilities in the
event of floods, fires, earthquakes or other disasters under rules
adopted Thursday by the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission unanimously approved rules that give the deaf and
hard of hearing access to information that threatens life, health,
safety and property. That can be accomplished through real-time
closed captioning, open captioning, scrolling words or some other
means.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is essential that emergency information be provided,'' FCC
Chairman William Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   The rules come after complaints that some people with
disabilities nearly lost their lives during Hurricane Fran and
Hurricane Floyd because weathercasts did not carry closed
captioning.
</P>
<P>
   Although broadcasters will be allowed to deliver the information
in a variety of ways besides closed captioning, the FCC rules
require them to provide critical information like evacuation routes
and the location of shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule is expected to become effective in about 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Closed captioning is a form of technology that transmits
information as encoded data in the television signal. A person who
wants to see closed captions must have a decoder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
