<HEADLINE> Jury Gives Victim's Kids $9M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A jury has ordered a physicians group to
pay $9 million to the children of a man who died of a brain
aneurysm the size of a golf ball.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors could have saved the life of Gabriel Anderson, 24, if
they had operated before the aneurysm burst, argued a lawyer for
Anderson's children, ages 3, 5, and 7.
</P>
<P>
   The jury returned the verdict Tuesday against Florida Emergency
Physicians, Kang &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ramsey, a lawyer for the doctors, said the physicians
provided excellent care and nobody should be blamed for Anderson's
death.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are deadly conditions and the patients can die despite
the best of care,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
