<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA OKs Use of Clot-Busting Tool  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A device used to remove blood clots from the
heart won government approval Thursday for use on leg arteries.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration approved the additional use of
AngioJet for clearing blockages in the leg, a problem for thousands
of diabetics and others with high blood pressure, high cholesterol
and the overweight.
</P>
<P>
   AngioJet, which won approval last year for heart use, is a
catheter containing a steel and a plastic tube. The end of the
metal tube is bent into a halo shape and shoots a jet of saline
solution back into the tip of the plastic one, creating a vacuum
that pulls along any blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment with the device takes about one minute, FDA said.
</P>
<P>
   The new use will assist patients with peripheral vascular
disease, which develops when the arteries carrying blood to the
legs become narrow or clogged, stopping the flow of blood.
Currently, these clots are generally treated with drugs, but those
can cause bleeding problems and, if left untreated, the clots can
lead to amputation of the leg.
</P>
<P>
   AngioJet is made by Possis Medical Inc. of Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Possis: http://www.possis.com
</P>
<P>
   FDA: http://www.fda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
