<HEADLINE> Senate to pass 'fire-safe' cigarette legislation  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The leader of the state Senate said Thursday
his chamber will pass legislation early next week that would make
New York the first state to require tobacco companies to sell
self-extinguishing cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel that now is the time to do it. New York can provide
leadership for the federal government,'' Senate Republican Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno said at a news conference at the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The Cigarette Fire Safety Act was passed by the Democratic-led
state Assembly the past three years and again on Monday, but had
always failed to gain enough support in the Republican-controlled
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Sen. Frank Padavan, who sponsored the Senate bill, said with
15 Republican co-sponsors and the support of the Democratic
minority, ''there's no doubt that it will pass the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   After the bill is passed in the Senate, it would still need the
approval of Gov. George Pataki if it is to become law.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokeswoman Suzanne Morris said, ''We'll take a look at
it when we get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of so-called ''fire-safe'' cigarettes say the long,
continuous burn of most American cigarettes too often leads to
deadly fires when smokers fall asleep with them in their hands,
leave them unattended or fail to snuff them out. They said the bill
could greatly reduce the number of fires caused by burning
cigarettes left unattended.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes were the leading cause of fatal fires in New York in
1997, the latest year figures were available from the state Office
of Fire Prevention and Control.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know hundreds of lives of New York City residents and New
York state residents will be saved with passage of this
legislation,'' said Capt. Peter Gorman, president of the Uniformed
Fire Officers Association of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the legislation would require tobacco companies to
make cigarettes that stop burning if they're not smoked within a
certain time period. It also calls for the industry to meet other
performance standards to be set by the state Office of Fire
Prevention and Control to limit the risk that cigarettes would
ignite household furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   If signed into law, the measure would go into effect April 1,
2001. The industry would be required to stop marketing
non-self-extinguishing cigarettes in New York one year after that
date.
</P>
<P>
   Federal legislation on the issue would pre-empt the state bill,
Padavan said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Philip Morris said the tobacco giant already is
working on ''cigarettes that are less likely to ignite certain
fabrics but also appealing for smokers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We think this is an issue that's best dealt with at a federal
level,'' Brendan McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there is no such thing as ''fire safe''
cigarettes, preferring instead to classify cigarettes according to
their ''reduced ignition propensity.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said one example of what Philip Morris is working on
is a ''banded'' cigarette paper, which has compounds at regular
band intervals that induce the cigarette to stop burning.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Smith, a spokesman for Louisville-based Brown and
Williamson, said smokers don't want a self-extinguishing cigarettes
if they will go out while they are being smoked.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York state government: http://www.state.ny.us/
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris: http://www.philipmorris.com
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson: http://www.brownandwilliamson.com
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco Products Liability Project: http://www.tobacco.neu.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
