<HEADLINE> Powell: No VP, Maybe Cabinet  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO N.C. (AP) -- Colin Powell hasn't changed his mind
since 1995. The retired general still insists the presidency or
vice presidency still isn't in his future.
</P>
<P>
   When the conversation moves to a Cabinet position however, that
opportunity just might make the former Joint Chiefs of Staff
rethink a few things.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no interest in being vice president. I'm not being coy
or cute. ... I admire people who seek political office but you need
to have a certain type of passion for that,'' Powell said, en route
to North Carolina for an event this week for America's Promise, The
Alliance For Youth, the volunteering and mentoring organization for
youth he has led for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If any president or elected official asks you to serve (in a
Cabinet post), you've got to listen to that request. I'm not ruling
anything like that out but I'm not ruling it in either.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks around Washington have already been talking up Powell as a
perfect fit as Secretary of State if George W. Bush, the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee, made the call.
</P>
<P>
   For now at least, Powell said he was fulfilled leading the
charge for the nation's youth while heading up America's Promise.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been in the vineyards planting the vines and we now see
them bearing fruit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, Powell got Gov. Jim Hunt to support the goals
of America's Promise.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, signed during a rally at a Greensboro
shopping mall, Hunt issued an executive order giving state
employees paid time off to mentor children.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of community and corporate leaders in North
Carolina, Powell drinks in the message from representatives from
companies like First Union Bank, the Pepsi Bottling Co. and General
Electric -- a pledge to give employees paid leave to volunteer at
local schools and community facilities.
</P>
<P>
   At the mall, Powell tells a cheering crowd, ''The children of
today have enemies in their lives - drugs, crime, violence and
despair. We have to step forward and be mentors.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many times Powell expresses his passion for
helping children or his aversion to the prospect of nonstop
political fund raising and the other confines of seeking elected
office, the general knows another question about his nonexistent
political ambitions is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ten years ago, I was a lieutenant general who was dragged into
the White House. Before I knew what happened, I was chairman,''
Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you turned back the clock 12 years and gave me back the
anonymity I had, it wouldn't bother me in the least. At least I
could go to garage sales again.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said he believes American voters could look beyond its
racially divided past and unite behind a black candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the country is ready,'' he said. ''When I considered
running (for president) in 1995, I had to talk to America and I
concluded the country had changed to a point where it would be
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he added, ''the country has matured.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
