<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Opens Impeachment Inquiry  </HEADLINE>
By NORMA LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The state House voted overwhelmingly
Thursday to open an impeachment inquiry into New Hampshire's
Supreme Court justices, deepening a constitutional crisis that
began over a divorce case.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers decided 343-to-7 to authorize the first impeachment
probe of a New Hampshire judge in 210 years.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has brought down one member of the high court already
and threatens three of the four remaining justices.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court's been sinking its own ship pretty well,'' said Rep.
Paul Mirski, sponsor of the legislation. ''We've got to let the
committee go where it can go. This stuff is just going to continue
to erupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeanne Shaheen called the vote ''a necessary step toward
restoring the public's confidence in our judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote, which empowers the House Judiciary Committee to
investigate Chief Justice David Brock and other members of the
court, comes nearly two weeks after Justice Stephen Thayer resigned
rather than face prosecution on charges he tried to influence the
assignment of judges to hear his own divorce case.
</P>
<P>
   In a report, Attorney General Philip McLaughlin also alleged
Brock violated the law by listening to Thayer.
</P>
<P>
   While Brock's alleged offense was not criminal and carries no
punishment, the report also concluded that justices who were
excused from cases because of conflicts of interest were still
allowed to comment on proposed rulings in those cases.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said in his report that it was up to the
Legislature to decide what to do about the alleged ethics lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Brock has defended the court, saying no justice besides Thayer
ever tried to affect the outcome of a case in which he was
disqualified. He said judges who disqualified themselves merely
corrected grammar or factual errors in proposed rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Julie Brown called the inquiry a ''political hack job''
prompted by the court's unpopular ruling two years ago requiring
the state to overhaul the way it pays for the public school system.
</P>
<P>
   ''These men have served the state well. Their reputations are
destroyed by using the word 'impeachment,''' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Vermont Constitution, impeachable offenses include
''bribery, corruption, malpractice or maladministration of
office.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Judiciary Committee recommends impeachment of any of the
justices, the House would put the articles of impeachment to a
vote. If any passed, the Senate would sit as a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Brock, two others could face removal -- Sherman Horton
and John Broderick. The fourth member of the current court, Justice
Joseph Nadeau, was not named in the attorney general's report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
