<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were higher in
trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures prices were boosted by strong gains in the
soyoil market, which is seeing improved world prices for vegetable
oil. Soybeans also received a lift from talk China, a recent
purchaser of South American soybeans, may enter the market for
another purchase, perhaps from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures prices were lifted by uncertainty over the amount
of rain to fall in the Midwest corn crop belt. There is concern
rainfall will be light and that the soil will become drier in
coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures prices, though slightly higher, continue to trade
in a narrow range, due to a lack of market-affecting news.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery was 2\ cents higher at $2.57} a bushel;
May corn was 2 cents higher at $2.27{ a bushel; May oats were 2\
cents higher at $1.23{ a bushel; May soybeans were } cent higher at
$5.38\ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle futures prices were higher and pork futures prices were
mixed in trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle were .30 cent higher at 69.45 cents a pound;
May feeder cattle were .10 cent higher at 84.62 cents a pound; June
lean hogs were .02 cent lower at 75.05 cents a pound; May pork
bellies were .93 cent higher a 96.60 a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
