<HEADLINE> Jury Orders Mack Trucks To Pay $50M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROVE HILL, Ala. (AP) -- Mack Trucks Inc. was ordered to pay $50
million in a lawsuit alleging a trucker would have survived a fiery
wreck if the manufacturer had installed an inexpensive electrical
cutoff device.
</P>
<P>
   A jury returned the verdict Wednesday in favor of Mary
Witherspoon. Her son, Tonnie Witherspoon, was driving a load of
logs in 1995 when his rig jackknifed, pinning the 33-year-old
driver inside, then caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   The mother's lawyers argued that Mack should have installed a
switch that could have disabled the electrical system in a
rollover.
</P>
<P>
   ''The inexpensive device would have interrupted electrical
arcing in the power system, preventing the fire that claimed the
man's life,'' lawyer Robert T. Cunningham Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1975 proposal from the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration to install such switches died after truck companies
fought it, he said. He said Mack still does not install the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, we have great sympathy for the family,'' William
Daniels Jr., a lawyer for Mack, said Thursday. ''At this point, we
are evaluating all our options.''
</P>
</TEXT>
