<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan: Watch Trading Costs  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The risk of inflation persists, Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said Thursday, as new government
figures showed the spike in energy costs lifting wholesale prices 1
percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of indications of prices going up,'' Greenspan
said in testimony to the Senate Banking Committee. ''If you look,
however, at the underlying cost structure of American business, I
see no evidence of an acceleration'' in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan defended the Fed's moves to raise interest rates and
said the stock market's wild swings in recent days showed it is
''groping for the correct balance.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday's close, the technology-heavy Nasdaq index had
tumbled 27 percent since its record high on March 10, putting it in
bear market territory. The blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average
is down a more modest 7 percent from its Jan. 14 record, with a
decline Thursday of more than 200 points amid inflation jitters
stirred up by the report on wholesale prices.
</P>
<P>
   The recent gyrations and divergence between the two stock
indexes ''are reflecting the basic underlying forces'' of sharply
different rates of return on high-technology stocks compared with
more traditional ones, Greenspan told the senators.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what's happening is that the markets are groping for
the correct balance underlying the system,'' Greenspan said. He
added that it is very difficult to determine what the correct price
level should be.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, the central bank chief denied that
the dramatic losses in the Nasdaq index in recent days were caused
by the Fed having pushed up interest rates five times in the past
10 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ... insist upon continuing to deny that our goal is to
jawbone the stock market. It is not,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the Fed's interest rate moves were designed to protect
the economy from potential damage from the persistent risk of
inflation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the rapid changes sweeping the nation's securities
markets, Greenspan advised against a government mandate for any
form of centralized network for displaying stock quotes and urged
caution on switching to stock trading in decimals.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street appears to be inching toward creation of a
centralized quote network, which would show stock quotes across an
array of competitive markets. Greenspan said that given the pace of
technology-driven change in the markets, ''It is difficult to
contemplate how a government mandate could be implemented; systems
might well be obsolete before we were halfway through the planning
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions of new investors and increasing competition from new
electronic communications networks, known as ECNs, have put
pressure on the nation's two biggest exchanges, the New York Stock
Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it fails to respond to technological change, one
centralized trading venue, even the NYSE, can be displaced by
another as other trading systems take advantage of newer technology
to offer greater efficiency or to provide new functions investors
value more highly,'' Greenspan testified.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the stock exchanges' anticipated switch to quoting
prices in decimals, rather than fractions, Greenspan said he agreed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission ''about being careful
about trying to move forward too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, under a decimal system, a stock price now quoted as
10{ would become 10.50.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC wants the exchanges to begin decimal trading later this
year, but the Nasdaq market has said its computer systems aren't
ready yet to handle the switch from traditional fractions. SEC
Chairman Arthur Levitt recently said he believed it would be
confusing for investors to have the NYSE start trading in decimals
before the Nasdaq did so.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anybody is smart enough to figure out where the
markets are going as we go through this dramatic change,'' Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, the Banking Committee chairman, said at the
start of the hearing. ''I think it is very important that we let
technology lead and that we let regulation follow.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said some degree of government
intervention was needed. ''The government should set speed
limits,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1635 </TRAILER>
