<DOCNO> APW20000413.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain To Meet Next Month  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his toughest
rival in last winter's presidential nominating fight, John McCain,
will meet in Pittsburgh on May 9 for the first time since the
Arizona senator folded his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course I want his support, but I don't know if it will
happen as a result of the meeting,'' Bush told reporters Thursday
in Austin. ''John wants to visit. I want to visit,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters just off the Senate floor, McCain said,
''I'm sure we'll have a fruitful discussion'' including possible
ways of helping out in the GOP campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he hopes to address the party convention this
summer, he said, ''that's a decision Governor Bush will make.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has already pledged to support the nominee of his party,
but has said the enthusiasm he puts into the effort will depend in
part on Bush's willingness to adopt elements of the senator's
''reform agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain already has begun campaigning for GOP candidates for the
House and Senate, and in a separate announcement during the day,
his office said he would travel to Pennsylvania, New York and New
Jersey over the next two days on behalf of GOP congressional
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential nomination in hand, Bush has been attempting in
recent weeks to unify the party and place his own mark on the GOP
national organization.
</P>
<P>
   He pocketed the endorsement of another primary rival, Steve
Forbes, late last month. And earlier this week, he dispatched Fred
Meyer, a former state GOP chairman in Texas, and Maria Cino, a
senior campaign aide, to the Republican National Committee. Several
GOP sources say the Bush campaign is also intent on placing trusted
aides in key positions overseeing the RNC's communications
apparatus and operations at the GOP convention scheduled for
Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain talked by phone the night the primary campaign
effectively ended, on March 7, and at least once since. Their
relationship, outwardly quite cordial during the early stages of
the campaign, deteriorated as the two men engaged in a fast-paced
series of primaries with the nomination at stake.
</P>
<P>
   They attacked one another in television commercials and through
surrogates -- Bush standing by at one point while a veteran accused
the former Vietnam POW of neglecting veterans' concerns, and McCain
airing television ads that said the Texas governor twisted the
truth like President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also angered the McCain camp in a newspaper interview in
mid-March in which he said McCain ''didn't change my views'' about
any issues. Bush swiftly changed his tone and said the next day
that McCain had highlighted the need for reform, for example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
