<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 201; Nasdaq Off 92  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A fragile advance by technology stocks shattered
today as weakness in the blue-chip Dow Jones industrials spread to
the broader market. Stocks came under pressure after a spike in
wholesale inflation raised new fears about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary calculations, the Nasdaq composite
index fell 92.85 to close at 3,676.78, bringing its loss for the
week to 769 points. The index had risen as much as 145 points
earlier in the session before collapsing in the final hour of
trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow plummeted 201.58 to close at 10,923.55, its steepest
point drop since March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 26.66 to 1,440.51.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-8 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,721 down, 1,251 up and 486
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.03 billion shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.14
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.23 to 492.21.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology stocks are clearly in a bear market.'' said Eugene
G. Mintz, financial markets analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP;
Co. ''The Nasdaq tried to rally two or three times and just
couldn't hold it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's loss left the Nasdaq 27 percent below its March 10
closing record of 5,048.62. Wall Street professionals consider a 20
percent drop from a peak the traditional touchstone of a bear
market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop is a
growing sense that investors pushed technology issues too far last
year, giving many young, unproven companies stock prices they did
not yet deserve.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's inability to sustain its short-lived rallies
indicates that the nervousness that sent the index on a long spiral
downward is still in place, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambus, a maker of technology used in the computer chip
industry, provided the latest cautionary tale. Just Wednesday, the
company reported a quarterly loss of $6.98 per share, citing
acquisition costs and one-time expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Today, several Wall Street brokerages raised their ratings on
Rambus stock. But investors apparently felt the steep losses were
reason enough to dump the stock, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any bottom-fishing that occurs will be among stable companies
that make money,'' said Michael Strauss, managing director of
Commonfund Asset Management. ''The heyday for stocks that have a
good story but no earnings is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kerschner, chief investment strategist at PaineWebber,
predicted bigger declines ahead for technology companies that he
dubbed ''new new industrials'' -- large-capitalization technology
stocks that have only recently gone public.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies in that category could see their share prices
sliced by another 33 percent before their prices are in line with
their earnings potential, Kerschner said.
</P>
<P>
   The late-day selloff overshadowed some genuinely good news on
corporate earnings. Advanced Micro Devices, a leading computer chip
maker, said late Wednesday it earned $1.15 a share in the first
quarter, nearly twice analysts' forecasts of 58 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro stock got a powerful lift today. The broader
semiconductor sector also rose, with LSI Logic and Texas
Instruments up.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks kept the Dow lower as inflation fears
resurfaced. J.P. Morgan, which rose Wednesday after reporting
strong profit growth, fell today. American Express also declined.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and brokerage stocks were weighed down by the latest
government report on inflation. The Labor Department's Producer
Price Index showed wholesale prices shot up 1 percent in March, led
by the biggest jump in energy costs in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The advance was a worse showing on inflation than the 0.5
percent rise many analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric fell sharply even after reporting its earnings
rose 20 percent in the first quarter, led by strong performances at
its industrial systems and NBC units. Profits beat analysts'
estimates by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   Separately today, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
dismissed charges that the Fed has tried to drive the stock market
lower by boosting interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have denied and I continue to deny that our job is to
jawbone the stock market; it is not,'' Greenspan said in testimony
today before the Senate Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
