<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-CT--Boy Witness, 1st-Ld Writethru,670  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Lawyers for a man accused in the
killings of an 8-year-old boy and his mother are asking that the
charges be dropped because a woman who claimed to be an eyewitness
to the murders later said she lied.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Lee -- the prosecution's star witness -- originally told
police she acted as a lookout and then watched Adrian Peeler shoot
Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke, in their
Bridgeport home on Jan. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lee later pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit murder and
agreed to testify against Adrian Peeler and his brother, Russell,
who is accused of masterminding the killings to stop the little boy
from testifying against him in an earlier murder.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter she wrote to her lawyer in December -- after she
cut a deal with prosecutors for a seven-year sentence -- Lee says
she lied about what she told police.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that I have told them is lies,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to make this thing right and deep down inside God's
know (sic) that I did not have anything to do with the murder.''
</P>
<P>
   She also wrote, ''I can't not (sic) live with myself telling a
lie on the Peelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection in Russell Peeler's trial is nearly completed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a day after the letter was made public, Russell
Peeler's lawyers filed a stack of motions asking for dismissal of
the charges, immediate adjournment of the trial, a mistrial and
continuance.
</P>
<P>
   ''This statement of this witness alters the nature and
complexion of this prosecution so dramatically that the trial may
not proceed forward without court intervention,'' Peeler's lawyers
argue in their motion for a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's lawyers, John Walkley and William Koch, also ask Judge
G. Sarsfield Ford to order that the defense be given access to Lee
immediately so they can get a new statement from her.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's basically admitted that everything she's said to this
point is a lie,'' said Walkley.
</P>
<P>
   Ford rejected the request for an adjournment of the trial, but
said he would reserve a final decision until a full hearing is held
Monday on all the defense motions.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict would not comment
on Lee's letter.
</P>
<P>
   ''The jury will have to decide,'' he said, when asked if Lee
will be a credible witness.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter to her lawyer, Lee says she hopes to get a lighter
sentence than the seven years prosecutors are expected to
recommend. She has an undisclosed terminal illness.
</P>
<P>
   That letter contradicts three letters Lee wrote to Bridgeport
police detectives at about the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In those letters, Lee admitted her role in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know what I did was wrong. I get down on my knees every
night and ask God to forgive me for what I have done to the boy and
his mother,'' she said in a letter to Detective Dwayne McBride.
</P>
<P>
   She also mentions her fear of the Peelers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God that my life is still here because the Peelers did
not kill me and that is a blessing from God,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Koch said the Peelers did not threaten Lee to get her to change
her story.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has been in the federal witness protection program while
waiting to testify against the brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler's lawyer, Patrick Culligan, said he may file
similar motions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Josephine Lee's letter to her attorney certainly undermines
and probably eliminates any probable cause for the state to
continue to prosecute Adrian Peeler and his brother, Russell,''
Culligan said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyer, Richard Reeve, would not comment on the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers face the possibility of the death penalty if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler is already serving a 105-year sentence for the
killing of Rudolph Snead, Clarke's boyfriend. The little boy was to
testify against Peeler in the Snead murder trial. Peeler also is
serving a life sentence on federal drug charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
