<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Mills To Promote Car Safety  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. (AP) -- Stung by criticism over their rewards to a
7-year-old who drove off in his sister's car in search of Cheerios,
General Mills officials say they will produce car-safety messages.
</P>
<P>
   The Minneapolis cereal maker announced the move Wednesday after
delivering coupons for a year's supply of Cheerios and other
goodies to the family of Perley King.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills will produce and distibute both print and radio
ads to be run at no charge as public service messages. General
Mills spokeswoman Liv Lane said the company has not determined how
much it will spend on the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''General Mills certainly does not condone reckless behavior,''
the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
   But that's precisely how many people interpreted the company's
decision to provide the youngster with freebies.
</P>
<P>
   Callers to at least one radio talk show in Seattle blasted the
rewards, and a letter writer to the local newspaper, The News
Tribune, said she planned to boycott General Mills products for a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''What upset me about this is that ... he's clearly getting very
mixed messages here,'' said Deirdre Sargent of Fort Lewis, whose
letter arrived at the newspaper Wednesday. ''He gets free cereal
for a year and a bike.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on April 1, while other family members slept, Perley and
his dog, Bear, climbed into the car and drove three miles in search
of a food store.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce County sheriff's deputies received reports from other
drivers of an ''erratic driver'' or ''a little kid driving'' and
surrounded the car within blocks of Interstate 5, sheriff's
spokesman Ed Troyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Perley apparently managed the adventure without an accident,
except for putting a small dent in his mother's truck and bumping a
patrol car when he stepped off the brake at the roadblock, Troyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, representatives from General Mills visited
Perley's family at its south Tacoma home. They presented him with
coupons for a year's supply of Cheerios and a new yellow mountain
bike ''to help him understand that a 7-year-old should travel on
two wheels, not four,'' General Mills said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
