<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Thursday, April 13, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dow Ends Down 201.58; Nasdaq Off 92.85
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A fragile advance by technology stocks shattered
today as weakness in the blue-chip Dow Jones industrials spread to
the broader market. Stocks came under pressure after a spike in
wholesale inflation raised new fears about the economy. The Nasdaq
composite index fell 92.85 to close at 3,676.78, bringing its loss
for the week to 769 points. The index had risen as much as 145
points earlier in the session before collapsing in the final hour
of trading. The Dow plummeted 201.58 to close at 10,923.55, its
steepest point drop since March 7. Broader stock indicators were
also lower.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:
Dow Industrials:        10,923.55  - 201.58
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,251  Declines 1,721  Unchgd  486
NYSE Volume:       1,032,534,070
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online58]   - 3}  
S&AMP;P 500:         1440.51 - 26.66
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          915.23  - 11.56
Nasdaq Composite Index        3,676.78  - 92.85
Gold(final) -    $281.10    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale Prices Surge in March
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The biggest leap in energy prices in nearly 10
years made wholesale inflation in March rise 1 percent for the
second month in a row. Meanwhile, soaring gasoline prices helped
push up retail sales by a faster-than-expected pace. The federal
reports show the speeding economy continues to be fueled by hardy
consumer spending, yet aside from energy prices, inflation remains
quiet. The core rate rose a modest 0.3 percent. On the retail
front, sales rose 0.4 percent in March, twice as fast as economists
expected. Excluding the volatile category of car sales, which fell
sharply, March's total retail sales were up a sizable 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco, Arco Merger Approved
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC promised today to move swiftly to
conclude its purchase of Atlantic Richfield Co. after receiving
government approval that had been held up for months over concern
about its impact on competition. The Federal Trade Commission voted
5-0 to approve the merger of BP Amoco and Atlantic Richfield, or
Arco, for $27.6 billion after an agreement to divest significant
holdings in Alaska. The new company will be the second-largest oil
company not owned by a government, behind Exxon Mobil Corp., a
merger approved by the FTC last November. BP Amoco stock was down |
at 51{ today; Atlantic Richfield was also down |, at 83 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan: Watch Trading Costs
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
today ordinary investors should pay attention to costs that may be
''buried'' in their trading contracts. He also said the time may
not be ripe yet for stock trading in decimals instead of fractions.
Greenspan said investors should not only consider commissions in
trading. He told the Senate Banking Committee that other costs
could include delayed executions of stock trades, failures to
execute trades and lost profit. He said disclosure to investors by
brokerage firms will enable them to make more informed choices.
</P>
<P>
   IMF Official Defends Globalization
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- International Monetary Fund and Clinton
administration officials today defended their efforts to promote
freer trade and greater integration of the global economy. They
said such steps offered the best hope of lifting hundreds of
millions of people out of abject poverty. Globalization -- the bane
of thousands of demonstrators in the nation's capital this week who
contend that world capitalism has failed to help the poor -- has
gotten a bad rap, said acting IMF Managing Director Stanley
Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Warns of Wrong Jet Rivets
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. has warned airlines and federal
regulators that rivets that reinforce a plane's structure need to
be replaced in 27 747-400 jumbo jets. A mechanic at Boeing's
Wichita, Kan., plant discovered that as many as 1,000 of the wrong
kind of rivets had been installed on each of the 27 aircraft, 10 of
which have been delivered and are in service with airlines. Boeing
spokeswoman Shannon Myers said the rivets used on the upper deck
and main deck of the jumbo jets do not pose a flight safety risk.
Myers said, however, that the rivets do help reinforce part of the
plane's structure and that those used cannot handle the stresses
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Libraries Get $2.5B Internet Funds
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A program to connect schools, libraries and
communities nationwide to the Internet will receive $2.25 billion
in funding this year, the Federal Communications Commission
announced today. That's the full amount allowed under FCC rules.
Last year, 82 percent of the nation's public schools and more than
half of the public libraries received discounted services under the
''e-rate'' program, with more than 53,000 urban schools and more
than 25,000 rural schools receiving support. Vice President Al Gore
said the additional funds would ensure that a total 1 million
classrooms would be connected.
</P>
<P>
   GM Earns $1.78B in First Quarter
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. stock was up { at 88 today
after it reported that it earned $1.78 billion in the first
quarter, down 2 percent from a year ago. The results still beat
Wall Street expectations. The world's largest automaker said today
it earned $2.80 a share, in the January-March period compared to
$1.82 billion, or $2.68 a share last year. Earnings per share
increased because fewer shares of GM are on the market now than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times Earnings Up 35 Pct.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times Co. posted a 35.3 percent
increase in first-quarter earnings, beating Wall Street estimates
as newspaper advertising revenue surged. The owner of The New York
Times, The Boston Globe and 22 other newspapers earned $83.1
million, or 47 cents a share, in the January-March period, up from
$61.4 million, or 34 cents a share, a year earlier. The latest
results beat the analysts' expectations of 43 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Higher
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed marginally higher today,
dragged down by a faltering technology sector. Shares rallied a
bit, however, as the Nasdaq in New York recouped in early U.S.
trading. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies
fell 0.12 points to 384.84 and the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index ended
down 0.04 points at 430.79. In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100
Share Index rose 6.2 points, or 0.1 percent, to 6,357.0. In Paris,
the CAC 40 closed up 25.64 points or 0.4 percent at 6,264.34
points. In Milan, the blue-chip MIB30 index gained 0.2 percent, or
110 points, to close at 45,534.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
