<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan: Ships To Treat Ballast Water  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ships would be required to replace or purify
their ballast water before entering the Great Lakes under
legislation being pushed by several lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the bill will keep out foreign species such as
the sea lamprey, ruffe and zebra mussel that are wrecking havoc on
marine ecology and industries.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are suffering a number of economic consequences because of
non-native species,'' said Rep. Pete Hoekstra, R-Mich. ''That's not
new. What is new is that we are introducing federal legislation to
deal with the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ships use ballast water to stabilize the vessel. But the water
also can carry marine life from other places the ship has visited.
Most ships empty most of their ballast by the time they enter the
Great Lakes, but there is often enough to keep non-native species
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Invaders such as the sea lamprey, ruffe and round goby threaten
the $4.5 billion Great Lakes fishing industry. Zebra mussels clog
water intake pipes, doing an estimated $120 million in damage
between 1989 and 1994, according to a report sponsored by the eight
Great Lakes states.
</P>
<P>
   But the shipping industry says it would be unduly burdened by
such a rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm concerned about my job,'' said Karl Hardesty, a Michigan
freighter pilot. ''I'm concerned about the jobs of the tugmen that
provide services to these vessels.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm concerned about the jobs of the longshoremen ... the truck
drivers who deliver these goods, the jobs of the miners. There's a
huge industry that's supported by Great Lakes shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Barcia, D-Mich., said the lawmakers would work with
shippers to come up with a solution that would not ruin their
livelihood.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Great Lakes Commission: http://www.glc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
