<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton cancels plans to headline Arab event  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights -- smarting from
news that its chairwoman contributed to Hillary Rodham Clinton's
campaign, on Thursday postponed public discussion of a report said
to criticize Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's New York Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The commission denied any connection.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the first-lady-turned-politician scrapped plans to
headline a charity dinner for an Arab-American group because
representatives from the Israeli Embassy were not invited. Certain
Arab states do not recognize the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under these circumstances, Mrs. Clinton will no longer be able
to serve as honorary chair of the Mosaic Foundation event,'' a
statement from the first lady's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mosaic Foundation is made up of the wives of Arab
ambassadors to the U.S. who raise money for charity. This year's
dinner on May 3 is to benefit Save the Children. Clinton has served
as honorary chairwoman for the dinner for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Kim Serafin called Clinton's
decision to back out ''a classic Clinton flip-flop.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously she's pandering for the Jewish vote,'' Serafin said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is courting New York's large Jewish population in her
bid for the U.S. Senate against Giuliani. She strained her
relationship with some Jews last year after a visit to the West
Bank. There, Clinton embraced Soha Arafat after the wife of Yasser
Arafat accused Israelis of using poison gas on Palestinian women
and children. The first lady distanced herself from Mrs. Arafat's
remarks the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Giuliani denounced a civil rights commission
probe against the NYPD after word surfaced in Newsday that the
panel's chairwoman Mary Frances Berry contributed to the first
lady's campaign. Berry gave $250 last year to Clinton and another
$300 to the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, which has
pledged support to her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't take much to figure out this is a political
operation,'' Giuliani said Thursday after a campaign stop on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   But Berry defended her donation.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have a right to make campaign contributions to anyone
they please,'' Berry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She said she would continue to participate in the commission's
discussion of the NYPD.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (the report) is about Giualiani's office, not Giuliani.
It's about the police department in New York. It's not about
Hillary Clinton and it's not about the senatorial campaign,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's spokesman David Aronson said it was unclear
when the draft report would be discussed and declined to explain
the delay. The report was scheduled for discussion Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member commission is preparing a report on the NYPD
that several sources say is expected to be highly-critical and
could call for the appointment of a federal monitor. The commission
began its probe into the police force last year in the wake of the
shooting of Amadou Diallo and the torture of Abner Louima at the
hands of New York City cops.
</P>
<P>
   The commission held a hearing in New York City in May. Giuliani
and Police Commissioner defended the police force. But the Rev. Al
Sharpton and others described it as out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Six members of the commission were appointed by Democrats and
two by Republicans. The panel has no enforcement powers but can
make recommendations to the president, Congress and federal
agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
