<DOCNO> APW20000413.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: EPA failing to protect children farmworkers frompesticides  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government is failing to protect
children working in farm fields from exposure to potentially
dangerous pesticides, according to a report released on Thursday by
Congress' nonpartisan investigative arm.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office report concluded that children in
farm fields ''are especially vulnerable to the adverse effects of
pesticides and are not adequately protected from pesticide
exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said the Environmental Protection Agency's Worker
Protection Standard is not enforced consistently and treats
children as adults.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when the EPA measures the amount of time that
should elapse before workers are allowed back into the fields after
pesticides are sprayed, it uses a body weight of 154 pounds - well
over the weight of a small child, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Lantos, D-Calif., requested the GAO probe along with
Reps. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., and Bernie Sanders, I-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA did not immediately return a phone call seeking comment.
But in a written response to the GAO, Marcia Mulkey, director of
pesticide programs, said EPA was reviewing its worker protection
standards. She said, in concept the agency agreed with the report's
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Mull, executive director of the Association of Farmworker
Opportunity Programs, called the report's findings troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Department of Labor has found children as young as six
working in agriculture. We know that children far younger than that
are accompanying their parents into the field,'' she said. ''The
health of hundreds of thousands of children is at great risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Children age 13 and under may perform agricultural work with
parental permission and certain other restrictions, under
Department of Labor guidelines. While it is difficult to measure
exactly how many child workers there are at any one time, a Rutgers
University study in 1998 estimated that 290,000 children --
two-thirds of them 15 years or younger -- were working unlawfully in
American in 1997. The study analyzed census and other data.
</P>
<P>
   According to the EPA guidelines, the 154-pound benchmark can be
used to protect children 12 years old and up because ''their bodies
have less surface area and they perform less work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mull said that failed to take into account that children
''tend to roll right around in the dirt and plants'' more than
adults, increasing their exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The report called on the EPA to back up their claim that the
current standards are adequate for children ages 12 and up. And
noting that children under age 12 are even more vulnerable to
pesticide exposure, it recommended the EPA create separate
standards for them.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said children under age 12 are at increased risk
because their internal organs are maturing, they fail to wear
clothing that protects them from exposure and they are involved in
more contact with plants and soil.
</P>
<P>
   The report also urged the EPA to expand its database on
pesticide-related illnesses and to improve the distribution of that
information, saying there was a general lack of reliable
information. And it recommended more consistent enforcement of
existing worker standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect EPA to implement these recommendations and report to
us on their progress,'' Waxman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 1745 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Farm Kids Not Protected  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government is failing to protect
children working in farm fields from exposure to potentially
dangerous pesticides, according to a report released on Thursday by
Congress' nonpartisan investigative arm.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office report concluded that children in
farm fields ''are especially vulnerable to the adverse effects of
pesticides and are not adequately protected from pesticide
exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said the Environmental Protection Agency's Worker
Protection Standard is not enforced consistently and treats
children as adults, when they are far more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when the EPA measures the amount of time that
should elapse before workers are allowed back into the fields after
pesticides are sprayed, it uses a body weight of 154 pounds - well
over the weight of a small child, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   ''The EPA does not distinguish between children and adults,''
Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said.
</P>
<P>
   Lantos requested the GAO probe along with Reps. Henry Waxman,
D-Calif., and Bernie Sanders, I-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA did not immediately return a phone call seeking comment.
But in a written response to the GAO, Marcia Mulkey, director of
pesticide programs, said EPA was reviewing its worker protection
standards. She said, in concept the agency agreed with the report's
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Mull, executive director of the Association of Farmworker
Opportunity Programs, called the report's findings troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Department of Labor has found children as young as six
working in agriculture. We know that children far younger than that
are accompanying their parents into the field,'' she said. ''The
health of hundreds of thousands of children is at great risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Children age 13 and under may perform agricultural work with
parental permission and certain other restrictions, under
Department of Labor guidelines. While it is difficult to measure
exactly how many child workers there are at any one time, a Rutgers
University study in 1998 estimated that 290,000 children --
two-thirds of them 15 years or younger -- were working unlawfully in
American in 1997. The study analyzed census and other data.
</P>
<P>
   According to the EPA guidelines, the 154 pound benchmark can be
used to protect children 12-years-old and up because ''their bodies
have less surface area and they perform less work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mull said that failed to take into acount that children
''tend to roll right around in the dirt and plants'' more than
adults, increasing their exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The report called on the EPA to back up their claim that the
current standards are adequate for children ages 12 and up. And
noting that children under age 12 are even more vulnerable to
pesticide exposure, it recommended the EPA create separate
standards for them.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said children under age 12 are at increased risk
because their internal organs are maturing, they fail to wear
clothing that protects them from exposure and they are involved in
more contact with plants and soil.
</P>
<P>
   The report also urged the EPA to expand it's database on
pesticide-related illnesses and to improve the distribution of that
information, saying there was a general lack of reliable
information. And it recommended more consistent enforcement of
existing worker standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect EPA to implement these recommendations and report to
us on their progress,'' Waxman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1751 </TRAILER>
