<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FleetBoston Earnings Jump in 1Q  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN POPE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- FleetBoston Financial reported a 45 percent jump
in first-quarter net income as the bank capitalized on a strong
capital markets business tied to the frenzied stock market.
</P>
<P>
   A year after Fleet and BankBoston merged to create the country's
eighth largest bank, the company reported earnings of $957 million
in the first quarter, or $1.03 per share, compared with $661
million, or 68 cents a share a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding merger-related costs, earnings rose 22 percent to $808
million, or 87 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ''The early read on the combination between BankBoston and Fleet
Financial is that it's a smashing success,'' said Gerard Cassidy,
managing director of equity research at Tucker Anthony Cleary Gull
in Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings easily beat predictions of analysts, who were told
last month the company should beat their average estimate of 80
cents by 7 cents a share. In January, analysts were estimating
earnings of 67 cents a share, Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very impressive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston's shares fell $1.06\ to $37.25 in trading at 4:30
p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange, where stocks were broadly
lower Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bank posted very strong results in non-interest income,
which jumped 51 percent to $2.36 billion from $1.56 billion in the
first quarter 1999. Much of that was driven by the company's
capital markets business led by Robertson Stephens, and investment
services, which includes its online trading unit Quick &AMP; Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   The bank raked in fees from mergers and acquisitions and by
underwriting public offerings, Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston's specialist operations, meanwhile, benefitted from
heavy trading in stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their specialist operations don't really care if the markets
go up and down, they just care about volume,'' Cassidy said.
</P>
<P>
   Net-interest income was basically flat at $1.72 billion in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While non-interest expenses also were up, $2.41 billion compared
to $1.94 billion last year, FleetBoston plans to fire 4,000
employees by the end of the year to reduce overlapping jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The merged company has outperformed all expectations,'' said
Terry Murray, FleetBoston chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy agreed FleetBoston is off to a fast start. But he said
the final verdict won't come for another year, when the two
companies are fully integrated and have completed their divestiture
of 278 branches to Sovereign Bank of Pennsylvania, as required by
the Federal Reserve Board when it approved the merger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
