<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Amo Houghton says he will seek an eighth term  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLEAN, N.Y. (AP) -- Rep. Amo Houghton, eager to protect his
district and the Republicans' slim majority, said Thursday he will
seek an eighth term.
</P>
<P>
   The 74-year-old Houghton had planned to retire but was concerned
if he did that his district in southwestern New York might be
eliminated when Congressional lines are redrawn after this year's
census count. New York is expected to lose two Congressional seats.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rural representation is real and if you want to look out the
window and let the scene pass you by then you get outdistricted and
I'm not going to allow that,'' Houghton said in Olean during a trip
through his 10-county district, which stretches from Lake Erie in
Chautauqua County to the Finger Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   He made his plans known to Gov. George Pataki and state Senate
Majority Leader Joe Bruno on Wednesday. ''Now, they can't give me
any promises but at least they know how strongly I feel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described moderate, Houghton was one of only two
Republicans to vote against impeaching President Clinton. He pushed
instead for a strongly worded censure. He founded The Republican
Main Street Partnership in 1997 to bring together moderate
lawmakers and business executives, governors and mayors. He has
been a staunch advocate for the National Endowment for the Arts and
public television.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton's centrist views have often put him at odds with more
conservative leaders in the House. But many of those leaders --
worried about defending another open seat in November -- lobbied him
aggressively to stay. Democrats must pick up only six seats to
regain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert was among those who met with
Houghton in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had a lot of impact on me,'' Houghton said. ''It's not that
he put the hard sell on it but he said, 'please, if this is
important to you, hang with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert spokesman John Feehrey called Houghton's announcement
''a very important decision for the GOP.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This shows that Republicans are going to keep the majority,''
Feehrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton came to Congress after 25 years at the helm of the
Fortune 500 Company Corning Inc., which his family founded in his
hometown of Corning. He is one of the wealthiest members of
Congress and pays for his foreign travel. Corning's stock has
soared recently because the company is the largest supplier of
fiber optics, credited with allowing for expansion of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from Corning, Houghton considered becoming a
missionary in Africa, but ran for Congress instead. He has won
re-election easily.
</P>
<P>
   A devout Episcopalian, Houghton is co-chairman of the Faith and
Politics Institute, a nonpartisan interfaith group set up to
provide political leaders with opportunities for moral reflection
and spiritual community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 1755 </TRAILER>
