<HEADLINE> First Union Reports 13 Percent Drop  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE (AP) -- First Union said Thursday that profits slumped
13 percent in the first quarter as fee income declined and costs
rose at the nation's sixth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits, which exclude merger-related costs, totaled
$838 million, or 85 cents a share, meeting Wall Street's lowered
expectations. That compares with operating earnings of $965
million, or $1 a share, for the first quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Including charges for First Union's acquisition of CoreStates
Financial two years ago, net income totaled $840 million, or 85
cents a share, compared with $706 million, or 73 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been prepared for a less prosperous year at the
Charlotte, N.C.-based bank, which has branches in 12 eastern states
and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   First Union's shares fell 81\ cents to $35.87{ in trading at
4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange. The bank's stock has
fallen almost 38 percent in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, fee income slipped more than 3 percent to
$1.86 billion from $1.93 billion. That was offset by a 10 percent
rise in net interest income to $1.99 billion.
</P>
<P>
   However, the bank's strategy of saving money by laying off
workers appeared to have backfired. First Union is now spending
heavily to keep key employees. The bank's non-interest expenses
jumped 13 percent to $2.39 billion in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   First Union Web site: www.firstunion.com
</P>
</TEXT>
