<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rebound As Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Government bonds rebounded Thursday as blue-chip
stocks stumbled and traders looked for a haven for money coming out
of the stock market. The gains came despite fresh inflation
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 9/32, or
$2.81 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell to 5.79 percent from 5.81 percent late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Treasurys bounced higher amid a broad selloff of stocks. The Dow
industrials fell 201.58 and the Nasdaq composite index extended its
slide into bear market territory, giving up early gains to close
down an additional 92.85.
</P>
<P>
   Traders typically buy relatively safe Treasury bonds to park
their money during turbulent times on stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   The late gains for bonds reversed early losses on fresh
inflation jitters.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the trading day, the government reported that
soaring energy prices made wholesale inflation in March rise 1
percent for the second month in a row. In addition, there was a
fresh inflation warning from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates five times since June to try
to keep a lid on inflation. It is widely expected to increase rates
a sixth time in May.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates and high inflation both reduce the value
of investments that pay a fixed return, such as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, short-term notes were unchanged to
up 3/32 point, while intermediate notes rose [ point to 7/32 point,
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.79 percent as the
discount fell 0.02 percentage point from Wednesday to 5.64 percent.
Six-month yields were 6.05 percent, and the discount remained at
5.80 percent. One-year yields were 6.10 percent as the discount
fell 0.01 percentage point to 5.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.00 percent from 5.94 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 at 95 23/32. The average yield to
maturity was 5.92 percent, unchanged from Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
