<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Dems To Push Gun Control  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- Frustrated over gridlocked gun control
legislation, Senate Democrats said Thursday they would ''consider
all procedural and parliamentary options'' to restart negotiations,
even if it means blocking some legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they were angry that the legislation is stuck in
a conference committee, with the anniversary next week of the
Columbine High School shootings. The measure passed the Senate soon
after last year's shootings at the Colorado school.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our message is simple,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
''There is nothing on the Senate schedule more pressing than saving
children's lives. We are sick and tired of delay and we aren't
going to take it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten Senate Democrats detailed their concerns in a letter to
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are extremely frustrated, as most Americans must be, by
this lack of progress,'' they wrote. ''We will carefully consider
all of our procedural and parliamentary options in an effort to
ensure that the conferees finish their work and send a conference
report to the House and Senate before the school year ends in
June.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they were still working out details of their plan
to get the bill moving and could not specify their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans pointed the finger at Democrats and said the dispute
could have been resolved months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's certainly regrettable that the Democrats would try to use
the Columbine tragedy as a news hook to further their political
aims,'' said Lott spokesman John Czwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   Czwartacki accused House Democrats of rejecting GOP-backed gun
control measures. ''Today we could be one step closer. These could
all be law today if Democrats had not decided to put politics
before progress.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton traveled to Columbine on Wednesday in hopes of
turning up the pressure on Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A House-Senate conference committee has been assigned to
reconcile differences between a Senate-passed bill that would set a
72-hour background check on gun-show sales and a House bill that
shrank the wait to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has met only once, in August. The White House
attributes the delay to political maneuvering by the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., floated a
concession on the key issue of waiting periods for gun show
purchases. In a letter Wednesday, Hyde said a majority of House
Republicans involved in negotiating the legislation supported a
compromise closer to the president's position.
</P>
<P>
   In line with Clinton's thinking, Hyde said, background check
waiting periods would apply both to would-be gun purchasers with
unresolved arrest records and those with red flags for other
offenses such as drug use, mental incapacity, domestic violence or
stalking.
</P>
<P>
   But the ranking Democrat on the Judiciary Committee, Rep. John
Conyers of Michigan discounted Hyde's offer and said it was
''further capitulation by the Republican leadership to the NRA's
political gamesmanship.'' Conyers said the GOP compromise contained
fatal loopholes that exempted people indicted for crimes from
longer waiting periods and allowed ''bad apple'' gun dealers to
avoid federal scrutiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1819 </TRAILER>
