<DOCNO> APW20000413.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Nears OK of $1.83T Budget  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ignoring President Clinton's position that the
plan ''defies common sense,'' Congress moved Thursday to the brink
of approving a $1.83 trillion budget calling for tax cuts, debt
reduction and extra money for schools and the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted nearly party-line, 220-208, to approve the
fiscal 2001 measure. Quick Senate passage was expected. Clinton
does not have to sign the fiscal outline, but an election-year veto
battle looms over 13 annual spending bills and any tax legislation
lawmakers send him translating their budget's plans into reality.
</P>
<P>
   The package leaves the two parties poised for a campaign season
touting starkly different views of how to use surpluses from the
non-Social Security side of the budget. Republicans would use much
of it for tax cuts, Democrats prefer more domestic spending and
debt reduction, and each accuses the other of jeopardizing Social
Security surpluses they have pledged to leave alone.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who would like to spend more are not keeping their eye
on the target: balancing the budget, paying down debt, protecting
Social Security,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that to pay for excessive tax cuts, Republicans
would slice needed domestic programs while insufficiently
bolstering Social Security and Medicare or reducing the national
debt. He said Congress should have done a better job of using
''this magic moment of possibility'' -- the government's hardy
fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   ''The proposal from my point of view defies common sense,'' he
told the American Society of Newspaper Editors. ''I think the
argument is over. We had a test run. We had 12 years of their
proposals -- do the big tax cuts first and it'll all work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's reference was to the 12 years of Presidents Reagan and
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He also seemed to take a swipe at George W. Bush, the GOP's
presumptive presidential nominee, saying the tax cut plan
Republicans are ''running on this year is even bigger'' than the
10-year, $792 billion tax package he vetoed last year. Bush's $483
billion, five-year plan has an estimated 10-year cost of more than
$1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Completion of the budget would mark the second straight year
Congress had done so by the April 15 deadline. The date is usually
ignored, but the quick action illustrates how GOP leaders are
determined to adjourn Congress early for re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides would use the $1 trillion in expected Social Security
surpluses over the next five years to reduce the $3.7 trillion
publicly held debt, with the goal of eliminating it by 2013. Most
economists say such a dramatic reduction of that debt would press
interest rates downward and fuel the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the two parties are divided over how to use the surplus
projected from the rest of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans would use much of it for a tax cut of at least $150
billion and perhaps more than $200 billion, depending on lawmakers'
decisions and how much economic growth occurs over the next few
months. Democrats want a smaller tax reduction, with more money set
aside for domestic programs and debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ''In an election year, they want to spend all your money and
tell you that's right,'' Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete
Domenici, R-N.M., said of Democrats, adding, ''Beware.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, said, ''Any way you want to
cut it, the center piece of this budget is a massive tax cut at the
expense of debt reduction, Social Security, agriculture and
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget would set aside up to $40 billion over
five years for any new prescription drug benefits that lawmakers
add to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But action is not required, and the money could be used for
other ''reforms,'' such as easing cuts in Medicare reimbursements
to many hospitals enacted in the 1997 budget-balancing deal.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties say they want to enact a prescription program this
year. Clinton wants it to cover all elderly Americans, while
Republicans want to limit it to lower-income people or those with
extremely high drug bills.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also calls for $311 billion for defense next year, $5
billion more than Clinton wants. And it would spend $289 billion
for domestic programs, about $30 billion less than Clinton seeks.
</P>
<P>
   Included would be increases for education, veterans and
biomedical research, though final decisions will be made in later
spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two-thirds of the budget covers interest payments
on the debt, plus benefits like Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The measure approved Thursday was a House-Senate compromise of
similar budgets each chamber had passed earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In a symbolic victory for environmentalists, the compromise
dropped non-binding language assuming that some money would be
raised by allowing oil drilling in Alaska's Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge. The Senate had narrowly refused last week to drop
that provision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
