<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treasurer reform bill passes Legislature  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A bill intended to reform the operation
of the state treasurer's office in the wake of crimes committed by
former-Treasurer Paul Silvester has passed the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The bill sailed through the Senate unanimously, then passed the
House on a 141-7 vote Thursday. It now goes to Gov. John G.
Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll decide whether to sign the bill after reviewing it,''
said Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland had threatened to veto a weaker version of the bill last
week because it didn't impose enough oversight of the office or
crack down on so-called finder's fees paid by companies to people
who set up investment deals with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''This makes the office of treasurer a little bit less risky,''
said Rep. Ronald San Angelo, R-Naugatuck. ''This truly is the real
treasurer reform bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The reform measure came out of last year's scandal surrounding
Silvester, a Rowland appointee who pleaded guilty in September to
charges of racketeering and money laundering related to
fund-raising in his failed 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted accepting kickbacks from finders fees paid by
companies with which he invested state pension money. He is to be
sentenced June 16.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, the state Ethics Commission would have a say in
determining who can collect finder's fees for brokering investments
of state pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would create the position of investment specialist
in the treasurer's office and strengthen oversight safeguards by
the Investment Advisory Council.
</P>
<P>
   The bill outlaws the payment of finder's fees to anybody except
qualified financial counselors so designated by the treasurer in
consultation with ethics officials. It provides penalties for
anybody who violates the finder's fee provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill addresses our concerns,'' said Alan Plofsky,
executive director of the state Ethics Commission. He had attacked
the earlier version of the bill, which would have permitted
''investment professionals'' to do business with the treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Plofsky said the earlier bill was virtually worthless because
anybody could call himself an ''investment professional.'' The
amended bill is a great improvement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Denise Nappier also supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is sound, it is prudent and it was the right thing to do,''
Nappier said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, among other things, replaces the deputy treasurer with
a chief investment officer and prohibits the state treasurer, any
candidate for state treasurer, or any member of the Investment
Advisory Council, from seeking campaign contributions from persons
connected to an investment company.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who has denied any knowledge of Silvester's
fund-raising illegalities, appointed Silvester after former
treasurer Christopher Burnham resigned to take a job with an
investment company that had done business with the state.
</P>
<P>
   The reform bill requires the treasurer to wait at least one year
from the date a contract is negotiated before going to work for the
company, if the contract amounts to at least $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also restricts the governor's power to appoint someone
to fill a vacancy in the Treasurer's Office when the General
Assembly is not in session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 1821 </TRAILER>
