<HEADLINE> Venezuela Elections Spur Tension  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA HERNANDEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez's main
challenger in next month's polls has refused to take part in a new
plan to include opposition members on a panel meant to ensure fair
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidate Francisco Arias Cardenas called the
government's proposal a ''joke'' because it doesn't give the
opposition a vote on the National Election Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't name someone to serve on the National Election Council
as a clown,'' said Arias, according to a campaign press release
issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Arias's comments came as tensions over May 28 presidential
elections intensified with opposition politicians, Catholic Church
leaders and retired military officials insisting fair balloting may
not be possible because Chavez controls the electoral council.
</P>
<P>
   Election authorities this week proposed allowing each
presidential candidate to name a representative to the council as
observers without decision making power.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the government's plan to add nonvoting members,
Arias, a former army officer who helped Chavez stage his famous
1992 coup attempt, has asked the council to add five new voting
representatives from various civic and political organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The National Election Council has come under increasing pressure
to move quickly to ensure fair elections after two mayors from the
opposition party were dismissed from office Tuesday and replaced
with members of President Hugo Chavez's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   An interim legislature appointed by a pro-Chavez constitutional
assembly alleged the mayors from the eastern state of Delta Amacuro
were creating an ''unstable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an abuse of power,'' said Armando Rodriguez, head of
Venezuela's mayoral association. He said the allegations were vague
and unfounded. ''This may be the start of a grand persecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's critics say the decision was just the latest attempt by
the president to amass power and silence opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office last year, Chavez has pushed through a new
constitution that dissolved congress and called for new balloting
to ''re-legitimize'' most public offices, including the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez faces his most serious challenge from Arias, a former
comrade-in-arms who accuses the president of abandoning the
original goals of their 1992 rebellion. Arias is seen as having a
real chance against the charismatic president because he isn't part
of the traditional parties Chavez virtually erased since taking
office.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders have expressed concern over the fact the election
council was hand-picked by Chavez's movement, saying it failed to
guarantee the most basic impartiality needed in a popular election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
