<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monitors Said Key in Peru Runoff  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- International monitors may have made the
difference between election fraud and a ballot outcome that will
force President Alberto Fujimori into a runoff election with
economist Alejandro Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Observers and diplomats, mainly from the United States and
Europe, were key players in last Sunday's general elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on their reports, the international community stepped up
the pressure on the government,'' said political scientist Fernando
Rospigliosi. ''Ultimately, the government might have been disposed
to ignore the popular protests, but what they definitely could not
ignore was international pressure and the threat of sanctions. That
was key.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, exit polls and unofficial tallies by independent
monitors had indicated Fujimori would not reach the 50 percent plus
one vote needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   But after an unexplained 12-hour delay, the first official
returns showed Fujimori on track to claim a first-round victory,
prompting suspicions of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   For three tense days, Toledo's supporters took to the streets by
the tens of thousands in Peru's main cities in mostly peaceful
demonstrations that threatened to turn violent if Fujimori claimed
an unprecedented third five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The president's supporters complained that the monitors were
helping destabilize the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are conscious that our work has been highly scrutinized,''
said Eduardo Stein, head of the delegation from the Organization of
American States, responding to government criticism that election
monitors overstepped their bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe we have tried to conduct an active observation in an
extremely complex and questionable election,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS mission fielded 80 people on election day, complimenting
some 20,000 Peruvian monitors from Peru's Ombudsman office and
Transparencia, a citizen watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   While Peruvians went to the polls on Sunday, the U.S. Congress
was in the process of passing a bipartisan resolution advising
President Alberto Fujimori that the United States could ''modify
its political and economic relations with Peru'' if international
observers continued to find fault with his third-term re-election
bid.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Tudela, Fujimori's vice presidential candidate and a
former foreign minister, complained bitterly about U.S.
interference in the election.
</P>
<P>
   He said he rejected in the ''most energetic terms the fact that
a foreign government would emit a judgment value about elections in
another country before the official count is in.''
</P>
<P>
   But political scientist Fernando Tuesta said without the
attention brought to bear by the monitors, ''the government would
have imposed a first round victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Of that I'm absolutely sure,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1831 </TRAILER>
