<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30-Yr., 15-Yr. Mortgage Rates Slip  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rates on 30-year and 15-year mortgages edged
down for the second week in a row but are still up more than 1
percentage point from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The average interest rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages fell
to 8.12 percent for the week ending April 14 from 8.20 percent the
previous week, according to a survey released Thursday by Freddie
Mac, the mortgage company. This time a year ago, 30-year mortgages
averaged 6.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-February, the rates on 30-year mortgages hit a 3{-year
high of 8.38 percent. That was the highest since a 8.42 percent
rate for the week ending July 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing, also
ticked down this week to 7.76 percent from 7.83 percent. This time
a year ago, 15-year mortgages were at 6.47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an
average initial rate of 6.86 percent this week, up from 6.79
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three
types of mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Mortgage Bankers Association of America said
that mortgage loan applications for the week ending April 7
increased 7.7 percent from the previous week and were down 13
percent compared with the same week last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1834 </TRAILER>
