<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill To Up Taiwan Military Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., on
Thursday put a bill to increase U.S. military aid to Taiwan on the
Senate calendar, possibly leading to a floor vote on the issue
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., immediately imposed a ''hold'' on
the measure, complicating Lott's efforts to bring it to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Baucus, a leader in the effort to grant China permanent trade
benefits, contends the bill could complicate the upcoming Senate
debate on the Clinton administration's China trade package.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has asked the Senate not to consider the
legislation, even though it won the 341-70 support of the House
last Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwan Security Enhancement Act would increase military
exchanges with Taiwan and reassert Congress' role as a consultant
in annual arms sales to Taiwan. China, which considers the
self-governing island a renegade province, has voiced strong
opposition to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott supports the bill and would like to see the Senate vote
on it, said Lott spokesman John Czwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   Lott put the bill on the Senate calendar at the request of a
bipartisan group of 13 senators led by Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark.
''This legislation will provide greater balance and clarity to our
relations with Taiwan and China,'' Hutchinson said in a letter to
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Baucus' countermove means that, at the least, Lott will have to
marshall 60 votes for the measure to overcome threatened delaying
tactics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1841 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
