<DOCNO> APW20000413.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden to face intense state scrutiny of financial practices  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state agency that oversees municipal
governments plans to ask on Friday for the power to supervise all
of Camden's financial records and operations, one step shy of a
full takeover of New Jersey's poorest city.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being poor and operating efficiently is way different than
poor and not caring how you operate, and that's the point here,''
said Ulrich Steinberg, the state's director of the Division of
Local Government Services. ''The city seems to think that because
they're poor, they don't have to keep records.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have until Saturday to correct a dozen faults
outlined by the state or face action that could include a takeover.
Camden -- where 70 cents of every city dollar spent comes from state
aid -- does not keep proper financial records, including a general
ledger and an account of city payouts, all of which are required by
law, the state alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimatum came a day after Camden Mayor Milton Mayor Milan
was named in an indictment charging him with extortion, money
laundering and mail fraud. Authorities say Milan accepted payoffs
and gifts from city contractors and took bribes from organized
crime figures.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have very low ratables. They have practically no
commercial industry,'' Steinberg said. ''But the overall problem is
that you have no private investment in Camden because of the
economic and political instability.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg's application for the supervision program is scheduled
to be heard Friday morning by the state Local Finance Board. If the
board sides with Steinberg, the measure would be forwarded to the
attorney general and three cabinet officers for final approval.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said Thursday she supports the supervision
program and if that doesn't work she will ask the Legislature for
the power to assume complete control of the city. Whitman said she
will ''certainly encourage the attorney general to move quickly''
with approval.
</P>
<P>
   ''But at the same time, I want to make sure that we are moving
forward with legislation that would give us the ultimate authority
to do a complete takeover if, in fact, the supervision doesn't do
what the people expect, and what the people of Camden deserve,''
Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hope that we'd never have to exercise that, because
it's dramatic and it's extreme, but the problems in Camden are
dramatic, and they're extreme, and we need to rectify them,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, Camden does not meet the strict legal grounds
for a state takeover, Steinberg said. If it did, it would become
the first municipality to be controlled by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Under the supervision program, all city spending would be
monitored by Steinberg's office, he said. The division also would
monitor hiring practices and other city procedures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milan did not return calls left at his office by The Associated
Press. His staff directed all questions to city attorney John A.
Misci.
</P>
<P>
   ''The city is prepared to discuss the dictates and the
timetables and the status of each one of those dictates,'' Misci
said.
</P>
<P>
   If the state does engage in the supervision program, city
residents will not notice an immediate change, Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his staff will use the first few weeks to survey the
city's business practices before making changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-13-00 1844 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite TV Service Bill Approved  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved a bill Thursday to make it
easier for rural and small town Americans who rely on satellite
dishes for their television to get local TV signals.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed on a 375-37 vote, would offer $1.25
billion in loan guarantees to help satellite and other television
providers extend local TV broadcasts to areas where it is not now
financially viable to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill is crucial for Americans in rural and smaller markets
who rely on their local television stations for news, politics,
weather, sports and emergency information,'' said Rep. Bob
Goodlatte, R-Va., a co-sponsor with Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has passed similar legislation and differences
between the two sides must now be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   A bill enacted into law last fall opened the way for satellite
carriers to provide local network TV broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   While satellite companies have begun offering local stations for
viewers in larger, more populated markets, they have made clear
that it is not economically feasible to provide such service in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte said that Roanoke, a city of 100,000 in his district,
will not benefit from last year's law and that more than 30 million
TV households will remain beyond the reach of local TV via
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The bill ''will ensure that rural Americans will not be treated
as second-class citizens,'' said Eva Clayton, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The loan guarantees would be capped at 80 percent, meaning that
the federal government would promise to cover 80 percent of the
loans if the borrower defaults.
</P>
<P>
   The loan program, to be administered by the Department of
Agriculture, would be phased out at the end of 2006.
</P>
<P>
   While there was little argument that rural America deserves
better access to local TV, several lawmakers objected to government
intervention in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla., said the federal government would
be subsidizing companies so they can better compete. ''That should
send a chill throughout Congress and the rest of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 3615.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Information on the issue at:
http://www.house.gov/goodlatte/satellite.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1844 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0193 </DOCNO>
