<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Republicans Amass War Chests  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Jim Rogan, a California Republican who is
among the Democrats' top targets this fall, had almost $1 million
in the bank as of the end of March, according to figures released
Thursday by the National Republican Congressional Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan was one of the House managers who presented the case for
impeaching President Clinton to the Senate. He had $965,000 in his
account as of March 31, as compared to $255,356 at the same time
two years earlier. Rogan has raised close to $4 million for his
re-election; in 1998, he spent a total of $1.3 million on his
campaign, which he won with 51 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, who faces state Sen. Adam Schiff this fall, is one of
several vulnerable House Republicans who have amassed large war
chests in anticipation of tough re-election fights.
</P>
<P>
   The NRCC released the numbers Thursday to highlight how these
lawmakers are well-prepared financially to take on their Democratic
opponents. The reports are due at the Federal Election Commission
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''These record-breaking fund-raising figures clearly show that
Americans support the progress Republicans have made on issues
important to our families,'' NRCC spokeswoman Marit Babin said.
''People have responded to our message of reducing the marriage tax
penalty, returning local control of education and restoring
character and morality in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Others include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Rep. Clay Shaw in Florida, who is facing state Rep. Elaine
Bloom. Shaw had $1.3 million in the bank as of March 31 -- more than
twice as much as the $530,127 cash on hand he had two years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rep. Ernie Fletcher in Kentucky, who has raised $1.1 million
for his re-election and had $925,000 in the bank. When he first ran
in 1998, he spent $1.3 million on his campaign. Fletcher is being
opposed by former Rep. Scotty Baesler, who gave up the seat in 1998
to run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rep. Don Sherwood in Pennsylvania, who narrowly beat Democrat
Pat Casey two years ago and now is in a rematch. Sherwood raised
$800,000 for his re-election and had $560,000 in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats touted the fund-raising success of their
candidate for the Virginia seat being vacated by retiring
Democratic Rep. Owen Pickett. Lawyer Jody Wagner raised $337,000
during the first three months of 2000 as compared to $264,000 for
GOP state Sen. Edward Ed Schrock.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a huge deal,'' Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee spokesman John Del Cecato said. ''She has really stunned
a lot of people with how successful she's been. Her fund-raising
strength shows how much support she has in the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also cited former Rep. Jane Harman, trying to reclaim
the California congressional seat she gave up to run for governor
in 1998. Harman raised $863,000 during the first three months of
the year, as compared to $820,000 for Republican incumbent Steve
Kuykendall. Harman also had almost twice as much money in the bank,
$700,000 versus $370,000 for Kuykendall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1851 </TRAILER>
