<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Native Group Funds OKd  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A new treaty giving the Nisga'a aboriginal group a
homeland in British Columbia won final approval from Parliament on
Thursday and was enacted into law.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate chamber voted 52-15 with 13 abstentions to pass the
treaty, which survived a lengthy opposition filibuster in the House
of Commons last year. After the Senate vote, Gov. Gen. Adrienne
Clarkson granted royal assent to the treaty, effectively making it
law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaty, the 5,500 Nisga'a assume self-governing status
in an 800-square-mile territory in northwest British Columbia and
receive $173 million, along with funding for commercial fishing and
other economic ventures.
</P>
<P>
   While the treaty provides the Nisga'a a much smaller territory
than the group's claimed traditional lands and removes their
tax-exempt status, it is considered a possible model for future
agreements with other native groups seeking land and self-governing
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Royal Assent of our treaty signifies the end of the
colonial era for the Nisga'a people,'' Chief Joseph Gosnell said
outside the Senate chamber. ''Today, the Nisga'a people become
full-fledged Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
   The treaty still could face legal wrangling. Two lawsuits
challenging the constitutionality of the treaty are pending, and
some of the land granted to the Nisga'a is claimed by other native
groups in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Affairs Minister Robert Nault says further talks would
attempt to settle any land disputes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
