<HEADLINE> Soldier says loss of legs was worth it  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A 23-year-old soldier who lost his legs
trying to help a stranded couple and their 4-year-old grandchild on
the New York State Thruway Sunday called his injuries ''worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather lose something like legs than have a 4-year-old
lose their life,'' Spc. Dean L. Johnson of Warwick, Rhode Island
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's car was stranded in the right lane of the Thruway
during a heavy snowfall in the Columbia County town of Chatham
Sunday afternoon. Johnson said he pulled his pickup truck behind
the car and figured he could push it out of traffic and give the
motorists a ride to a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ''I noticed the child's car seat in the back and had to stop,''
he said. ''I was going to get flares out when I looked in the
rearview mirror and saw the truck coming around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson ran from his car and tried to dive out of the truck's
way, but the truck's trailer struck him when the vehicle jackknifed
upon slamming into Johnson's pick-up.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, I thought I was OK and I tried to get up and run
back,'' Johnson said. ''But I looked down, and my legs were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ''So I started yelling 'Medic! Medic!' thinking the truck
slammed into the child.''
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, 57-year-old Harold Feltt of Saratoga County
was ticketed for driving too fast, having faulty windshield wipers
and failing to keep a log book, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the accident, Feltt was in fair condition. The couple
and the 4-year-old escaped serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   State troopers said that if Johnson's pickup was not parked
behind the couple's car, the tractor-trailer would have hit the car
with full-force, likely killing all three occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who returned to his Fort Drum base one month ago after
finishing a 9 month tour of duty in Bosnia, said the real heroes on
Sunday were the state troopers and motorists who helped him before
medics arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier instructed those who stopped to help him to wrap
belts around his legs to stop the bleeding. He said a woman, who he
thinks was named Margaret, sat with him to keep him warm and talk
him through the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Schoenig, Johnson's nurse, said the soldier is ''ahead
of the grid'' in terms of how fast he's healing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him we'd take one step at a time, so not to overwhelm
him,'' Schoenig said. ''But he said 'I don't want small steps, I
want leaps.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''My family has a big Fourth of July bash that I plan on walking
into,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
