<HEADLINE> Ramsey's Lie Detector Test on Hold  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WELLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- An offer by John and Patsy Ramsey to take
a lie detector test in the slaying of their daughter is on hold as
they argue with police over who would conduct the test.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said Thursday they're waiting for the other to act.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our position is that in good faith that we have met their
conditions. We are waiting for an answer on whether they are going
to take one,'' Police Chief Mark Beckner said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am waiting to hear from him. As I see it the ball is in his
court,'' said Lin Wood, the Ramseys' lawyer, in a telephone
interview from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been arrested in the death of 6-year-old JonBenet,
who was found beaten and strangled in the basement of the family
home Dec. 26, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Beckner has said the parents ''remain under the umbrella of
suspicion.'' They have denied involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said the main stumbling block over the polygraph is who
would conduct the exam. Wood objects to a police or FBI examiner
because those agencies have been involved in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anyone connected with the Ramsey investigation
... qualifies as an independent entity,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Beckner said, ''We will meet the conditions set by John Ramsey.
We can certainly find FBI examiners who know nothing about the
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys made the lie-detector offer during a recent flurry
of interviews generated by the publication of their book, ''The
Death of Innocence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
