<HEADLINE> Social Live Help Prevent Dementia  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elderly people who live alone, have no friends or have a bad
relationship with their children are 60 percent more likely to
develop dementia than those whose social contacts are more
satisfying, a new study suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Stockholm Gerontology Research Center at
Karolinska Institute in Sweden, whose study is published this week
in The Lancet medical journal, found that the more socially
isolated old folks were, the more likely they were to develop the
brain condition.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Suzman of the U.S. National Institute of Aging called
the research an intriguing and important extension of recent
findings that social engagement and close relationships are
powerfully associated with general health and longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very good start, a very good first study,'' he said,
adding that he will remain skeptical that there is a real
protective effect of a social life until further research confirms
the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Dementia is a component of diseases such as Alzheimer's and
Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe that by 2050, the ranks of the elderly, which
will include the Baby Boomers, will swell by at least 10 times what
it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Dementia) is already a large problem, but it's going to
become an enormous problem unless there are ways to intervene,''
Suzman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish researchers asked 1,200 people aged 75 or older
whether they lived alone and had no friends to speak of, and
whether they had a unsatisfying relationship with their children.
</P>
<P>
   A bad relationship with their children was not defined by how
often they saw them or spoke to them, but by the quality of the
rapport.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists then monitored them for three years to see who
developed dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The people whose lives were lacking in all three areas were
considered to have a poor social network, while those who had two
of the factors were considered to have a limited social network.
</P>
<P>
   Those two groups together had a 60 percent higher chance of
developing dementia than their counterparts who had only one
negative aspect or an extensive social network.
</P>
<P>
   When each factor was taken separately, those who lived alone
were 50 percent more likely to develop dementia, as were those who
were friendless.
</P>
<P>
   A poor relationship with their children doubled the subjects'
chances of becoming demented.
</P>
<P>
   ''Particularly alarming is the indication that risks are higher
among those having unsatisfactory contact with children than among
those having no children at all,'' said Lisa Berkman of Harvard
University's School of Public Health in a critique of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman added that the sense of belonging and worthiness that
social ties bring may be an important buffer against the onset of
dementia. A diversity of relationships is critical and having one
strong bond is not enough, she hypothesized.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the study, about 176 people had developed dementia
and 300 others had died.
</P>
<P>
   Suzman said it remains unclear why social ties might protect the
elderly from dementia. He said it could be that social engagement
uses the cognitive functions of the brain, keeping it active.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might be that social networks buffer them from stress,''
Suzman said, adding that high cumulative levels of stress increase
the risk of dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The study could not tell whether mild, undiagnosed brain decline
could have prompted the people to withdraw socially.
</P>
<P>
   It also could not show how long ago those leading isolated lives
had become cut off, which would make it difficult to predict
whether intervention later in life would do any good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1902 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Wild Party' A Bigger, Better Bash  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Critic
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- You've got to hand it to director George C.
Wolfe. He knows how to put on a big bash with style.
</P>
<P>
   Consider his version of ''The Wild Party,'' the second of two
musicals this season based on a Jazz Age poem by Joseph Moncure
March that celebrates sin and gin and the people consumed by both.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, composer Michael John LaChiusa and a terrific design team
have worked quite a transformation on March's hard-boiled rhythms
and rhymes. Not perfect, mind you, but with enough sizzle and snap
to make for an adult musical that satisfies the soul and the senses
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Just like it did to the earlier version of ''The Wild Party,''
the ghost of ''Chicago'' hangs over this production, which opened
Thursday at Broadway's Virginia Theater. And that's not necessarily
a bad thing, although here, the cynicism is darker and cuts deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe and set designer Robin Wagner have taken to heart the fact
that this party gathers together a group of vaudeville performers,
from stripper to ageless chanteuse to hoofer and more.
</P>
<P>
   The creators have placed the action within the confines of an
ornate Victorian proscenium arch, not unlike the framework where
many of these artists would have worked. In fact, placards on the
side of the stage announce many of the musical numbers, just as if
they were being performed in the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wolfe's vision is anything but sweet and nostalgic. This
party serves up its drinks with more than a taste of bitters. At
the center of the sourness is the volatile relationship between
Queenie, a dancer, and Burrs, here both a clown and a singer who
dons blackface in the manner of Al Jolson.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe and LaChiusa have neatly expanded the poem's slim story
line, but it remains remarkably faithful to the original work.
LaChiusa's ambitious score artfully suggests the sound of the
1920s, without sounding as if it is a museum piece. The music pays
homage to early Ellington, Gershwin, and Cole Porter, even saluting
the master's penchant for dropping famous names of the day into his
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   The songs couldn't be better showcased, particularly by its
three leads, Mandy Patinkin, Toni Collette and the eternally young
Eartha Kitt.
</P>
<P>
   Patinkin always has been a dangerous, possessed performer,
willing to push to the edge in portraying a character. That
fearlessness works to his advantage in ''The Wild Party,'' as he
creates a Burrs whose almost psychotic jealousy not only seems
plausible but inevitable. And the range of that voice! Whether bass
or falsetto, it commands the stage.
</P>
<P>
   As a musical-theater newcomer, Toni Collette, as the abused
Queenie, more than holds her own. She sings surprisingly well,
dances passably and most importantly, projects the right degree of
vulnerability that this confused creature should possess.
</P>
<P>
   When Wolfe needs someone to stop the show, he brings on Kitt,
who plays Dolores, a diva of indeterminate age and infinite life
experience. He wisely allows Kitt to do what the audience expects:
purr in her famous guttural growl and slink across the stage while
displaying the best legs in show business.
</P>
<P>
   Kitt also gets ''When It Ends,'' LaChiusa's sobering wakeup call
near the end of festivities, an anthem warning that no party lasts
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the off-Broadway ''Wild Party,'' Wolfe's production gives
the other guests their due. Each gets a moment center stage, making
the event seem more like a real party.
</P>
<P>
   The slight story focuses on a triangle, the arrival of Black, a
handsome gangster who is brought to the party by Kate, supposedly
Queenie's best friend. It's here that the evening falters a bit,
particularly in its depiction of Black, played with less than the
appropriate charisma by Yancey Arias.
</P>
<P>
   There's no lack of show-biz savvy displayed by Tonya Pinkins,
the jilted Kate. She sizzles, particularly in a number that pairs
her off against Queenie.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the triangle reaches its inevitable tragic conclusion
without a big musical payoff, a fact Wolfe disguises quite cleverly
with the help of Joey McKneely's evocative choreography.
</P>
<P>
   The other guests are a rich collection of the exotic and the
undone. Marc Kudisch does the spoiled, cocaine-sniffing, sexually
fluid playboy to smooth perfection. Ditto Jane Summerhays and Sally
Murphy as an aging stripper and her zonked-out girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   As a pair of black dandies, Michael McElroy and Nathan Lee
Graham strut and harmonize to some of LaChiusa's best tunes. Norm
Lewis and Leah Hocking offer a moment of poignancy as a washed-up
fighter and his equally has-been dancer-girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Grupper and Stuart Zagnit, as two bewildered businessmen,
provide some welcome humor in the midst of all the debauchery.
Innocence -- plus a clarion voice -- is provided by Brooke Sunny
Moriber as a fresh-off-the-farm ingenue, whose naivete quickly
evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe is the expert ringmaster, though, pulling all these people
together. And they look fabulous in Toni-Leslie James' costumes and
bathed in some of the best lighting on Broadway, done by Jules
Fisher and Peggy Eisenhauer.
</P>
<P>
   One major disappointment: a balky sound system that muffles too
many of LaChiusa's lyrics. Considering the quality of the show,
that is a major crime indeed. This is one ''Party'' that need to be
experienced in its entirety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comparison of Clinton, GOP Budget  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A comparison of the $1.83 trillion,
Republican-written fiscal
2001 budget that Congress completed on Thursday, and President
Clinton's $1.84 trillion proposal. Fiscal 2001 begins next Oct. 1.
<TEXT>
<P>
   --SURPLUSES: The congressional plan sees a $170 billion surplus
next year, the biggest ever, growing to $232 billion by 2005. All
but $40 billion of the five-year total of $997 billion in projected
surpluses would come from Social Security. The entire Social
Security surplus would be used to pay down the $3.6 trillion
publicly held debt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would also use the entire Social Security surplus for
debt reduction. He has a five-year total of $90 billion in
non-Social Security surpluses left over.
</P>
<P>
   --TAX CUTS: Republicans would cut taxes by at least $150 billion
over the next five years, and perhaps more than $200 billion.
Clinton proposed $99 billion in tax cuts plus $96 billion in tax
increases on tobacco and some corporate transactions. Details won't
be decided until later legislation, but the two sides both want to
cut taxes for education and health expenses and for many married
couples, but in different ways. Over the five-year period, the
government currently expects to collect $10.8 trillion in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   --MEDICARE, SOCIAL SECURITY: Both sides say they want to start a
new prescription drug benefit for Medicare beneficiaries.
Republicans set aside up to $40 billion through 2005, while
Clinton's would start in 2003 and is costlier. Neither side
proposes benefit cuts or tax reductions for Social Security or
Medicare that many experts say will be needed to pay for the baby
boom generation, which begins retiring in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   --OTHER SPENDING: Republicans would spend $311 billion for
defense, $5 billion more than Clinton. For other domestic programs,
the GOP wants $289 billion, about $30 billion less than Clinton
wants. Republican would increase spending over this year's levels
for education, veterans, the National Institutes of Health, and
some other programs, but unspecified other programs would face
cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
