<HEADLINE> Cell Phone Tax Bill Clears Panel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A solution to the problem of taxing cellular
telephone calls cleared a key hurdle Thursday with approval by the
Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's supporters aim to eliminate confusion over how
calls from mobile phones should be taxed, setting taxes based on a
caller's address, regardless of the call's origin. The wireless
industry and city and state officials are backing the bill, which
is sponsored by Sens. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., and Byron Dorgan,
D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   On a unanimous vote, the committee approved the measure allowing
calls to be taxed by the state and local governments with
jurisdiction over the caller's home or office address. Similar
legislation is moving through the House.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is designed to allow carriers to collect taxes more
easily and free governments from tracking calls inside their
boundaries. Brownback said it will stimulate growth in the industry
by reducing costs, which boosts the number of minutes used by
callers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
