<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collins holds to school construction position before blackministers  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Wearing a tie decorated with the faces of
children of different races, Assembly Speaker Jack Collins tried to
convince a crowd Thursday that his multi-billion dollar school
construction plan will help students throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   His audience was the Black Ministers Council of New Jersey, some
members of which represent churches in the state's so-called
special needs districts. Those districts would not receive 100
percent state aid for all building and renovation projects under
Collins' plan.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's bill is competing with one advanced by Senate
President Donald DiFrancesco and supported by Gov. Christie
Whitman. That measure provides full state building aid for the 30
special needs districts, as ordered by the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Collins disagrees that the court ordered 100 percent state
funding in its May 1998 ruling. If it did, the speaker said he
believes the court committed a constitutional error by neglecting
to consider legislative input.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know that constitution, the same constitution that
protects us all from overzealous police officers,'' he told the
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will seek a formal clarification from the justices
soon, in time for a final Assembly vote on the bill in late May.
</P>
<P>
   ''I may be crazy, but I'm crazy for the constitution. I think
they overstepped their bounds,'' he said. ''Until I am convinced
that this state will not suffer from what I view as a
constitutional violation ... I will not go quietly in the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said his plan will benefit children who attend school in
towns that are just as poor or poorer than those designated as
having special needs. It sets up additional aid and no-interest
loans for other districts throughout New Jersey. The special needs
districts, meanwhile, would receive 100 percent funding for
projects that address health, safety and overcrowding concerns, but
less aid for other projects.
</P>
<P>
   It's wrong ''to allow the dominance of education money for poor
children to be focused only in one area, the urban areas. It
doesn't matter if you're in a big town or a little town, you
hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But ministers, who gave Collins a polite if not lukewarm
greeting, said lawmakers ought to abide by the court's order.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're for 100 percent. We've been forgotten, abused and left
out for so long that we need 100 percent just to get close to the
right level,'' said the Rev. Dwight Gill of the New Hope Baptist
Church in East Orange.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court said 100 percent. The Supreme Court ruled,'' said
the Rev. Stanley Justice of the Mount Zion A.M.E. Church in
Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Reginald T. Jackson, council executive director, urged
Collins, DiFrancesco and Whitman to settle their differences and
craft a compromise plan in time to meet the court's spring
deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
