<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Battle lines unfold as Democrats seek to hold edge, gain seats inCongress  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey battle lines were drawn
Thursday in the national fight to control Congress, as candidates
filed their petitions to run.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will work to preserve and expand their 7-6 edge in the
New Jersey delegation to the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The majority gives them some bragging rights. More importantly,
it puts them in the middle of the quest to pick up 12 seats across
the country, retake the House majority and have a Democrat swing
the gavel as Speaker of the House for the first time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic chairman Tom Giblin said the party's chances to
make gains are best in three districts, one where a veteran
Republican is stepping down to run for U.S. Senate, and two others
where proven Democratic candidates will try to oust veteran
incumbents who can be painted as too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the marquee race in New Jersey is for the U.S. Senate
seat being vacated by Democrat Frank Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Corzine and former Gov. Jim Florio have been campaigning
since last summer to become the nominee charged with keeping that
seat in Democratic hands.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans, Lautenberg's departure presents an
opportunity to end two decades of Democratic monopoly over New
Jersey's seats in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP primary is a four-way contest between U.S. Rep. Bob
Franks, R-Berkeley Heights; Atlantic County state Sen. William
Gormley; Essex County executive James Treffinger; and economics
professor Murray Sabrin.
</P>
<P>
   In order to seek the Senate GOP nomination, Franks must give up
his 7th District congressional seat after eight years in office.
The district covers parts of Essex, Middlesex, Somerset and Union
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Franks' departure gives Democrats an opportunity with Union
County manager Mike Lapolla and former Fanwood mayor Maryanne
Connelly heading the race for the June 6 primary nomination. Other
Democrats seeking the nomination are Jeffrey Golkin of Warren and
Joel Farley of Westfield.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP wants to save the seat for their party. They have
put up Assemblyman Joel Weingarten, R-Essex, and Tom Kean Jr. -- the
son of the former governor -- to compete for the Republican
nomination. The field also includes Mike Ferguson, who ran against
U.S. Rep Frank Pallone in 1998 in a different district, and
Republicans Roderick M. McNealy and Patrick Morrisey.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, Assemblyman Reed Gusciora, D-Mercer, will try to
unseat two-decade veteran U.S. Rep. Christopher Smith,
R-Robbinsville, in the 4th district, and Cherry Hill Mayor Susan
Bass Levin is challenging U.S. Rep. Jim Saxton, R-Mount Holly, in
the 3rd district.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that Reed Gusciora is probably the best candidate we
have had in many years against Chris Smith,'' Giblin said. ''And I
think our best hope is with Susan Bass Levin. She is going to get a
lot of support from women's groups in and outside that district.''
</P>
<P>
   On the defense, Democrats will try to save their one freshman,
U.S. Rep. Rush Holt, D-Hopewell, in the 12th district. Two
Republicans, Mike Pappas and Dick Zimmer, who both have held office
there in the past, will compete in the GOP primary to win their old
jobs back.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Democrats won their majority in the House delegation
when Holt upset Pappas two years ago. Zimmer had held the seat for
years before Pappas. The sprawling 12th District covers Hunterdon
County and parts of Mercer, Middlesex, Monmouth and Somerset
counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have any illusions about Holt,'' Giblin said, ''but
from Day One, he has continually surprised people.'' He noted the
freshman's extraordinary fund-raising effort to build up a $750,000
campaign fund.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, a key race could be the primary challenge by
Assemblyman Scott Garrett, R-Sussex, against Marge Roukema in the
5th district in Bergen, Passaic, Sussex and Warren counties.
Garrett gave her a tough primary fight there in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
