<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Complaints Vs. Pinochet Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- As a court prepares hearings on lifting
Gen. Augusto Pinochet's congressional immunity so he can stand
trial on human rights charges, yet another criminal complaint was
filed Thursday against the ailing former dictator.
</P>
<P>
   The 83rd criminal complaint was filed by lawyers on behalf of
relatives of seven dissidents executed shortly after the 1973 coup
led by Pinochet for allegedly attacking a military barracks.
</P>
<P>
   The executions were officially reported at the time by the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Though he avoided extradition to Spain on human rights charges,
Pinochet is facing a growing number of criminal complaints at home
over alleged abuses during his 1973-1990 rule.
</P>
<P>
   The judge probing the complaints, Juan Guzman, has asked the
Santiago Court of Appeals to strip Pinochet of the immunity he
enjoys as a senator-for-life to try him on one of the most
emblematic cases of rights abuses, the so-called ''caravan of
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The case refers to a military unit that entered several cities
in October 1973, dragging scores of political prisoners from jail
and executing them. The official toll was 72 people killed and 19
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, 84, returned home last month after 16 months confined
in London fighting extradition to Spain where a judge wanted to try
him. He was released after doctors determined he was mentally and
physically unfit to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers here sought a similar way out of Pinochet's legal
troubles, but the Court refused to consider health reasons and
confirmed the hearings on his immunity will open on Apr. 19.
</P>
<P>
   According to a government report, 3,191 people were killed or
disappeared and were never heard from again during Pinochet's
1973-90 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Since his return, Pinochet has remained out of the public view,
except for three hospital visits for tests, and has not commented
on the avalanche of legal actions against him.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the tests measured blood flow to Pinochet's brain
and local media said the tests confirmed that he has sustained
irreversible brain damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
