<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Lobbying Efforts Probed  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican opponent of permanent trade
status for China has triggered an inquiry into whether the Clinton
White House violated a law that prohibits using federal funds for
lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, is examining the administration's China Trade Relations
Working Group, a White House command center dedicated to securing
congressional approval for ''permanent normal trade relations''
status for China.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to presidential aide Mark Lindsay dated April 11,
the GAO requested interviews with White House officials, an array
of documents and detailed explanations of how the administration
didn't use federal funds for significant lobbying of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank R. Wolf, R-Va., said he requested the investigation
after learning about the group's ''war room,'' a command center
which could influence congressional debate before a House vote on
China's trade status during the week of May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very concerned that the White House may be tilting the
playing field against such a fair fight and using federal resources
with its all-out lobbying effort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is a vocal critic of human rights abuses in China.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Cruise, a spokesman for the working group, said the
administration has a legitimate role in promoting its China policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are confident that our efforts have been well within the
rules for advocating administration policies, and we will cooperate
with GAO's review,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits the use of congressional appropriations to
lobby lawmakers, although the statute allows executive branch
officials to request legislation ''which they deem necessary for
the efficient conduct of the public business.''
</P>
<P>
   The ''war room'' is run by David Lane, chief of staff for
Commerce Secretary Bill Daley. Since starting in January, their
operation has expanded to eight full-time staffers and an extended
group of about 20, which includes members from the Commerce, State
and Agriculture Departments, Cruise said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   White House working group on China: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office: http://www.gao.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
