<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Film Director Honored  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL WOOLLS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALZADA DE CALATRAVA, Spain (AP) -- Pedro Almodovar's hometown
turned out in force Thursday to honor the Oscar-winning Spanish
film director, praising him as the biggest man of La Mancha since
Don Quixote himself.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar wore an all-black outfit and dark glasses as he stood
before an adoring crowd in this one-cinema, dusty farming town of
5,000 in the plains of Castile-La Mancha, about 120 miles southeast
of Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   But Almodovar choked back tears as he held aloft the Oscar
statuette he won last month for his film ''All About My Mother,''
then pretended to offer it to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not wearing dark glasses to be coquettish or achieve a
certain look,'' he said. ''I'm wearing them because I don't want
you to see me cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar lived in Calzada de Calatrava until he was 8 years
old, when his father Antonio -- a traveling wine salesman -- moved
the family of six to the southwestern Extremadura region.
Eventually they ended up in Madrid, and Almovodar has returned here
only periodically, mostly in recent years after his late mother
Francisca started spending summers in the village.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this town considers him a native son, even naming a park
after him, and Almodovar says being back has a powerful emotional
effect on him, mainly because both of his parents are buried here.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here I don't feel like a successful filmmaker,'' Almodovar
said. ''Here, I am just the son of Antonio and Francisca. Here, I
am 8 years old again.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Almodovar left such a long time ago, few people here
know him personally and not everyone is a fan of his somewhat racy,
eccentric film style. In particular, some older residents have
little stomach for it. But Salvador Boiza, 17, says the younger set
loves it.
</P>
<P>
   ''When they showed ''All about my Mother,'' it was a sellout.
Lots of young people came,'' said Boiza.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Francisco Espinosa said the people of Calzada de Calatrava
had felt great pride as Almodovar worked his way up in the movie
world, directing 13 films and culminating in this heady year of
multiple movie honors for the 48-year-old director.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have the famous Hollywood hills in the background,''
Espinosa said at the ceremony. ''We don't live on the French
Riviera either,'' he added, ''but it is here, in your town, where
we have watched you with affection every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   He presented Almodovar with yet another statuette, this time a
silver-plated one of Don Quixote, and a framed parchment with a
quote from Cervantes' famed 17th-century novel. In the passage, Don
Quixote is about to set out from La Mancha region for the first
time in search of adventure with sidekick Sancho Panza, and muses
how future generations will enjoy and remember his feats.
</P>
<P>
   Of Almodovar, the mayor said: ''Your feats, Pedro, have already
been in Calzada's memory for years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2028 </TRAILER>
