<DOCNO> APW20000413.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Reached on Appeals Process  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Key House and Senate negotiators said Thursday
they had reached a tentative agreement on a plan to give patients
in health plans the right to dispute treatment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Though final language has not yet been decided, the process
generally would let patients appeal the decisions to an independent
review board that would decide whether the plan should pay for the
treatment or service that was denied.
</P>
<P>
   Patients could appeal when HMOs decide not to cover
prescriptions or decide that surgery or other treatments are not
necessary. Many Americans covered by managed care organizations are
concerned that, in their quest to keep costs down, HMOs are wrongly
denying care and routinely turn down patients who take their
complaints to review boards controlled by HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a tentative agreement,'' said Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., chairman of a joint committee that has been working for
more than a month to come up with a compromise between bills passed
by the House and Senate giving Americans some rights when dealing
with managed care organizations and other health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles called the appeals process ''a very significant
provision'' that would let patients in ''every employer-sponsored
plan in the country'' have the right to an external review.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, review panels would be hired by health
plans according to a set of standards set by the government that
would prohibit conflicts of interest between the panel and the
health plan and bar health plans from selecting reviewers that have
been promised incentives that would lead them to make biased
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Senate aides said health plans could contract with university
medical schools that would appoint doctors to consider appeals
according to their expertise. Cancer specialists would hear appeals
of cancer treatment decisions, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal panels would have two central duties. They would
decide whether patient disputes were eligible for the appeals
process and send appeals that were approved to be reviewed by
medical experts.
</P>
<P>
   Denial of services and treatments that are not covered under
plans -- presumably things like cosmetic surgery -- could not be
appealed. But panels could decide to review denials of treatments
not covered under plan rules if patients believe they are medically
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The reviewers would make an independent medical assessment of
HMO decisions based on scientific studies and clinical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats warned that one key aspect of the appeals process has
yet to be decided: coming up with standards that review panels
would follow in deciding whether disputes are eligible for appeal.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the committee still hasn't decided how many
Americans will be covered by a patients' bill of rights or whether
they will be allowed to sue health plans if they are not satisfied
with the outcome of the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm mindful that we have a way to go,'' said Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2039 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GE Profits Climb 20 Percent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- General Electric Co. said Thursday its
earnings rose 20 percent in the first quarter, led by strong
performances at its industrial systems and NBC units.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings were $2.59 billion, or 78 cents per share, compared
with $2.16 billion, or 65 cents per share, in the same period a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat the expectations of Wall Street analysts by a
penny, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues in the quarter rose 24 percent to $30 billion, up from
$24.17 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   GE's industrial businesses, which includes medical, plastics,
power, appliances and aircraft engines, had revenue growth of 21
percent in the quarter. The company had double-digit growth in
operating profit in six of its seven operating segments.
</P>
<P>
   GE Medical Systems unveiled the GE Senographe 2000D, the world's
first fully digital and FDA-approved mammography system; and the
Innova 2000, the first digital cardiovascular X-ray system. They
combined for more than $50 million in orders for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   GE Silicones, part of the plastics division, completed the
acquisition of Macklanburg-Duncan and formed a new subsidiary, GE
Sealants. The unit posted revenues of $1.86 billion, up 15 percent
from the same three-month period last year.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter NBC announced its partnership with the World
Wrestling Federation to form a new football league. The first game
of the XFL is scheduled for February 2001. The broadcasting unit
posted revenues of $1.4 billion, up 18 percent from the same period
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems had $4 billion in orders, up 35 percent for its
heavy-duty gas turbines. The unit and the U.S. Department of Energy
announced the 7H System, a natural gas-fired power generation
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''In addition to delivering record first-quarter results, GE's
businesses made aggressive moves to position themselves for strong
future growth,'' GE chairman John F. Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   GE Aircraft Engines continued to win more than half of the
world's orders for passenger jet engines, and brought in roughly
the same revenue from the first quarter in 1999. The Aircraft
division posted revenues of $2.44 billion, up 1 percent from last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Connection agreed to a $2 billion deal to outfit up to 500
Bombardier Aerospace jets with CF34 engines. Boeing and GE reached
a $20 billion agreement on the 777, powered exclusively by GE
engines. Overseas, the company made a $400 million deal with the
United Arab Emirates for its fleet of 80 F-16 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems continued to win more than 65 percent of the
orders for heavy-duty gas turbines in the United States, with
orders up 35 percent to $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   GE Appliances' revenues grew 15 percent in the quarter, led by
strong sales from Triton Dishwashers, Spectra Cooking products and
other new products and a partnership with Home Depot. The unit
brought in $1.38 billion in revenue, compared to $1.2 billion in
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock fell after its report, but was part of an
overall drop in the Dow Jones industrial average. GE shares fell
$6.75 to $150 in trading at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
