<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primitive Arts Unveiled at Louvre  </HEADLINE>
By MARILYN AUGUST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French President Jacques Chirac on Thursday
inaugurated a new wing of the Louvre housing the museum's first
ever collection of primitive art objects from the world's oldest
civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   Putting some 120 statues, masks and other items from Africa,
Asia, Oceania and North and South America in the Louvre took years,
and marks a major step up for an art form long disdained by the
French art establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ''These galleries have been conceived in such a way as to allow
visitors, literally overexposed to masterpieces from other
departments, with totally different styles and materials, to
discover art works comparable to the Louvre's greatest treasures,''
Chirac said in a speech marking the opening.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of many primitive art pieces remains a major problem
for museums and private collectors worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, French officials were forced to return a statue
smuggled out of Mali. Chirac pledged to make the restitution of
fraudulently acquired pieces a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Louvre officials had long opposed displaying primitive art along
side Greek and Roman treasures, arguing that the world's greatest
museum was not meant to serve as an art ''encyclopedia.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chirac, whose passion for primitive art is well-known,
pushed the project through, authorizing state-of-the art
renovations at the Louvre to showcase the private collection of
French expert Jacques Kerchache.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got the idea to put primitive art in the Louvre when I
realized that three-quarters of humanity were being ignored,''
Kerchache told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces, some thousands of years old, are as varied as the
cultures which produced them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights: a 19th century wood sculpture from Vanuatu
in the South Pacific, a Chupicuaro terra cotta sculpture from
Mexico dating to the seventh century BC, and a 20th century Inuit
mask of swan and whale from Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac also has given the green light for the building of a
larger museum to house existing collections of primitive art
currently on display at other Paris sites. It is expected to open
in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac said the new museum -- to be located on the Quai Branly
overlooking the Seine -- would end decades-old squabbling as to
whether primitive art should be displayed with the emphasis on
aesthetics or ethnology.
</P>
<P>
   ''Culture is the genius of its people,'' Chirac said. ''The
museum will show that there's no hierarchy among the arts, and no
hierarchy among peoples.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
