<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Nisga'a Treaty Passes Senate
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Nisga'a leaders smiled, clapped and fought tears
as a land-claim treaty started 113 years ago by their ancestors
cleared its last Parliamentary hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the agreement Thursday, giving the British
Columbia First Nation land, self-government powers and $253 million
in cash and economic funding.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa will kick in $255 million toward the deal that will cost
a total of $487 million.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of sometimes heated debate, senators voted 52-15 in
favor of the Treaty, with 13 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   The first agreement of its kind in British Columbia passed into
law later in the day with Gov. Gen. Adrienne Clarkson granting
royal assent.
</P>
<P>
   The Treaty passed in the House of Commons in December and has
already been ratified by the Nisga'a and the British Columbia
government.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for its benefits, the Nisga'a settle for a fraction
of claimed traditional lands and give up their tax-exempt status,
among other concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Hardliners Likely To Keep Pressing Bouchard To Protect French
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Language hard-liners took comfort on Thursday in
a ruling that upholds Quebec's sign law, but it won't likely stop
their calls for Premier Lucien Bouchard to do more to protect
French.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Paquet, president of the Mouvement national des
quebecois, praised the Quebec Superior Court decision. She said it
recognizes the need to maintain the predominant status of French on
outdoor signs.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we'd lost, it would have opened the way to bilingual or
English-predominant or maybe even unilingual English signs,''
Paquet said. ''It would have taken us back 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Paul-Marcel Bellavance overturned a lower court ruling,
noting that six million Francophones in Quebec share a continent
with 300 million anglophones.
</P>
<P>
   ''Quebec is in a unique linguistic situation,'' Bellavance
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Simpson and Wally Hoffman were fined $500 and court costs
because an outdoor sign at their rural Quebec shop, called the Lyon
and the Wallrus, has French and English words that are the same
size. They plan to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Premiers To Study Health Costs To Press Ottawa For More Money
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Canada's premiers will put together a
detailed report on what's driving up health costs to bolster their
case to Ottawa for restoring slashed transfer payments.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made Thursday in a conference call of
provincial and territorial leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Provincial health officials led by Manitoba and Ontario will
conduct the study.
</P>
<P>
   Alberta Premier Ralph Klein said federal Health Minister Allan
Rock indicated last month that ''if it could be demonstrated and
there was evidence of things that are driving up costs . . . his
government would look at sustainable funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein said officials will refine preliminary data on how health
costs are being driven up by such factors as a growing and aging
population, inflation, salaries, new technology and capital
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Provincial health ministers will review the data at their next
meeting in May and send the report to Ottawa after that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Cancer Expected To Strike More Canadians in Years Ahead
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- The first Canadian cancer picture for the new
century and beyond is painted with hope for children, breast cancer
patients and men with lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But while death rates have declined for these three groups, the
disease remains a looming threat, suggests a report on cancer
trends released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that between now and 2015, the total number of
new cancer cases is expected to grow by 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The society released the 12th annual report, called Canadian
Cancer Statistics 2000, in collaboration with Health Canada and
Statistics Canada.
</P>
<P>
   While heart disease is North America's top killer, cancer is the
leading cause of premature death.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there will be an estimated 132,100 new cases and
65,000 deaths. That's an increase over 1999, when there were an
estimated 129,300 new cases and a predicted 63,400 deaths (final
figures for '99 have not been compiled).
</P>
<P>
   ------
Former Premier Clark Denies He Tried To Discredit a Fast-Ferry
Critic
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- Former British Columbia
premier Glen Clark denied Thursday he tried to discredit a critic
of his government's fast-ferry project to protect himself and his
government from concerns about a nonexistent public bidding
process.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who resigned last August, testified it was his public
duty to deny the numerous concerns raised by Victoria marine
engineer Bob Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's safety and technical criticisms of the fast ferries
needed to be countered publicly, said Clark.
</P>
<P>
   But Ward's lawyer, Doug Christie, suggested Clark wanted to
deflect criticisms about the absence of public tendering on the
project and counter allegations the government was about to build a
white elephant.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, I don't accept that,'' Clark responded during
cross-examination. ''Mr. Ward was not on and on about the bidding
procedure. He was on and on about not choosing his bid. I don't
remember the bidding process being the focus of Mr. Ward's
complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   The fast-ferry project was not a publicly tendered project and
the vessels were built and managed by the Crown-owned British
Columbia Ferry Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, 63, is suing Clark in British Columbia Supreme Court for
comments he made in a Vancouver newspaper article in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Park To Be Developed in Curler Schmirler's Honor
</P>
<P>
   REGINA, Saskatchewan (AP) -- Olympic women's curling champion
Sandra Schmirler, who died earlier this year of cancer, will be
honored with a park in her name.
</P>
<P>
   SaskPower, a provincial Crown corporation, is spending $75,000
on the Sandra Schmirler Olympic Park in Biggar, Saskatchewan
</P>
<P>
   Biggar was the home town of Schmirler, who skipped her team to a
gold medal at the 1998 Winter Olympics in Japan. She was also a
three-time world curling champion.
</P>
