<HEADLINE> NATO To Take Risks in War Suspects  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- NATO's secretary-general, Lord
Robertson, told the Yugoslav tribunal Thursday that the military
alliance is prepared to take risks to arrest war crimes suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said NATO peacekeepers in Bosnia and Kosovo ''are
willing to take the risks,'' to arrest the tribunal's most wanted
suspects, including the wartime Bosnian Serb military chief Ratko
Mladic, political strongman Radovan Karadzic and current Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fugitives will be apprehended as soon as possible,''
Robertson said after meeting the tribunal's prosecutor, Carla del
Ponte. It was the first visit by a NATO secretary general to the
U.N. tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Robertson joined NATO six months ago, the alliance has
arrested six war crimes suspects, the most recent being Momcilo
Krajisnik, the most senior of the nearly 40 Bosnians in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik is accused of masterminding the ''ethnic cleansing''
campaigns that killed thousands of civilians in Bosnia in the
1992-1995 war.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thanks for the arrest,'' del Ponte said. ''But it is not
enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
