<HEADLINE> Diddley Files Lawsuit Against Nike  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- If Nike thought it could sell Bo Diddley
T-shirts without paying the guitar legend, the company might not
know Diddley.
</P>
<P>
   Diddley filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Manhattan late
Wednesday against Nike, saying the company had been marketing
T-shirts with his name, likeness and the words, ''You Don't Know
Diddley.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sorry that it's come to this but what's right is right,''
Diddley said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed with Diddley's real name, Ellas McDaniel,
said Nike struck a sour note with the 71-year-old rock 'n' roll
performer last year when it went ahead with the T-shirt sales even
though he never accepted the terms of a contract proposal made by
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 28,000 T-shirts were sold worldwide for more than
$200,000 after the company concluded it had an oral agreement with
Diddley, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The T-shirt campaign was a revival of a T-shirt sold a decade
earlier when Diddley was featured in a Nike television commercial
with athlete Bo Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit sought unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   Vada Manager, Nike's director of Global Issues Management, said
the Beaverton, Ore., company was aware of the lawsuit but had not
yet seen it.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company had authorized a royalty payment of between
$10,000 and $15,000 to be paid to Diddley and was prepared to
negotiate further if that was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll respond to their suit with the facts. Hopefully with
this offer, we'll have further discussions,'' said Manager, reached
by telephone in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   John Rosenberg, a lawyer for Diddley, said he was surprised to
learn Nike was talking about settlement offers similar to those
which had already been rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no settlement discussions pending at this time.
There are no proposals on the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Nike meant to make a proposal through the press, I will
respond through the press and say we reject it as entirely
unacceptable,'' Rosenberg added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
