<HEADLINE> Congressman: Boy Tried To Steal Car  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL TOLME, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A congressman who alleges an 8-year-old
tried to steal his car was accused by the boy's parents Thursday of
manhandling the child.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. James Moran says the incident occurred outside an
Alexandria recreation center where he was picking up his children
April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Moran, D-Va., said he grabbed the boy after the child approached
him in the parking lot, said he had a gun in his pocket and
demanded Moran's keys. Moran took the child inside the center and
asked officials to call the police, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Moran recounted the incident Tuesday on NBC's ''Today''
show, where he chastised the boy's parents, the child's mother and
father hired a lawyer and filed a complaint with a magistrate.
</P>
<P>
   They say Moran manhandled the boy and should be charged. They
also claim he was drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandria police spokeswoman Amy Bertsch said investigators had
failed in repeated attempts to interview the child since their
initial contact with him following the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The parents' lawyer, Ted Williams, held a news conference
Thursday and challenged Moran to take a lie detector test. Williams
said Moran had inflamed the situation by going on national
television and taking ''potshots at an 8-year-old boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams sent to reporters school transcripts showing the child
is an ''A'' student.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said he wanted the dispute to end and from the beginning
only wanted to impress upon the child the seriousness of his
actions. Moran said other people could vouch for his sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole incident illustrates dramatically why citizens
probably walk away from problems and don't get involved in dealing
with their community,'' Moran said.
</P>
</TEXT>
