<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Says It Won't Export Tuna  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The United States has lifted its nine-year
embargo on tuna from Mexico, but the Mexican government said
Thursday that exporting tuna would be futile as long as U.S. courts
prevent their use of a ''dolphin-safe'' label.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could start exporting like crazy now if we wanted, but
nobody's going to buy tuna that doesn't have a 'dolphin-safe'
label,'' said Dalia de la Pena Wing, spokeswoman for Mexico's
Secretariat of the Environment, Natural Resources and Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unjust that we don't have the label,'' she said. ''We'll
keep appealing until they declare it dolphin-safe.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a federal judge in San Francisco blocked the Clinton
administration's plan to loosen standards for the dolphin-safe
label and allow Mexican tuna to carry the label.
</P>
<P>
   Established by a 1990 law, the label can be used only on cans of
tuna that are not netted with dolphins. The Mexican tuna fleet, the
world's largest, catches tuna in large encircling nets that often
trap dolphins, which are then freed.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 law would allow use of the dolphin-safe label on tuna
caught with encircling nets as long as observers stationed on the
tuna boats saw no dolphins killed or harmed. The U.S. government
would also have to find that dolphins were not being harmed by
repeated captures and releases.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary Richard Daley said a year ago that there was
no significant evidence of harm to dolphins from the practice. He
planned to change labeling standards Tuesday, but was blocked by
U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said the Commerce Department had failed to conduct
tests on dolphins -- also required by the 1997 law -- and to consider
the results before deciding whether the creatures were harmed. The
department says it recently started tests at sea but has no results
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Daley announced Wednesday that the government was formally
lifting its embargo on Mexican tuna, imposed in 1991 because of
dolphin-killing. Imports cannot carry a dolphin-safe label,
however, if the tuna was caught with encircling nets.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the environmental groups that challenged the labeling
change have also sued in the U.S. Court of International Trade in
New York to preserve the Mexican embargo. The suit contends Mexico
has not fully complied with U.S. regulations intended to reduce
dolphin deaths. The court heard arguments Wednesday but has not yet
ruled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2209 </TRAILER>
