<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Automakers Join Alliance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese automakers Nissan Motor Co. and Renault SA
of France said Friday they will join an Internet parts-purchasing
company being planned by General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and
DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   The planned company will give the five partners a combined
purchasing power of $300 billion, said Nissan, which is 36.8
percent owned by Renault.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to creating a single channel for the purchase of
components, the online system will help strengthen the flow of
information with suppliers, quicken product development and cut
costs, Nissan said.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to say when operations will begin or how much
each partner will invest, said Nissan spokesman Ryuji Nakayama.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler announced in February
that they will join forces in the Internet venture to handle
purchasing of raw materials, parts and office supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The planned alliance continues a trend among the world's
automakers toward partnerships or mergers. Such deals are expected
to cut the massive costs of designing and building vehicles and
developing environment-friendly engines.
</P>
<P>
   Debt-ridden Nissan has undertaken a recovery campaign since
Renault bought a stake in it for $5.4 billion early last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2229 </TRAILER>
