<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Samoan Heads Sentenced To Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   APIA, Samoa (AP) -- Two former Cabinet ministers were sentenced
to death Thursday, after a judge confirmed a jury's findings that
the pair were guilty of murdering a rival member of Samoa's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Exercising powers to either confirm or quash a jury's guilty
verdict which was split 4-1, judge Andrew Wilson accepted the
decision against the two conspirators.
</P>
<P>
   They were then sentenced to death, the only punishment allowable
for murder. However, no convicted killer has been hanged in modern
Samoa, with sentences routinely commuted to life in prison by the
head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Former Women's Affairs Minister Leafa Vitale, 57, and
ex-Communications Minister Toi Aukuso, 68, were found guilty of
murdering Luagalau Levaula Kamu, who was shot in the back while
talking on a mobile telephone during a political gathering on July
16 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kamu was shot with an M-16 rifle by Vitale's son, Alatise, who
carried out the slaying for his father and Aukuso.
</P>
<P>
   After admitting to the assassination last year, Alatise Vitale
was sentenced to death, but his punishment was later reduced to
life imprisonment. During the trial he first testified that his
father knew nothing of the killing and then admitted he had ordered
it.
</P>
<P>
   The faces of the two accused were impassive while the findings
were read Wednesday, but Aukuso clutched tighter at the handrail of
the defendants' box, and a stunned silence fell over the Samoan
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Their trial, which began Jan. 17 and heard testimony from 65
witnesses, put government corruption in Apia under the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   A popular figure, Kamu was part of a new wave of young
politicians seeking to clean up political life. His killing was
seen as an attempt to prevent publication of reports on corruption
believed to implicate former ministers and legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also alleged the former ministers had Kamu killed
out of jealousy because he had been appointed to the Public Works
Cabinet post, a position whose holder has been known to be offered
bribes from local companies competing for government-funded
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Vitale denied ordering the hit and described Kamu as a ''very
good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But Aukuso told the court Vitale had asked him to shoot Kamu and
Prime Minister Tuilaepa Sailele Malielegaoi last year. Aukuso said
he refused to carry out the killings after Vitale failed to pay him
the agreed fee.
</P>
<P>
   The murder was Samoa's first political killing since the former
German and New Zealand territory gained independence 38 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as Western Samoa, the island chain has a population
of about 164,000. The United States territory of American Samoa
comprises several islands in the same island group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2236 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000413.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Figg-Currier, Hetherington Lead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Calif. (AP) -- Taking advantage of agreeable morning
conditions, Cindy Figg-Currier and Rachel Hetherington shot
6-under-par 66s Thursday and were tied for the first-round lead at
the LPGA Longs Drugs Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Figg-Currier, who was also tied for the first-round lead a year
ago after shooting a 68, played in the first group off at the
6,388-yard Twelve Bridges Golf Club course.
</P>
<P>
   Following a par at No. 1, Figg-Currier birdied the next three
holes. She finished with seven birdies and a lone bogey on No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   A hard rain Wednesday evening made for ideal conditions the next
morning. The course absorbed the rain with little problem and
softened the greens, which are typically a source of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A tricky wind that gusted to 22 mph made the course tougher in
the afternoon on a day when 21 golfers shot below par, most of them
with morning tee times.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best part about the morning was there wasn't any rain,''
Figg-Currier said. ''I woke up at one in the morning and I heard
the rain coming down. I was worried about playing in a downpour.
When I saw that blue sky I was shocked. We got a real break.''
</P>
<P>
   Teeing off about two hours later, Hetherington also birdied Nos.
2 through 4. The Australian-born Hetherington caught Figg-Currier
with the last of six birdies at No. 16, making an eight-foot putt.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been wet here in the past and I can remember hitting
3-woods into some of the par-4s,'' Hetherington said. ''This course
seems to get better every year. The fairways are terrific and so
are the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   One shot behind the leaders was Michelle Bell, who had to take
the last three years off due to a serious problem with her immune
system. In the first morning group off the back nine, Bell had six
birdies. Her only bogey came when she landed in the lip of a bunker
on No. 16 and two-putted.
</P>
<P>
   ''The course played a lot longer than it did in the pro-am and
practice rounds,'' Bell said. ''The advantage was that the greens
held. You could really fire at the pins.''
</P>
<P>
   In a group at 69 were Brandie Burton, Jill McGill, Cristie Kerr,
Mhairi McKay and Carin Koch, who finished second in the 1998 Longs
Drugs Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Juli Inkster and Se Ri Pak both shot 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam rallied after playing the front side one over.
She recorded her first birdie at No. 10 and rolled in a 25-foot
putt on the par-5 12th for an eagle. She finished with a 71.
</P>
<P>
Divots: Sorenstam and her caddy had to chase a turkey off the 10th
green prior to a long birdie putt. ''It was a lucky turkey, I wish
I hadn't scared it away,'' she said. ... Colleen Walker injured her
hand and dropped out of the tournament after playing eight holes.
... Two Hall of Fame golfers struggled. Pat Bradley had a 76 and
Patty Sheehan shot a 77.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
