<HEADLINE> Lebanon Marks Civil War Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanon on Thursday marked the 25th
anniversary of a civil war that killed 150,000 people, amid
concerns about fighting after Israel withdraws its troops from the
south of the country this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 people carried white roses as a symbol of peace in a
demonstration outside parliament in downtown Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ''The war is a thing of the past. It will never return,'' former
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri told the crowd, which included several
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The war broke out April 13, 1975 when right-wing Christian
Phalange militiamen ambushed a bus carrying Palestinians in the
Christian suburb of Ein el-Rummaneh, killing 26.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ''bus incident'' quickly plunged the entire
country in a bloody sectarian conflict that lasted 15 years and
caused, according to U.N. estimates, $25 billion worth of
destruction. The war also displaced about half a million people,
many of whom are still waiting for government funds to return to
their home areas.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers marked the anniversary by publishing pictures of the
bullet-riddled bus as a reminder of the incident that has badly
shaken Muslim-Christian coexistence. ''So We Won't Forget,'' said a
headline in the leftist As-Safir newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''Among the factors that prevent a renewal of the war is the
consciousness of the people who have drawn lessons from the war,''
Samir Franjieh, a Christian intellectual said in comments published
by As-Safir.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers published pictures and television stations played
videotapes showing scenes of high-rise buildings going up in flames
as rival Christian and Muslim militias battled with rockets, mortar
shells and machine guns in streets and residential areas on both
sides of Beirut. The fierce fighting left Beirut, a major hub for
tourism, banking and commerce, in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown area, devastated by fighting, is being rebuilt
under a multibillion dollar reconstruction plan.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-based Human Rights Watch Thursday called on the
Lebanese government to allocate adequate time and resources to
effectively investigate the cases of the missing.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the civil war ended with a Christian-Muslim
political power-sharing agreement, the armed militias have been
dismantled but the sectarian divisions remain.
</P>
<P>
   While the conflict ended across the country, violence continued
in southern Lebanon, where Israel occupies a strip of territory
with the aim of protecting its own border from guerrilla attacks.
Israel has promised to withdraw its army by July but there are
fears in Lebanon that a pullout without an overall peace agreement
involving Lebanon, Syria and Israel could plunge that region in
fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2242 </TRAILER>
