<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bengals' Ki-Jana Carter Injured  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Ki-Jana Carter, the Cincinnati running back
who has missed almost half of his NFL career with injuries since
the Bengals selected him first overall in 1995, reinjured the knee
that sidelined him last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before rumors get too far out of hand, let me clear things
up,'' Carter said Thursday on his Web site, which is maintained by
California-based Broadband Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, I injured my knee. But it's certainly not career- or
season-ending like people are saying,'' Carter said. ''I was just
working out, doing some jumping drills, and my kneecap popped out
and then popped back in. I felt numbness throughout my whole leg
and I knew right away what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can walk, but my knee is swollen.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, 26, told the Bengals the injury occurred Tuesday night
near his home in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. He was examined Thursday in
Miami by Dr. James Andrews, an orthopedic surgeon from Birmingham,
Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals trainer Paul Sparling said the exam revealed a partially
dislocated kneecap. Carter dislocated the same kneecap in the third
game last season and missed the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he would have arthroscopic surgery on Tuesday and
would miss the Bengals' minicamp but would be ready to play this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''The procedure involves heat shrinkage of the connective tissue
around the kneecap,'' Sparling said. ''The goal is to shrink the
connective tissue so the kneecap does not (dislocate) again.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no guarantee it will be successful, but it gives
Ki-Jana his best chance of being able to play next season. The only
other options are a reconstruction of the knee, which would put him
out for the season, or to rehab without surgery, which leaves the
very real possibility that the injury would occur again.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Penn State star, originally from Westerville, Ohio,
is entering his sixth NFL season. His status could be especially
critical to the Bengals because Corey Dillon, who has rushed for
1,000 yards each of the past three seasons, says he feels
unappreciated and wants to play for another team.
</P>
<P>
   Carter missed his entire rookie season in 1995 with a torn
ligament in his left knee. He played only one game in 1998 because
of a severe wrist fracture. His season ended last year on Sept. 26
at Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ''Granted, things haven't been that fair to me on the playing
field so far, but neither my season nor my career is at all over,''
Carter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2248 </TRAILER>
