<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressGiorgio Bassani:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Author Giorgio Bassani, best known for his
semi-autobiographical novel ''The Garden of the Finzi-Continis''
and its elegiac depiction of Italian Jews during the rise of
Fascism, died Thursday of Parkinson's and Alzheimer's diseases. He
was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Bassani lived much of his life in the provincial town of
Ferrara, and its Jewish life was the wellspring for most of his
literary works.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Garden of the Finzi-Continis,'' published in 1962,
portrays an aristocratic Jewish family whose beautiful estate
serves as a haven -- though a temporary, illusory one -- against a
menacing world. Amid harsh anti-Semitic edicts by dictator Benito
Mussolini that set the stage for the deportation and persecution of
Italy's Jews, the characters live a cloistered and romantic life.
</P>
<P>
   The novel was made into a film by director Vittorio De Sica that
won the Academy Award for best foreign film in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Bassani had been jailed by the Fascists during the war.
</P>
<P>
   He won Italy's prestigious Strega literary award in 1956 for
''Five Stories about Ferrara.''
Earl English:
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- Earl English, who was dean of the
University of Missouri School of Journalism from 1951 to 1970, died
Tuesday. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   The school's graduate studies center was named after English in
September.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, English led an effort by the American Council on
Education for Journalism to accredit journalism schools. He also
was instrumental in raising money for the Freedom of Information
Center, a research and reference library on First Amendment issues.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Ceola, two daughters, a sister, and
four grandchildren.
Ken Peterson:
</P>
<P>
   SANTA FE (AP) -- Ken Peterson, who worked as a artist on Walt
Disney's ''Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' died March 29 of
cancer. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief attempt at making his own animated motion
pictures, Peterson joined the army of young artists Disney hired in
1936 for ''Snow White,'' the first feature-length animated film.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson headed the art department for many animated films,
including ''Alice in Wonderland,'' ''Lady and the Tramp'' and
''Sleeping Beauty.''
Bob Phillips:
</P>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Bob Phillips, the first assistant Joe
Paterno hired after becoming Penn State's head coach in 1966, died
Wednesday. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips retired as an assistant after the Nittany Lions'
national championship season in 1986. He continued as a volunteer
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips coached the backfield when John Cappelletti won the
1973 Heisman Trophy. He also coached tight ends, receivers, punters
and quarterbacks -- among them Todd Blackledge, who led Penn State
to its first national title in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was named to the Pennsylvania Football Coaches Hall of
Fame in 1993.
Bob Tamarkin:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Bob Tamarkin, a former Chicago Daily News writer
who covered the Vietnam War and later the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, died Tuesday. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   As the Vietnam War ended and Americans were fleeing, Tamarkin
stayed in Saigon to document the chaotic evacuation of the American
Embassy, leaving on the last helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the United States, he became an expert on
the Mercantile Exchange, making it the subject of three of his
seven books.
</P>
<P>
   Tamarkin also was Midwest bureau chief for Forbes magazine and a
writer for the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Civia; a son and three daughters; a
sister and five grandchildren.
Francis L. Zrostlik:
</P>
<P>
   MASON CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Francis L. Zrostlik, who founded tire
service and tool businesses, died Wednesday of cancer. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, he started Iowa Mold Tooling in his garage. Based in
Garner, the company expanded into mobile air compressor systems,
tire service trucks and materials handling equipment. By 1971, the
company was exporting vehicles to construction, mining, railroad
and utility industries around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The company had grown to $40 million in sales by 1985 when
Zrostlik sold it. He retired three years later, but in 1990 started
Stellar Industries, which also makes tire service trucks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Zrostlik won the Entrepreneurial Spirit Award sponsored
by Ernst &AMP; Young, USA Today, NASDAQ, the Kauffman Foundation and
the Entrepreneur of the Year Institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
