<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Reaches Deal on Africa Bill  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate leaders broke a long logjam
over Africa trade legislation Thursday night, tentatively agreeing
to compromise legislation that would give new trade benefits to
Africa, Central America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which had passed both chambers but in significantly
different forms, has been subject to intense negotiations since
last November.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative deal, which still must be approved formally by
negotiators from each chamber, was hammered out in a private
meeting among top House and Senate leaders, including Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., and trade leaders from both chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The speaker believes this is a good deal for the American
consumer,'' said John Feehery, a spokesman for Hastert. He said the
speaker hoped the compromise measure could be brought up after
Congress returns from its spring recess.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the deal were sketchy, but those close to the
negotiations said House leaders agreed to accept a more expansive
Senate version in terms of countries covered.
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed bill only dealt with the 48 countries of
sub-Saharan Africa. The Senate bill -- and now the compromise --
covers these nations, plus 24 Caribbean-Central American nations as
well.
</P>
<P>
   In another compromise, House leaders agreed to go along with
some restrictions on the volume of goods to receive duty-free
treatment while Senate leaders agreed to lower restrictions than in
the original Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the House bill would have given items of clothing
and other textile products from the covered countries duty-free
access to U.S. markets, while the Senate bill would have limited
duty-free imports to 1{ percent of all similar U.S. imports, rising
to 3 percent over six years.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise would allow duty-free imports to rise from 1{
percent to 3{ percent of all U.S. imports over six years, according
to congressional officials who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders, meanwhile, said they would drop a Senate-passed
requirement that African-assembled apparel use U.S. fabric and
thread, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the poorest countries in Africa would be eligible
for duty-free treatment in U.S. markets with no restrictions for
four years, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts manufactured in Caribbean and Central American
countries would be subject to some restrictions not applied to
other apparel, however, in a nod to U.S. textile manufacturers, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative agreement had the support of key Democrats,
including Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Rep. Charles Rangel,
both of New York. Moynihan is the senior Democrat on the Senate
Finance Committee and Rangel the senior Democrat on the House Ways
and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good tentative agreement. Congressman Rangel was
confident that what was outlined will pass both houses,'' said
Rangel spokesman Dan Maffei.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, it will be the first major trade bill approved since
1994, when Congress agreed to U.S. participation in the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made the Africa bill a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   However, administration officials and congressional leaders
hoped to be able to deal with the measure before taking up an even
more contentious trade bill later in the spring, extending
permanent trade benefits to China to help ease the way for China's
entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would lower or eliminate tariffs and quotas on
products from the regions covered as well as making it easier for
American businesses to invest.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has been opposed by senators from textile
states, who contended it would harm America's garment industry, and
by labor and environmental groups that said it failed to set
standards for protecting workers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 434.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2317 </TRAILER>
