<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bolivian Congress Upholds Decree  </HEADLINE>
By PETER McFARREN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- Government negotiators reached agreement
Thursday with protesting farmers to lift remaining barricades in
exchange for the freedom of activists being held in a remote
Bolivian town.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Walter Guiteras said Thursday the deal had
been struck with Pedro Vilca, one of the leaders of the National
Farmers Confederation, to end nationwide protests after the
government releases the detainees -- including the group's top
leadership -- being held in the town of San Joaquin.
</P>
<P>
   Guiteras said he expected the release to occur sometime Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is one more step in calming eight days of
protests, roadblocks and violent confrontations that led Bolivia on
Saturday to suspend constitutional guarantees. On Thursday,
Bolivia's Congress upheld the decree.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ''state of siege'' order declared Saturday by
President Hugo Banzer, police can detain people without a warrant,
restrict travel and political activity and establish curfews.
Congress authorized the measure after a heated all-night session,
with opposition legislators condemning the government's repression
of protests.
</P>
<P>
   Banzer, a retired general and former dictator turned democrat,
said the measure was necessary because the protests were
threatening government stability.
</P>
<P>
   The decree is in force for 90 days. If Congress had rejected it,
the state of siege would have ended immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere Thursday, shops, businesses and schools reopened in
Cochabamba, the city where the protests first broke out, while a
nationwide strike to protest the state of siege fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   La Paz was calm Thursday after several hundred students clashed
with police for several hours on Wednesday. Some two thousands
buses and trucks that had been stranded around the country by
peasant-erected roadblocks began moving Wednesday. Only scattered
roadblocks remained in areas near La Paz.
</P>
<P>
   The government admitted that while the water rate hike sparked
the protests, the dire economy made them grow and spread.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economic crisis Bolivia and the region has been going
through no doubt contributed to the problems here,'' Information
Minister Ronald MacLean told The Associated Press. ''When a crisis
hits us we do not have a cushion to absorb its impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide protests eased after the government reached
agreement with organizers late Monday to reject the water rate
hikes. Under the agreement, the government canceled a contract for
a water expansion project and revised a water law to end fees for
rural well water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
