<HEADLINE> Clinton To Address Indian Concerns  </HEADLINE>
CLAUDE R. MARX
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton promised Thursday night to
use the rest of his time in office and his post-presidential years
to do even more to improve the lives of American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   He told Indian donors to the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee that starting next year -- when ''I have more time to work
on fewer things'' -- he would undertake projects relating to
economic development, health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the New Market Initiative, which would encourage
investment in economically struggling areas, was an important part
of his efforts to achieve these goals.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is currently pending before several congressional
committees. House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has endorsed
key provisions of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe in the potential of all people. I believe that
intelligence is equally apportioned among all races, but
opportunity isn't,'' Clinton told guests at a $10,000-a-person
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again apologized for earlier government policies that
hurt Indians and caused the government to ''run from our own
responsibility'' to improve their health and welfare.
</P>
<P>
   In a later speech to another committee fund-raiser, he said
Congress should use ''this magic moment of possibility'' to ensure
that the current economic recovery continues.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated his concern that Republican proposed tax cuts
would cause a return to era of big deficits. He said ''sensible''
cuts, combined with plans to protect Medicare and Social Security
would keep the current recovery going.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
