<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Group Accepts Donation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A group raising money to build a new library at
Columbine High School said Thursday it will accept a stock donation
from a strip club owner that could be worth several hundred
thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Club owner Troy Lowrie had offered Healing of People Everywhere
600,000 shares of stock in an outdoor advertising company earlier
this month. HOPE didn't immediately accept.
</P>
<P>
   But members decided at a meeting this week to accept Lowrie's
donation toward the $3.1 million needed to tear down the old
library at Columbine and to build a new library and atrium.
</P>
<P>
   The library was the scene of the worst damage last April 20 when
two teen-agers shot and killed 12 students and a teacher before
killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   HOPE said it would accept the gift because Lowrie offered it
''from the heart.'' In a written statement, HOPE said it would not
block anyone who wants to help Columbine heal.
</P>
<P>
   Lowrie, 35, owns PT's, PT's Gold and All Stars clubs in
metropolitan Denver and seven strip clubs in other states. He
agreed to donate the stock at the request of Angela Sanders, 23, a
dancer at PT's Gold whose father, Dave Sanders, was the teacher
killed at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   The stock is from New Millennium Media International Inc., a
Florida outdoor advertising company in which Lowrie has a 9 percent
interest. The value of the donation depends on the stock price when
it is sold.
</P>
<P>
   When Lowrie made the offer earlier this month, he said he hoped
his business dealings would not stop the group from accepting.
</P>
<P>
   ''This money is from a media company that is not related to the
adult industry. I hope they wouldn't turn it down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not immediately return a phone call Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
