<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eleven Charged for Staging Crashes  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK BARTELS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Eleven people were charged Thursday
with staging car crashes to collect insurance money, including some
suspects who used their children to help fake the crashes, state
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Children as young as 7 years old were used as passengers and
trained to act injured after the crashes, said Clay Simpson, a
staff attorney for the state Insurance Department.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, four members of the ring staged crashes in
which they caused accidents that made it look as if the other
driver was at fault, Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   The supposed ''victims'' would then settle with insurance
companies, Simpson said. Having a child or two in the crashes added
credibility that would help convince the companies that the
collisions were genuine accidents.
</P>
<P>
   But one suspect added a little realism, Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the suspects physically struck one of the small
children in the head so he would have an injury ... and be able to
go to the hospital,'' Simpson said.
</P>
<P>
   An undercover Fort Smith police officer infiltrated the ring,
and Simpson said investigators, aided by the FBI, recorded audio
and video tape of the suspects bragging about collecting insurance
money.
</P>
<P>
   They face a variety of charges, including insurance fraud, theft
by deception and endangering the welfare of a minor, according to
the Insurance Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
