<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-13 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Cable Operators Talk Merger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Jupiter Telecommunications Co., Japan's largest
cable-TV operator, is in talks with Titus Communications Corp., a
Japanese subsidiary of Microsoft Corp., about a possible merger,
both companies said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nihon Keizai Shimbun reported Friday that Jupiter and Titus
plan to merge around July. They would have a combined subscriber
base of 660,000 subscribers across Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Keiko Morita, spokeswoman for Tokyo-based Jupiter, said talks
are under way between the two companies. ''But nothing has been
decided,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Titus spokesman Yoichi Hiraoka confirmed talks were continuing
but refused to give details.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jupiter and Titus now offer broadcasting and flat-rate,
high-speed Internet access and telephone services in major cities
across Japan.
</P>
<P>
   If combined, the new company would challenge the domination of
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. in communication services in
Japan, the Nihon Keizai report said.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter is owned 60 percent by Sumitomo Corp., a major Japanese
trading company. The remaining 40 percent interest is owned by
Liberty Media Corp., a subsidiary of AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, U.S. computer software giant Microsoft
acquired a 60 percent stake in Titus. Titus is 20 percent owned by
Itochu Corp., a major trading company, and another 20 percent by
electronics maker Toshiba Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-13-00 2353 </TRAILER>
